1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. c4 Bg7 4. Nc3 O-O 5. g3 c5 {*} 6. d5 d6 7. Bg2 e6 8. O-O exd5 9. cxd5 a6 {Efstratios Grivas: 'This is my basic suggestion. '} 10. a4 Re8 11. Bf4 Qc7 12. Nd2 Nbd7 13. Nc4 $2 Bf8 14. e4 ({(} 14. Qb3 b6 $1 {).} {or} 15. Bf3 Rb8 16. Rfd1 Bb7 $3 17. e4 Bc8 18. Re1 Ne5 19. Bxe5 dxe5 20. Bg2 Bd7 21. Na3 Rb7 22. Bf1 Ra8 23. Qc2 Ne8 {Efstratios Grivas: 'Black takes advantage of the placement of the e4-bishop, gaining important central space. Possible also is'} 24. Bd3 Nd6 25. Qe2) (14. Qd2 b6 15. e4 Rb8 {Augustin,J-Tal,M/Moscow 1977.} 16. Qc2 $5 b5 17. axb5 axb5 18. Na5 b4 19. Ne2 Ba6 20. Rfc1 Nxd5) (14. h3 Rb8 15. Na3 Ne5 16. Bg5 Bg7 17. f4 $13 {.} Ned7 {transposes to the lines above.} 18. e4 $1 h6 19. Bh4 c4 {Efstratios Grivas: 'transposes to the lines above.'} 20. Qc2 Qc5+ 21. Kh2 b5 22. axb5 axb5 23. g4 Ba6 24. Nxc4 $11 Qxc4 25. Rxa6 Nxe4) 14... Nh5 15. Be3 Ne5 $1 $146 {Efstratios Grivas: '!'} (15... b6 16. h3 Rb8 17. Qd2 Ne5 18. Nxe5 $15 {Marschner,J-Klundt,K/Germany 1989.} {After} dxe5 19. Ne2 $1 Bd6 20. f4 $1 f6 21. f5 $1 {Black is much better}) 16. Nxe5 Rxe5 17. f4 $2 Re8 18. Bf3 Nf6 $1 {Efstratios Grivas: 'Black's advantage is considerable. The doubled d-pawns control important central squares, in sharp contrast to the white doubled f-pawns that don't contribute much. Moreover, the presence of the b-pawns favours Black as the white pawn on b5 is easier to get at and thus weaker than the black one on b7. Finally, the c1-bishop is only apparently a better piece than the g7-bishop (due to the presence of the d4-pawn); a more careful examination reveals that the c1-bishop does not have a satisfactory square to move to as it must keep a3 and c3 under control, preventing an invasion by the black rook. '} 19. Re1 Bd7 $17 {Efstratios Grivas: '!' Efstratios Grivas: 'Black cannot expect anything special from using the e-file; in fact, White could in that case proceed with relieving exchanges. '} 20. a5 b5 21. axb6 Qxb6 $1 {Opening another front, as the threatened ...h4-h3 can only be met by a further weakening of the white pawn-structure.} 22. Qd2 Ng4 $1 {Threatening an invasion by 23...c3.} 23. Bxg4 Bxg4 $1 {All of Black's pieces are optimally placed, maximizing the dynamic potential in his position. On e8, the queen controls the e-file while also eyeing the b-pawn, while the c8-rook is ready to penetrate White's ranks.} 24. b4 Bg7 25. bxc5 $2 Qb4 $1 {The threat of 26...c2! forces White to retreat.} 26. e5 Rab8 27. Reb1 Qc4 28. cxd6 f6 $1 {The resulting rook ending is won for Black as the passed d-pawns are very powerful and the black king will quickly be centralized.} 29. Qd4 Rxb1+ 30. Rxb1 Qxd4 31. Bxd4 fxe5 32. fxe5 Bxe5 $1 {Black returns his "optical" material advantage. The white f4-pawn is hardly a worthy opponent for the black passed d-pawn as it is doubled and devoid of prospects. In effect, Black has an extra pawn.} 33. Bxe5 Rxe5 34. Rb7 Re3 $1 {Preventing any counterplay involving a future sacrifice with f5.} 35. Na4 Rf3 36. Kg2 Rf7 {0-1 (36) Dedes,N (2310)-Grivas,E (2465) Iraklion 1992 CBM 121 [Efstratios Grivas] The ending is easily won as Black enjoys several advantages: centralized king, passed extra pawn, more active rook.} {A mistake in time trouble. White ought to remain passive with} 37. Rc7 {when his position is unpleasant, but Black would have to work to prove his superiority} {(} Kf8 $5 {, intending ...f5 or ...c2,} {or} 38. Nb6 $5 {intending ...h6).} {White is running out of satisfactory moves, as neither} Ke8 39. h3 $1 {nor} Bf3+ 40. Kg1 $1 {is of much help. Now, the threat of 21.e7! with counterplay against the b7-pawn forces Black's hand.} {Efstratios Grivas: 'Practically 'forced', as after any other retreat of the e4-bishop the white e2-pawn would come under unbearable pressure (...a2 and ...e8). An example is'} Rf6 $15 {×d5} 41. Rc8+ Kf7 42. d7 *


