1. d4 {Efstratios Grivas} Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Bf4 Bg7 5. e3 O-O 6. Be2 Bg4 7. h3 Bxf3 8. Bxf3 c6 9. O-O Nbd7 {This is my basic suggestion.} 10. e4 dxe4 11. Nxe4 Nxe4 12. Bxe4 e5 13. dxe5 Nxe5 14. c3 (14. Qe2 Re8 15. c3 Qf6 16. Bg3 Nd7) 14... Qxd1 ({White is running out of satisfactory moves, as neither} 14... Qh4 15. Qc1 $1 {nor} Rad8 16. Bc2 $1 {is of much help. Now, the threat of 21.e7! with counterplay against the b7-pawn forces Black's hand.} {Practically 'forced', as after any other retreat of the e4-bishop the white e2-pawn would come under unbearable pressure (...a2 and ...e8). An example is} Nd3 17. Bxd3 Rxd3) 15. Raxd1 Rad8 $1 16. Bc2 (16. Bg5 f6 17. Bf4 Rfe8 {The ending is easily won as Black enjoys several advantages: centralized king, passed extra pawn, more active rook.} {A mistake in time trouble. White ought to remain passive with} 18. Bc2 {when his position is unpleasant, but Black would have to work to prove his superiority} {(} Bf8 $5 {, intending ...f5 or ...c2,} {or} 19. Rfe1 $5 {intending ...h6).}) 16... Bf6 17. Bxe5 (17. Bh6 Rfe8 18. Rfe1 Rxd1 $1 {Black returns his "optical" material advantage. The white f4-pawn is hardly a worthy opponent for the black passed d-pawn as it is doubled and devoid of prospects. In effect, Black has an extra pawn.} 19. Rxd1 Rd8 20. Rxd8+ Bxd8 $1 {Preventing any counterplay involving a future sacrifice with f5.}) 17... Bxe5 18. Rxd8 Rxd8 {Black's advantage is considerable. The doubled d-pawns control important central squares, in sharp contrast to the white doubled f-pawns that don't contribute much. Moreover, the presence of the b-pawns favours Black as the white pawn on b5 is easier to get at and thus weaker than the black one on b7. Finally, the c1-bishop is only apparently a better piece than the g7-bishop (due to the presence of the d4-pawn); a more careful examination reveals that the c1-bishop does not have a satisfactory square to move to as it must keep a3 and c3 under control, preventing an invasion by the black rook.} 19. Rd1 Rxd1+ $1 {Black cannot expect anything special from using the e-file; in fact, White could in that case proceed with relieving exchanges.} 20. Bxd1 Kf8 21. Kf1 Ke7 $1 {Opening another front, as the threatened ...h4-h3 can only be met by a further weakening of the white pawn-structure.} 22. Ke2 Bc7 $1 {Threatening an invasion by 23...c3.} 23. Kd3 Bb6 $1 {All of Black's pieces are optimally placed, maximizing the dynamic potential in his position. On e8, the queen controls the e-file while also eyeing the b-pawn, while the c8-rook is ready to penetrate White's ranks.} 24. f3 Bc7 25. a4 $2 a5 $1 {The threat of 26...c2! forces White to retreat.} 26. Bb3 f5 27. Bc4 h6 28. b4 Kf6 $1 {The resulting rook ending is won for Black as the passed d-pawns are very powerful and the black king will quickly be centralized.} 29. b5 cxb5 30. Bxb5 Bd6 0-1


