1. c4 {Mikhalevski,Victor Mikhalevski,Victor Mikhalevski,Victor Hecht Mikhalevski,Victor: 'Mikhalevski,V Mikhalevski,V Hecht'} Nf6 2. Nc3 d5 3. cxd5 Nxd5 4. Nf3 g6 5. e4 Nxc3 6. dxc3 (6. bxc3 {after} Bg7 7. d4 {leads to Gruenfeld defence.}) 6... Qxd1+ ({Bad is} 6... Nd7 7. Bc4 Bg7 $2 {because of} 8. Bxf7+ $1 {winning a queen}) 7. Kxd1 Bg4 8. Bf4 (8. Be2 Nd7 (8... Nc6 { 9...0-0-0}) 9. Be3 e5 10. Nd2 {½-½ Petrosian,T-Botvinnik,M/Moscow 1963/MainBase/[Bulletin] (10)} (10. h3 Bxf3 11. Bxf3 Bc5 $10)) 8... c6 9. Bc4 ({White also tried} 9. Kc2 Nd7 10. Nd2 e5 11. Bg3 f6 12. Bc4 Nb6 13. Bb3 Bc5 14. a4 a5 15. h3 Bd7 16. f4 exf4 17. Bxf4 Ke7 18. Rae1 Rhe8 19. g4 Be6 20. e5 Nd7 $2 21. exf6+ Kxf6 22. Bxe6 Rxe6 23. Bg5+ $1 $18 {1-0 Sambuev,B-Turov,M/St Petersburg RUS 1998 (37)}) 9... Nd7 10. Kc2 Bxf3 11. gxf3 e5 12. Bg3 $5 $146 {In the previous games White tried other retreats:} (12. Bd2 Bd6 13. Rad1 Ke7 14. Be3 f6 15. Rd2 Rhd8 16. Rhd1 Bc7 17. Bg8 Bb6 18. Bxh7 Nf8 19. Rxd8 Rxd8 20. Rxd8 Kxd8 21. Bg8 g5 22. Bf7 Ke7 23. Bh5 Kd6 24. Bg4 Ng6 25. a4 Nf4 26. b4 Ng2 $11 {Krivonosov,O-Moberg,K/Oerebro 1995/EXT 98/½-½ (39)}) (12. Be3 Bc5 13. Bh6 Bxf2 (13... Bf8 14. Bd2 h5 15. Rad1 Nb6 16. Bb3 Bh6 17. Bxh6 Rxh6 18. h4 Rh7 19. Kd3 a5 20. a3 Nd7 21. Ke3 Nc5 22. Ba2 Ke7 23. f4 exf4+ 24. Kxf4 Rhh8 25. Rd4 Rhd8 26. Rhd1 Rxd4 27. cxd4 Rd8 28. Ke3 {Vaganian,R-Lerner,K/Odessa 1989/URS-ch/1-0 (42)}) 14. Rad1 Rd8 15. Rhf1 Bc5 16. f4 Bf8 17. Bg5 Be7 18. Bh6 Rg8 19. Rxd7 Rxd7 20. fxe5 Bf8 21. e6 fxe6 22. Bxe6 Bxh6 23. Bxg8 Bg5 24. Rf2 Rg7 25. Bc4 Re7 26. Kd3 {½-½ Sufiev,R-Turov,M/Pardubice 1997/CBM 59 ext (26)}) 12... h5 13. h4 Bh6 14. Rad1 {[%csl Rd7][%cal Gc4f7]} Rf8 {Probably first inaccuracy.Black gives away the d6-square in the full White's possession that brings first problems very soon.} (14... Rh7 $5 {is interesting in order to meet} 15. Rd6 {with} Bf8) 15. Rd6 Rc8 $6 {One inaccuracy pulls another and finally White can take the initiative.} ({Better was} 15... O-O-O $5 16. Rhd1 Kc7 {keeping the position.}) 16. Rhd1 Rc7 17. Bf1 $1 {[%csl Re5][%cal Gf1h3][%mdl 32] Perhaps Black had missed this srong manoeuvre.Otherwise he would probably play 15...0-0-0.} Bf4 $2 {This is already bad as the pawn on f4 will be lost in few moves.} (17... f6 {was the only defence and despite White is better anyway he has to find a way how to prove his superiority.} 18. Re6+ Kd8 (18... Kf7 $2 19. Bc4 $1 $18) 19. Bh3 Rf7 20. a4 $14 {with reliable,but a bit passive position for Black.}) 18. Bh3 Nb6 19. Bxf4 exf4 20. b3 $1 {[%csl Rf4] White restricts mobility of black knight while the pawn on f4 has to wait for its fate.} Ke7 21. c4 {[%cal Gc4c5] Creating another unpleasant threat of c5 following by d7.} Nd5 ({Not better is} 21... c5 22. a4 $1 {[%cal Ga4a5]}) 22. e5 $16 {White is already obtaining clear positional advantage.} Nb6 (22... Nb4+ {was slightly better} 23. Kb1 $1 c5 {[%cal Gb4c6]} 24. Rd7+ Rxd7 25. Rxd7+ Ke8 26. Rxb7 Nd3 27. Rxa7 Nxe5 28. Bg2 $16) 23. R1d4 $6 {winning a pawn Grivas transfers the game into the technical position where white's chances to win seems to be much higher than black's to keep the position.But look what happens.} (23. Kd3 $1 {[%cal Gd3e4] was stronger} f5 $1 {The only sensible defence.} 24. Rxg6 Rd7+ 25. Ke2 Rxd1 26. Kxd1 Nd7 {The point of 23...f5} 27. Rg7+ $1 Ke6 28. Ke2 $16 {[%csl Ra7,Rb7,Rf4,Rf5,Rh5] and Black is lack of moves.}) 23... c5 24. Rxf4 Nd7 25. Bxd7 Rxd7 26. Rxd7+ Kxd7 27. Rf6 {[%cal Gf3f4,Gf4f5][%mdl 4096] White is a pawn up and prepares decisive advance f3-f4-f5.} Ke7 28. f4 (28. Rd6 {preventing possible counterplay is met by} f6 $1 29. Rxf6 Rxf6 30. exf6+ Kxf6 31. Kd3 Ke5 $1 32. Ke3 Kf5 {with most likely draw.}) 28... Rd8 {looking for counterplay along the d-file.} 29. f5 gxf5 $1 {Only chance.} ({In case of} 29... Rd4 30. fxg6 fxg6 31. Rxg6 Rxh4 32. Kd3 $1 {two united pass pawns in the centre are decisive.}) 30. Rxf5 Rd4 31. f4 Ke6 32. Rf6+ Ke7 33. Kc3 Rd1 {Again the only defence as pawn moves on the queen side would make the situation even more unpleasant.} 34. Rf5 Rf1 ({Worse is} 34... Rd4 35. b4 {creating additional weaknesses.}) 35. Kd3 Ke6 36. Rf6+ Ke7 37. Rf5 Ke6 38. Rf6+ Ke7 39. Ke4 Rh1 {Precise defence gives its fruits.Black wins back a pawn.However White is still better thanks to the strong lump in the centre.} 40. Rh6 Rxh4 41. Rh8 Rh2 42. Rb8 Rxa2 ({Or} 42... b6 43. Rb7+ Kf8 44. Rxa7 h4 45. Kf3 {and White wins.}) 43. Rxb7+ Kf8 44. Kf5 {[%cal Gf5f6]} Rg2 $8 45. Rxa7 h4 (45... Rg3 $5) 46. Ra1 (46. e6 {is not sufficient for a win as Black save his skin with the aid of beautiful defence:} fxe6+ 47. Kf6 Kg8 $1 (47... Ke8 48. Kxe6 Rg6+ 49. Kd5 Rh6 50. Kxc5 h3 51. Ra1 h2 52. Rh1 {and White probably wins.}) 48. Rc7 h3 49. Rxc5 Rg7 $1 {[%cal Gh3h2]} 50. Rh5 Rf7+ $1 51. Kxe6 Rh7 52. Rg5+ Rg7 53. Rh5 Rh7 $11) 46... h3 47. Rh1 Rg3 48. Ke4 Kg7 49. f5 Rxb3 {Black is probably has good chances to escape.} 50. Rg1+ Kf8 51. Rg4 $1 {Only chance is to make white rook active.It has to be behind the black pass pawn.} Rb1 $1 {[%cal Gh3h2]} 52. Rh4 Rd1 $1 53. Rxh3 Rd4+ 54. Ke3 Rxc4 $11 {Finally Black gets theoretically drawish position.His pawn on c5 doesn't change much.The draw can be reached even without this pawn.} 55. Rh8+ Kg7 ({White wins beautifully after inaccurate} 55... Ke7 56. Rc8 Kd7 $2 57. e6+ $1 fxe6 58. f6 Rc3+ 59. Kf2 $1 (59. Ke4 Rc4+ 60. Ke5 Rc1 61. f7 $140 $4 Re1+ 62. Kf6 Rf1+) 59... Rc2+ 60. Kg3 Rc3+ 61. Kg4 Rc4+ 62. Kg5) 56. Rc8 Rc1 57. Rc7 Kg8 58. Kf4 {[%cal Gf4g5,Gg5f6]} Rg1 $1 {Black gives up his c-pawn as it's more important to prevent penetration of white king.} 59. Rxc5 {Hecht: ' Schwarz verteidigt sich lange erfolgreich in einer Stellung, die in der einschlägigen Literatur recht stiefmütterlich bedacht wird. Klar ist jedenfalls, dass die weißen Gewinnaussichten steigen, wenn die weißen Bauern, wie hier, bereits auf der 5. Reihe stehen. Die Stellungsbeurteilung liegt irgendwo zwischen klarem Vorteil und Gewinn. FRITZ6 zeigt zwar ständig Gewinn an, kommt aber nicht auf den Punkt. Für Hinweise zu diesem Endspiel wäre ich dankbar. Weiß gelingt es weder, seinen König nach f6 zu transportieren, noch den schwarzen König vom f-Bauern zu trennen. Letzteres kommt erst nach Aufgabe des Be5 zustande. Dort sehen wir dann weiter. '} ({In case of} 59. Rc8+ Kh7 (59... Kg7 60. f6+ Kh7 61. Rf8 Rf1+ 62. Ke4 Re1+ 63. Kd5 Rd1+ 64. Kxc5 Kg6 $11) 60. e6 fxe6 61. fxe6 Re1 62. Kf5 Kg7 $11 {the draw is simple.}) 59... Kg7 60. Rc7 Rf1+ 61. Ke4 Re1+ 62. Kd5 Rd1+ 63. Kc6 Kg8 (63... Rf1 $2 {loses to} 64. e6 Rxf5 65. e7 Re5 66. Kd7 Rd5+ 67. Kc8 Re5 68. Kd8 {winning} (68. Kd8 {Hecht} Kg6 69. e8=Q Rxe8+ 70. Kxe8 f5 71. Ke7 Kg5 72. Ke6 f4 73. Ke5 Kg4 74. Ke4 $18)) 64. Rd7 Rf1 (64... Re1 {Hecht} 65. Kd6 Kf8 66. Rd8+ Kg7 67. e6 fxe6 68. fxe6 Rd1+ 69. Ke7 Ra1 70. Ke8 Kf6 71. e7 Ra7 72. Rd6+ Kg7 73. Re6 {[%cal Re8d8]}) 65. f6 ({An attempt to win by means of} 65. Rd8+ Kg7 66. e6 Kf6 67. Rf8 Rxf5 (67... Rc1+ $2 68. Kd7 Rd1+ 69. Ke8 Kxf5 70. Kxf7 $18) 68. Kd6 $1 {also doesn't work:} Ra5 $1 {The only,but sufficient defence.} 69. Rxf7+ Kg6 70. Rf8 (70. Rc7 Kf6 $11) 70... Ra6+ $11 {with theoretical draw.}) (65. e6 fxe6 66. fxe6 Kf8) 65... Ra1 66. Rb7 Rd1 67. Rb5 Ra1 68. Rb7 Ra6+ 69. Rb6 Ra1 70. Kd6 Kh7 71. Rb2 Kg6 72. Rg2+ Kf5 73. Rf2+ Kg6 74. Rg2+ Kf5 75. Ke7 {The only attempt to fight for win.} Ra7+ 76. Kf8 Kxe5 77. Kg7 {Hecht: ' Dies ist die fragliche Stellung, in der Weiß unter Opfer des Be5 seine Königsstellung erheblich verbessert und den schwarzen König vom Bf7 getrennt hat. FRITZ6 kommt hier nach längerer Rechenzeit zum Resultat Remis. Deutlicher wird die Sache, wenn man in die Varianten geht. Ich gebe in meinen Anmerkungen auch schlechtere Verteidigungen an, komme aber beim Zug 84 zur Sache. '} Kf5 (77... Rb7 {Hecht} 78. Re2+ Kd6 $2 79. Kf8 {[%csl Rf7][%cal Re2e7]}) 78. Re2 Ra5 (78... Ra6 $5 79. Rf2+ Ke6) 79. Rb2 (79. Kxf7 Ra7+ 80. Re7 Ra6 {'=' Hecht.}) 79... Ra7 80. Rb5+ Ke6 81. Rb8 Kf5 82. Rb6 Rc7 83. Rb5+ Ke6 84. Rb1 Kf5 (84... Ra7 {Hecht} 85. Re1+ Kf5 86. Re7 Ra6 87. Rxf7 { Hier liegt eine Remisstellung vor, weil sich der weiße König aus seiner beengten Position nicht befreien kann, ohne den f-Bauern aufzugeben..} Kg5 $1 88. Rf8 Rd6 89. f7 Rg6+ 90. Kh7 Rh6+ $11) 85. Rf1+ Kg5 86. Re1 Kf5 87. Re7 Rc1 ({Mikhalevski,Victor: 'Mikhalevski,V: 'oder''} 87... Rc6 $5 {Mikhalevski,Victor: 'Mikhalevski,V: 'Hecht''} 88. Ra7 (88. Rxf7 Kg5 $11) 88... Ke6 89. Ra1 Rc7 90. Re1+ Kf5 91. Re7 Rc6 $11) ({oder} 87... Rc6 {Hecht}) 88. Ra7 {[%cal Gg7f7] Last trap.White creates the threat of :f7.Black's defence is very simple he has to prevent the only White's threat.} (88. Rxf7 Rg1+ 89. Kf8 Ra1 $11) (88. Kxf7 Rc6 $11) 88... Rh1 $4 {[%mdl 16384] '?' Hecht. Very pity mistake.Black is tired after a long defence and makes decisive mistake when draw was almost inevitable. Hecht: 'Das ist der einzige für mich klar erkennbare Fehler in diesem Endspiel, mit dem sich Naumann um den Lohn seiner zähen Verteidigung bringt. Schade!. '} (88... Rc6 {Mikhalevski,Victor: '=' '=' '=' Mikhalevski,Victor: 'Mikhalevski,V: '=' '=''} 89. Rxf7 (89. Ra1 Rc7 $11) (89. Ra5+ {Hecht} Ke6 90. Ra7 Kf5 $11) 89... Kg5 $11) (88... Ke6 $2 {Hecht} 89. Ra6+ Kf5 90. Kxf7 Rc7+ 91. Kg8 Kg6 92. f7+ $18 {mit Schach!}) 89. Ra5+ Ke6 90. Ra6+ Kf5 91. Kxf7 $18 {Now White wins easily as the pass pawn is unstopable. Hecht: 'Der König kann unter günstigen Umständen f7 nehmen. '} Rh7+ 92. Kg8 Rh6 93. Kg7 Rg6+ 94. Kf7 Kg5 95. Ke7 Kh6 96. Re6 1-0


