1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Be7 5. Bg5 O-O 6. e3 Nbd7 7. Bd3 dxc4 8. Bxc4 a6 9. a4 c5 10. O-O cxd4 11. exd4 Nb6 (11... Qc7 $6 12. Qe2 Bd6 13. Rac1 Re8 14. Bd3 Qb8 15. Rfe1 b6 16. Ne5 $16 {Grivas,E-Katsiris,I/Athens 1998.}) 12. Bb3 Nbd5 ({For} 12... Bd7 {see the analysed game Graf,A-Sulskis,S/Moscow 2001.}) ({The alternative} 12... Nfd5 {proves that White is benefiting by the insertion of ...a6 and a4 moves:} 13. Bxe7 Nxe7 14. Re1 $1 (14. Qe2 Nbd5 15. Rfd1 b6 16. Qe4 Bb7 17. Ng5 Ng6 18. Bxd5 Bxd5 19. Nxd5 Qxd5 20. Qxd5 exd5 21. Rac1 Rac8 $11 {Ravi,L-Valiente,C/Dubai 1986}) 14... Nbd5 15. Ne5 $16 {Kacheishvili,G-Hammes,M/Bad Wiessee 2001.}) 13. Re1 Nxc3 ({Alternatives fails (except d) to satisfy: a)} 13... Re8 14. Ne5 Nxc3 (14... Bd7 $2 15. Nxd5 Nxd5 16. Qf3 $1 Nf6 17. d5 exd5 18. Bxd5 {1-0 Bernal Moro,L-Acebal Muniz,A/Mondariz 2002}) 15. bxc3 Nd5 16. Bd2 Rf8 (16... Nf6 17. Re3 Bd7 18. Rh3 $16 {Hecht,H-Hicker,H/Schwarzach 2001}) 17. c4 Nf6 18. Bc3 $16 {Pillsbury,H-Schlechter,C/London 1899.}) ({b)} 13... Nb4 14. Ne5 Bd7 15. Qe2 Rc8 (15... b6 $2 16. d5 Bc8 17. Rad1 Qc7 18. dxe6 Bxe6 19. Bxe6 fxe6 20. Nd7 {1-0 Spassky,B-Lengyel,L/Tallinn 1975}) 16. d5 $1 Nfxd5 (16... exd5 $2 17. Nxd7 Qxd7 18. Qxe7 $18) (16... Nbxd5 17. Nxd5 Nxd5 18. Bxd5 $16) 17. Nxd5 Nxd5 (17... exd5 18. Nxf7 $1 Rxf7 19. Bxe7 $18) 18. Bxd5 Bxg5 (18... exd5 19. Nxd7 Bxg5 20. Nxf8 Qxf8 21. Rad1 Rd8 22. Qf3 $18) 19. Bxb7 Rc7 20. Bxa6 Bc8 (20... Qb8 21. Red1 Be8 22. a5 $18) 21. Bxc8 Qxc8 22. a5 $16 {Ernst,S-Straeter,T/Germany 2005.}) ({c)} 13... b6 14. Nxd5 exd5 15. Ne5 Bb7 16. Rc1 Re8 17. Qf3 $16 {.}) ({d)} 13... Bd7 $5 14. Ne5 (14. Bxf6 Nxf6 15. d5 Nxd5 16. Nxd5 exd5 17. Qxd5 (17. Bxd5 Bf6 18. Ne5 Bxe5 19. Rxe5 Qf6 $11) 17... Bc6 18. Qf5 g6 19. Qf4 Bd6 $13) 14... Bc6 15. Rc1 $14 {.}) 14. bxc3 Bd7 (14... Nd5 $5 15. Bxe7 (15. Bd2 $5) 15... Nxe7 16. Qd3 b6 17. Bc2 $14 {Stefansson,H-Zifroni,D/Agios Nikolaos 1995.}) 15. Ne5 Rc8 16. Qd3 Re8 17. a5 $1 Nd5 18. Bd2 $1 {White controls more space (which is why he declines piece exchanges), greater central influence and attacking chances against the black king; in short, White is better.} Rf8 19. c4 $6 (19. Qh3 $1) ({or} 19. Bc2 {.}) 19... Nb4 20. Qe4 Nc6 $1 21. Nf3 (21. f4 $2 Nxd4 $1 $17 {.}) 21... Bf6 22. Bc2 g6 23. Bd3 $6 (23. Bc3 $1 $14 {.}) 23... e5 $1 24. dxe5 (24. d5 Bf5 25. Qe3 e4 26. dxc6 Rxc6 $1 27. Bxe4 Re6 $1 28. Ng5 Bxg5 29. Qxg5 Rxe4 $11 {.}) 24... Bf5 25. Qf4 Nxe5 $1 26. Nxe5 (26. Bxf5 $2 Rxc4 $1 $17 {.}) 26... Bxd3 27. Rad1 Bc2 28. Rc1 Bf5 29. Rcd1 Bc2 30. Ng4 $1 Bg7 31. Rc1 Bb3 $2 (31... Bd3 $1 $13 {.}) 32. Bb4 $1 Re8 33. Rxe8+ Qxe8 34. Nf6+ Bxf6 35. Qxf6 Qe6 36. Qd4 $1 Bxc4 37. Re1 {White's decision to enter this type of position was excellent. He has attacking chances on the weak dark squares while, should things not go according to plan, he has the draw in hand, thanks to the opposite-coloured bishops and the blocked queenside pawns. Black's (the defender's) greatest problem in such positions is that the opponent can keep "testing the waters" without taking any particular risks. Here Black has a long and arduous defensive task ahead of him, with White constantly creating threats and Black himself having no chance to win the game. The only plan one can suggest for Black is to exchange queens; this will guarantee him a draw, but White of course will hardly allow this to happen!} Qd5 38. Qf6 Qf5 39. Qe7 Be6 40. h3 Qd5 41. Re3 Qd8 42. Qxb7 Rc1+ 43. Be1 (43. Re1 $2 Rxe1+ 44. Bxe1) ({or} 43. Kh2 $2 Qc7+ $1 {would lead to a draw. White needs all three of his pieces to create threats and there is no need to rush. In due course White will free his pieces and resume the attack.}) 43... Qd2 44. Qb8+ Kg7 45. Qe5+ Kg8 46. Kh2 Qd5 47. Qf6 Qf5 $2 (47... Qd6+ $1 48. f4 Rc4 $1 49. Bg3 Qd4 $1 $11 {.}) 48. Qd8+ Kg7 49. Bc3+ Rxc3 (49... f6 50. Rf3 $1 $18) ({or} 49... Kh6 50. Qh4+ Qh5 51. Qf4+ Qg5 52. Bg7+ Kh5 53. Re5 Bf5 54. g4+ Kh4 55. Qg3# {.}) 50. Qd4+ $1 Qf6 51. Qxc3 h5 52. h4 Bd7 53. Kg3 Qxc3 54. Rxc3 Bb5 55. Kf4 f6 56. Rc7+ Kh6 57. g3 Bd3 58. Rf7 g5+ 59. Ke3 Kg6 60. Rxf6+ Kxf6 61. hxg5+ Kxg5 62. Kxd3 1-0


