1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. g3 Bg7 4. Bg2 O-O 5. O-O d6 6. a4 Na6 7. Nc3 c5 8. e4 (8. d5 $6 {is inferior due to} e6 $1 9. e4 exd5 10. exd5 Nb4 $1 {threatening ...f5.}) 8... Bg4 $146 (8... cxd4 {Ü 53/(74)}) 9. d5 Nc7 ({After} 9... Qc8 10. Re1 $1 { f4, e5 , intending f4 and e5, White has an edge.}) 10. h3 Bxf3 11. Qxf3 Nd7 ({a)} 11... b6 12. Rb1 (12. Re1 Nd7 13. Be3 a6 14. Bf1 Rb8 15. Qd1 b5 16. axb5 axb5 17. Rb1 b4 18. Ne2 Nb5 $13 {Vandrey,W-Kindermann,S/Cuxhaven 1993}) (12. Bd2 $1 {is probably best.}) 12... Nd7 13. Bd2 a6 14. Qe2 Qb8 15. h4 b5 16. b3 Nb6 17. axb5 axb5 18. Nxb5 Nbxd5 19. Nxd6 Nb4 20. Bxb4 $6 (20. c3 $1 $14) 20... cxb4 21. Nc4 Nb5 $44 {½-½ Kochyev,A-Bischoff,K/Graz 1981}) ({b)} 11... e6 12. dxe6 fxe6 13. Qe2 Nd7 14. Be3 Qe7 15. Rad1 Ne5 16. Nb5 Nxb5 17. axb5 a6 18. f4 Nf7 19. c3 $14 {Alvarez Peon,R-Suarez Real,A/Gijon 1999}) ({c)} 11... a6 {see game Grivas,E-Pavlovic,M/Athens 1996}) 12. Bd2 b6 13. Rfb1 $1 $14 {The start of an original plan, its aim being to assume the initiative on the queenside, a flank that traditionally is Black's territory in such positions.} e6 $6 ({The opening of the position favours White, who possesses the two bishops. Preferable was} 13... a6 14. b4 $1) ({or even} 13... Rb8 $5) 14. dxe6 $1 fxe6 ({After} 14... Nxe6 $2 15. Nd5 $16 {White is much better.}) 15. Qe2 Ne5 {[ c6-d4, d5] With the idea ...c6-d4 and ...d5, with unclear play.} 16. Nb5 $1 a6 $1 17. Nxc7 Qxc7 18. Be3 Nc6 19. c3 Na5 20. Re1 $1 Nb3 21. Rad1 c4 22. h4 $1 $16 {[×g6, d6, e6] White's superiority is significant, as Black's position contains several weaknesses (d6, e6 and soon g6 as well).} b5 23. h5 Rad8 24. axb5 axb5 25. hxg6 hxg6 26. Qg4 Qf7 27. Qg5 $2 $138 ({White's advantage could have been retained by} 27. f4 $1 $16 {(} b4 $2 28. Qe2 $1 $18 {)}) 27... b4 $1 28. Qb5 bxc3 29. Qxc4 Nd2 $2 ({A serious mistake. After} 29... Na5 30. Qb5 Nb7 31. bxc3 Bxc3 32. Re2 $14 {White's advantage is minimal.}) 30. Qd3 Nf3+ 31. Bxf3 Qxf3 32. bxc3 $16 {White's position is now winning, as he has an extra pawn while Black has not managed to rid himself of his weaknesses.} d5 $1 33. Bb6 $2 ({Returning the favour!} 33. e5 $1 Rf5 34. Bd4 $16 {would retain White's plus.}) 33... Rb8 34. Bc5 Bxc3 $1 35. Re2 $1 dxe4 36. Rxe4 Rf5 37. Qxf3 Rxf3 38. Rxe6 Rf6 $6 $138 (38... Kg7 $14 {is better.}) 39. Re3 $1 Ba5 40. Rd7 Rf7 41. Rd6 $16 {[ץa5] Despite the reduced material, White's superiority is small (but permanent) and is owed to the following factors: 1) Material advantage of one pawn (but with all pawns on the same side) 2) Weak black pawn on g6 3) Weakened black king 4) Sidelined and misplaced piece (the a5-bishop) White must combine all the aforementioned small advantages in order to achieve the desired victory.} Kh7 42. Ree6 $6 (42. g4 $1 $18 {seems even better, with threats like d4 and h3+.}) 42... Rg8 43. Bd4 Bc7 44. Rc6 Rd7 45. Bc3 {Any piece exchange favours the defending side, as it helps limit the options available to the attacker. There are, of course, exceptions justified by specific considerations.} Bd8 46. Kg2 $1 {[ e1-h1] Intending e1-h1+.} Kh6 $1 47. Re1 Rd5 48. Rh1+ Kg5 ({Worse was} 48... Rh5 49. Rd1 $1 $18) 49. Bb2 $1 {Black has no useful moves and must constantly monitor White's threats. Meanwhile, White has now added the threat of c1+ to his armoury.} Kf5 50. Rh7 Ke4 51. Rf7 g5 52. Rc3 $1 {White threatens 53.e3#.} Ra5 53. Rc8 $1 Ra2 ({No relief is offered by} 53... Rd5 54. Bf6 Rd6 55. Bxd8 Rdxd8 56. Rxd8 Rxd8 57. Kh3 $18 {, when White will win the ending.}) 54. Bc1 g4 55. Be3 $1 $18 ({The careless} 55. Rd7 $4 Rxf2+ $1 $11 {would spoil all of White's efforts. Now, however, the win is simple.}) 55... Re8 56. Rd7 Kf5 57. Bd4 1-0


