1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. c4 b6 4. g3 (4. a3 c5 5. e3 Bb7 6. Nc3 Ne4 7. Nxe4 Bxe4 8. Bd3 Bxd3 9. Qxd3 cxd4 10. Qxd4 Nc6 11. Qd3 Be7 12. e4 Qc7 13. O-O O-O 14. b3 Bf6 15. Ra2 Rfd8 16. Rd1 Rac8 17. g3 d6 18. Bf4 Ne5 19. Qe2 Ng6 20. Be3 Qb7 21. Bg5 Bxg5 22. Nxg5 Qc7 23. Nf3 Qc5 24. a4 Ne5 25. Rad2 h6 26. Nxe5 Qxe5 27. Qe3 $14 Rc6 28. f4 Qc5 29. Rd4 Re8 30. Kf2 e5 31. Rd5 exf4 32. gxf4 Qa3 33. Rg1 Qb2+ 34. Rd2 Qf6 35. Rg4 Rc5 36. Qd4 Rce5 37. Kg3 h5 38. fxe5 dxe5 39. Qd7 Re7 40. Qd8+ Kh7 41. Rf2 Qe6 42. Rg5 g6 43. Kg2 h4 44. Qd5 {1-0.}) 4... Bb7 5. Bg2 Be7 6. O-O O-O 7. Nc3 Ne4 8. Qc2 Nxc3 9. Qxc3 c5 10. b3 cxd4 11. Nxd4 Bxg2 12. Kxg2 Nc6 13. Bb2 Nxd4 14. Qxd4 Bf6 15. Qd2 Bxb2 16. Qxb2 {After a long theoretical variation (which is more extensively analysed in Grivas,E-Khetsuriani,B/Athens 2003) Black is stuck with a weak backward pawn on d7. Naturally, as often happens in this type of position, White's advantage is not really great, but it is static and consequently long-term, while the danger of defeat is significantly reduced. White's plans are simple and include the doubling of the major pieces on the d-file and the development of an initiative on both flanks. A nice, related example, can be found in the game Gheorghiu,F-Ree,H/Lone Pine 1979:} Qc7 17. Rfd1 (17. Rad1 Rfd8 18. Rd4 Qc6+ 19. Kg1 d6 20. Rfd1 Rd7 21. e4 Rad8 22. a4 $14 {is quite similar:} Kf8 23. Qa3 Ke8 24. Qc1 Qc5 25. Qd2 h6 26. h4 Ke7 27. Kg2 f6 28. Qe2 Qc6 29. Qg4 Kf7 30. h5 Re7 31. R1d2 Qc5 32. f4 Kf8 33. Qf3 Kg8 34. Qd1 Red7 35. f5 Qe5 36. Qf3 Rc7 37. g4 Rcd7 38. fxe6 Qxe6 39. Rd5 Re7 40. R2d4 Rc7 41. Qf4 Rcd7 42. Kf3 Kf8 43. Rd3 Ke7 44. a5 Rc8 45. axb6 axb6 46. Rb5 Rb7 47. Rbd5 Rd7 48. Qd2 Rc5 49. Qa2 Kf7 50. b4 Rxd5 51. Rxd5 g6 $6 (51... Re7 52. Qc2 Ra7 53. Qd3 $14) 52. hxg6+ Kxg6 53. Qh2 Rd8 54. Qf4 Qe7 55. Qd2 Qe6 56. Qd4 Kf7 $2 (56... Rc8 57. Rxd6 Rxc4 58. Rxe6 Rxd4 59. Rxb6 $16) 57. Qxb6 Rg8 58. Qc7+ Ke8 59. Rf5 {1-0 Abramovic,B-Krstic,P/Belgrade 2008.}) 17... Rfd8 18. Rd4 d6 19. Rad1 Rd7 20. R1d3 Rad8 21. Qd2 Kf8 22. e4 h6 23. f4 ({Rather premature. The move} 23. h4 $1 {intending h5 and g4-g5 would cause Black a serious headache.}) 23... Qc6 $1 24. a4 a6 25. h4 f5 $6 {Black finds it impossible to remain passive for such a long time. With this move he also weakens the e6-pawn, but hopes for counterplay based on the exposed white king.} 26. Qe2 fxe4 27. Rxe4 Re8 28. Qf3 Rf7 29. Kh2 Qc5 30. Rde3 Rf6 31. Qe2 Kf7 32. Qd2 $1 a5 {Forced, as White was threatening 33.b4!. But now Black has given up the possibility of counterplay with ...b5, the only decent plan he had at his disposal.} 33. Rd3 Rd8 34. Red4 Ke7 35. Qe2 Kf7 36. Qe4 $1 Qc7 37. Kg2 $2 {White had made good use of his position so far and should have now played 37.h5!. Next would be the advance of his g-pawn, supported by the white rooks. It is not necessary to offer specific variations as means of proof, as these plans would take up a lot of time and preparation. The only certain thing is that Black cannot effectively stop White's plan and, as a result, is condemned to defeat.} h5 $1 {The only move and a very good one, securing the draw. The question is, of course, why? The answer is simple! The lack of any satisfactory breakthrough favours the defending side. Both flanks have been blocked; as a result, White does not have at his disposal the most useful tool in such positions, i.e. the creation of a second front. This is an instructive and very significant strategic motif.} 38. Qf3 g6 39. Qe4 Rd7 40. Rd2 Rd8 41. Kh2 Rf5 42. Qd3 Ke7 43. Re2 Kf7 44. Qf3 Re8 45. Qe4 Re7 46. Red2 Rd7 47. Qf3 Rd8 48. Qd3 Ke7 49. Qe4 Kf7 50. Re2 Rf6 51. Rd3 Rc8 52. Red2 Rd8 53. Rd4 Rf5 1/2-1/2


