1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nbd2 Bf5 5. Nh4 Be4 6. f3 Bg6 7. Qb3 Qc7 8. e3 e6 9. Nxg6 hxg6 10. Bd3 c5 $1 $146 {A good novelty. Somehow its good merits had escaped White's preparation.} (10... Nbd7 {Ü 106/242}) 11. cxd5 exd5 ({Black should seriously consider} 11... Nxd5 $5 {where White has problems:} 12. e4 (12. Bb5+ Nd7 13. Ne4 cxd4 14. exd4 a6 15. Bxd7+ Qxd7 $15 {or}) (12. dxc5 Nd7 (12... Bxc5 13. Ne4 Bb4+ 14. Bd2 (14. Kf2 $6 Nc6 15. a3 Be7 16. Bd2 O-O-O $17) 14... Bxd2+ 15. Kxd2 Nc6 16. Ke2 f5 17. Qxb7 Qxb7 18. Nd6+ Ke7 19. Nxb7 Rab8 20. Rac1 $1 Rhc8 21. b3 Ndb4 $15) 13. Ne4 O-O-O 14. Bd2 Nxc5 (14... Rxh2 $6 15. Rxh2 Qxh2 16. c6 $1 $14) 15. Nxc5 Bxc5 16. Rc1 Kb8 $15) 12... Nb4 13. d5 Nxd3+ 14. Qxd3 exd5 15. exd5 Na6 $15 {.}) 12. dxc5 Nbd7 ({Interesting is the immediate} 12... Bxc5 13. Qc2 (13. Qc3 $6 Qe7 14. b4 Bxe3 (14... Qxe3+ $2 15. Kd1 $16) 15. Qc8+ Qd8 16. Qxb7 Nbd7 17. Nb3 Bb6 18. Bf4 O-O $17 {or}) (13. Nf1 Nc6 14. Bd2 O-O 15. Rc1 Qe7 16. Kf2 Rfe8 17. g4 Ne5 18. Kg2 (18. Be2 $6 d4) 18... b6 $15) 13... Na6 (13... Nbd7 14. b4 {transposes}) 14. Nb3 Rc8 15. Nxc5 Nxc5 16. Bb5+ $13 {.}) 13. Qc2 $6 ({White was quite optimistic at this point, so he avoided the 'drawish'} 13. Qc3 Bxc5 (13... Qxc5 $6 14. Qxc5 Nxc5 15. Bb5+ $14) 14. b4 (14. Nb3 Rc8 15. Nxc5 Nxc5 16. Bb5+ $13) 14... d4 $1 15. exd4 Nd5 16. Qc4 Ne3 17. Qc3 Nd5 $11 {.}) 13... Bxc5 $6 ({Black could take over the initiative with the other capture:} 13... Nxc5 $1 14. Bb5+ Kd8 $1 15. h3 (15. Nb3 Rc8 16. Nxc5 Bxc5 $17 {or}) (15. b4 Qe5 (15... Ne6 16. Qxc7+ Kxc7 17. a3 $11) 16. bxc5 (16. Bb2 Qxe3+ 17. Kf1 (17. Kd1 Ne6 18. Re1 Qb6 $17) 17... Ne6 18. Rd1 Bxb4 19. Ne4 Ke7 $17) 16... Qxa1 17. Nb3 Qe5 18. g3 Rc8 $17) 15... Rc8 16. Qd1 Qg3+ 17. Kf1 Kc7 $17 {.}) 14. b4 $1 (14. Nb3 Rxh2 $1 15. Rxh2 Bb4+ 16. Bd2 Bxd2+ 17. Qxd2 Qxh2 18. O-O-O O-O-O $17 {was not very encouraging for White.}) 14... Qe5 ({Black is obliged to enter the complications, as the position after} 14... Bd6 $6 15. Qxc7 Bxc7 16. Bb2 Ke7 (16... Rxh2 $6 17. Rxh2 Bxh2 18. f4 $44) 17. h3 $14 {would be fine for White.}) 15. Bb2 $1 ({White has not much after} 15. bxc5 $2 Qxa1 16. Nb3 Qe5 17. c6 bxc6 18. Qxc6 O-O 19. O-O Rac8 $17 {or}) (15. Nb3 $2 Rxh2 $1 16. Rxh2 Bxb4+ 17. Bd2 Bxd2+ 18. Qxd2 Qxh2 $17 {.}) 15... Qxe3+ 16. Kd1 Be7 17. Re1 $44 {White's compensation for the sacrificed pawn is fine, as his pieces cooperate harmoniously, he has the bishop pair and his king is perfectly safe. Black needs time to get his pieces into play.} Qb6 ({The other option was} 17... Qf4 18. Rc1 Kf8 (18... Qxb4 $2 19. Qc8+ Rxc8 20. Rxc8# {#}) 19. a3 (19. Qc8+ $2 Rxc8 20. Rxc8+ Ne8 21. Bb5 Ndf6 22. Bxf6 gxf6 23. Rxe8+ Kg7 24. R8xe7 Rxh2 $17) 19... Bd8 20. g3 Qg5 21. Nb3 $44 {.}) 18. Rc1 {Now White controls both open files and he also thinking of penetrating on the 7th rank.} Kf8 $1 (18... Rxh2 $6 19. Bd4 $1 Qd8 20. Qc7 Rxg2 21. Bf1 Qxc7 (21... Rg5 22. Qxb7 Kf8 23. Rc7 $44) 22. Rxc7 Rh2 23. Bxf6 gxf6 24. Bb5 Rd8 25. Rxb7 $14 {was what White would love to have!}) 19. a3 $1 ({The b4-pawn is important and White cannot afford to lose it:} 19. h3 $6 Qxb4 20. Bxf6 (20. Rb1 Qd6) 20... Nxf6 21. Rb1 Qd6 22. Rxb7 Bd8 23. Qb3 Bb6 24. Ne4 Nxe4 25. Rxe4 Qc5 $17 {as now White's king is rather exposed.}) 19... Re8 $6 ({Played with the intention to neutralise the pressure along the e-file, but I think that Black is obliged to accept the second pawn offer with the natural} 19... Rxh2 $1 {activating his rook at the same time, although White's compensation still seems good:} 20. Qc7 $1 Qxc7 (20... Rxg2 21. Bxf6 gxf6 $1 (21... Bxf6 $2 22. Qxd7 Bg5 23. Rc8+ Rxc8 24. Qxc8+ Qd8 25. Qxd8+ Bxd8 26. Bb5 $16) 22. Qxd7 Bd6 $44) 21. Rxc7 Bd6 22. Rxb7 Rxg2 23. Bd4 (23. Bb5 Bf4 24. Re2 Rxe2 25. Kxe2 $44) 23... a6 24. a4 $44 {.}) 20. Qc7 $6 ({Losing an important tempo. The simple} 20. h3 $1 Bd8 (20... Bd6 21. Qc8 $1) 21. Rxe8+ Kxe8 22. Qc8 $44 {was fine for White.}) 20... Bd8 $1 ({After} 20... Qxc7 $6 21. Rxc7 Rxh2 22. Rxb7 Bd6 (22... Rxg2 $6 23. Bxf6 Nxf6 24. Bb5 $16) 23. Rxe8+ Kxe8 24. Bf1 $14 {only White has winning chances.}) 21. Rxe8+ Kxe8 22. Qg3 $6 ({The Silicon Monster states that White's compensation after} 22. Qxb6 $5 Nxb6 23. h3 Ke7 24. Bd4 $44 {is also fine, but I felt that with the queens off the board it wouldn't be that easy...}) 22... Ke7 $6 ({Black should think of} 22... Nf8 $1 23. Be5 $1 (23. Kc2 $6 Ne6 24. h3 Bc7 25. Qe1 Kd7 $17) 23... Ne6 $15 {.}) 23. h3 {At last - the needed move!} Qd6 24. Qg5 $6 ({Again too optimistic.} 24. Qe1+ Kf8 25. Nb3 $44 {was the correct follow-up.}) 24... Bb6 (24... Rh5 $2 25. Qe3+ Kf8 26. Qxa7 $14 {.}) 25. Nb3 Re8 26. Bb5 $6 ({White loses control. Still he should have gone for} 26. Nd4 Kf8 27. Kc2 a6 28. Kb1 Ne5 29. Bf1 $15 {.}) 26... a6 $1 (26... Kf8 $6 27. Nc5 Bxc5 28. bxc5 Qe7 29. Qd2 $44 {.}) 27. Bxd7 (27. Ba4 Ba7 $1 28. Bxd7 {makes no difference.}) 27... Kxd7 $6 ({A centralized king with major pieces on board is not a good sign. Safe and good was} 27... Qxd7 28. Nc5 Qb5 $17 {.}) 28. Nc5+ Bxc5 (28... Ke7 $2 29. Nxb7 Qe6 30. Qe5 $14 {.}) 29. Rxc5 b6 {Black had to defend against the threat xf6 and /xd5.} 30. Rc2 Qe6 31. Qg3 (31. Qd2 Rc8 {and Black is a healthy pawn up, but maybe his winning chances are not many, especially after} 32. Rxc8 Kxc8 33. Bd4 Kb7 34. g4 $15 {. White had to go for it anyway.}) 31... Rc8 32. Rd2 $2 ({White cannot survive with such optimism! He should have accepted a 'reflection' of the previous note with} 32. Rxc8 Kxc8 33. Bd4 Ne8 34. Qg5 $15 {.}) 32... Qf5 $1 {Now Black's attack is unstoppable. But due to serious mutual time-trouble many mistakes were generated!} 33. Bd4 $6 ({This loses on the spot, as} 33. Bxf6 $6 gxf6 34. Ke2 Re8+ 35. Kf2 Kc6 36. Kg1 (36. Qh4 Qe5 37. Kg1 Qe1+ $19) 36... Qe5 37. Qf2 Qe3 $19 {. But White might had tried}) (33. Be5 Re8 34. f4 {where Black would have to find} Qb1+ $1 (34... Ne4 $2 35. Qb3 $1 $11) 35. Ke2 Ne4 36. Qd3 Qxd3+ 37. Rxd3 f6 38. Kf3 $1 Ke6 $1 (38... fxe5 $2 39. Rxd5+ Kc6 40. Kxe4 exf4+ 41. Kd4 $11) 39. Bd4 b5 $17 {.}) 33... Qb1+ $2 ({Both opponents missed the beautiful and effective} 33... Ne4 $1 34. fxe4 Qf1+ 35. Qe1 Rc1+ $19 {. Not only mutual time-trouble but also mutual blindness!}) 34. Ke2 Re8+ 35. Be3 Qf5 ({Black could immediately play} 35... Qb3 36. Qf4 Qxa3 37. Qd4 Re6 (37... Ke7 38. Qxb6 Kf8 39. Kf2 Kg8 $15) 38. Kf2 $44 {but in this case White would have achieve piece coordination and king safety, staying in the game.}) 36. Qh4 b5 $2 ({A blunder. Black had to go for} 36... Qe5 $1 37. Rd3 (37. Qd4 $6 Qxd4 38. Rxd4 Kc6 {is hopeless in the long run}) 37... Qb2+ 38. Rd2 Qxa3 39. Qd4 Re6 (39... Ke7 40. Qxb6 Kf8 41. Kf2 Kg8 $15) 40. Kf2 {as it was already mentioned in the previous note.}) 37. Qd4 $1 {Now White is fully back in the game!} Re6 $1 ({Best:} 37... Rc8 $6 38. Qa7+ Ke8 39. Qxa6 $14 {.}) 38. g4 $6 ({More 'accurate' was} 38. Qc5 Rc6 39. Qf8 Re6 (39... Nh5 40. Qb8 (40. g4 Nf4+ 41. Bxf4 Qxf4 42. Rxd5+ Ke6 43. Rc5 $11) 40... Rc7 41. g4 Nf4+ 42. Bxf4 Qxf4 43. Rxd5+ Ke6 44. Rc5 $11) 40. Qc5 $11 {or if White wanted to try for more he should have opted for}) (38. Qa7+ $5 Ke8 39. Qb8+ Ke7 40. Kf1 $1 $13 {.}) 38... Qe5 39. g5 $2 ({'Groundless' optimism is reality's enemy! A draw would be on the cards after the simple} 39. Qxe5 Rxe5 40. Kf2 $1 (40. f4 $6 Re6 41. g5 Ne4 42. Rxd5+ Rd6 43. Rxd6+ Nxd6 $15) 40... Re6 (40... Kc6 41. Rc2+ Kb7 42. Rd2 $11) 41. g5 Ne8 42. Rxd5+ Rd6 43. Re5 Nc7 44. Ke2 $11 {. But White spend his last valuable seconds wrongly thinking that he could go for more and finally he went for less!}) 39... Qxg5 $19 {Of course. Now White is plain lost.} 40. Qa7+ Ke8 41. Kf2 (41. Rc2 Kf8 $1 {was not an option either.}) 41... Qh4+ 42. Kg2 Kf8 $1 43. Qb8+ (43. Qd4 Qxd4 44. Bxd4 Nh5 $19 {.}) 43... Re8 44. Qd6+ Kg8 45. Qf4 Qe1 {And White resigned as he has no counterplay for his material deficit. An interesting battle with mutual mistakes and great fighting spirit.} 0-1


