1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Nbd2 d5 5. a3 Be7 ({Alternatively, Black could play} 5... Bxd2+ {, allowing White a slight edge due to the bishop pair but retaining a very solid, though perhaps passive, position:} 6. Bxd2 O-O (6... Ne4 7. Bf4 (7. e3 O-O 8. Rc1 a5 9. Qc2 c6 10. Bd3 f5 11. b4 Bd7 12. O-O $14 {Valenzuela Fuentealba,L-Duarte,M/Santiago 2008}) 7... O-O 8. Qc2 (8. e3 Nd7 9. Bd3 f5 10. Qc2 c6 11. O-O-O Ndf6 12. h3 Bd7 13. Ne5 $14 {Miralles,G-Nay,R/France 1995}) 8... Nc6 9. e3 g5 10. Bg3 f5 11. O-O-O $14 {Granda Zuniga,J-Galego,L/Turin 2006}) 7. Rc1 Nbd7 (7... c6 8. e3 Nbd7 9. Bd3 Re8 10. O-O Ne4 11. Qc2 Ndf6 12. Rfd1 Nxd2 13. Rxd2 Bd7 14. Ne5 $14 {Peng,Z-Hendriks,R/Hoogeveen 2000}) 8. Bg5 c6 9. e3 Qb6 10. Qc2 Ne4 11. Bf4 Ndf6 12. Bd3 $14 {Vescovi,G-Fernandes,F/Santa Barbara d'Oeste 1998.}) 6. g3 ({White's main alternative is} 6. Qc2 Nbd7 (6... O-O 7. g3 a5 8. Bg2 Nc6 9. O-O dxc4 10. Qxc4 a4 11. Rd1 Bd7 12. Qd3 $14 {Grivas,E-Angelis,M/Katerini 1993}) 7. e4 dxe4 8. Nxe4 O-O (8... c5 9. Nxf6+ Bxf6 10. Be3 Qc7 11. O-O-O cxd4 12. Nxd4 a6 13. g4 $14 {Grivas,E-Hobuss,U/Dortmund 1991}) 9. Bd3 $1 (9. Nc3 b6 10. Be2 Bb7 11. Bf4 c5 $13 {Grivas,E-Ivanovic,B/Egio 1986}) 9... Nxe4 10. Bxe4 Nf6 11. Bd3 b6 12. Bg5 h6 13. Bxf6 Bxf6 14. O-O-O Bb7 15. Bh7+ Kh8 16. Be4 Qc8 17. h4 $14 {Grivas,E-Georgiou,An/Limassol 1997.}) 6... dxc4 $6 ({This move suits White as his knight occupies a more central post. Better is} 6... O-O 7. Bg2 {and now: a)} Nbd7 ({b)} 7... b6 8. O-O Bb7 9. cxd5 Bxd5 (9... exd5 10. b4 a5 11. b5 c6 12. bxc6 (12. a4 cxb5 13. axb5 Ne8 14. Ne5 Nc7 15. Qa4 $14 {Medvegy,Z-Babula,V/Germany 2006}) 12... Nxc6 13. Bb2 b5 14. Ne5 b4 15. axb4 Bxb4 16. Nd3 $14 {Danielian,V-Vlasov,E/St Petersburg 1999}) 10. Qc2 Nbd7 (10... c5 11. e4 Bb7 12. dxc5 Bxc5 13. e5 (13. b4 Be7 14. Bb2 $14 {Luechtemeier,P-Schuetzhold,F/Leipzig 2003}) 13... Nd5 14. Ne4 Be7 15. Nfg5 g6 16. Nf3 $1 Nd7 17. Bh6 Re8 18. Qa4 $14) 11. e4 Bb7 12. e5 Nd5 13. Ne4 h6 14. Re1 (14. b4 c5 15. dxc5 bxc5 16. b5 a6 $11 {Farago,S-Froehlich,P/Budapest 2000}) 14... c5 15. dxc5 Nxc5 16. Nxc5 Bxc5 17. b4 Be7 18. Qe4 $1 Qd7 19. Qg4 $14 Kh8 20. Qh5 Kg8 21. Bxh6 gxh6 22. Qxh6 f5 23. Qg6+ Kh8 24. Nd4 Bc8 25. Rad1 Rd8 26. Nxf5 Bf8 27. Re4 Bg7 28. Rh4+ Kg8 29. Bxd5 exd5 30. Rxd5 {1-0 Grivas,E-Kalesis,N/Iraklion 2004.}) ({c)} 7... c5 8. dxc5 a5 (8... Bxc5 $6 9. b4 Be7 10. Bb2 a5 (10... Nbd7 11. O-O $16 {Polishchuk,O-Sowul,B/Augustow 2004}) 11. b5 Nbd7 (11... a4 12. Qc2 Nbd7 13. O-O b6 14. Nd4 Bb7 15. cxd5 $1 $16 {Brinck Claussen,B-Ortega,R/Havana 1966}) 12. O-O b6 13. Nd4 Bb7 14. cxd5 $16) (8... dxc4 9. Qc2 Bxc5 10. O-O c3 11. Qxc3 Be7 12. Nc4 Nc6 13. b4 Nd5 14. Qc2 b5 15. Ne3 Bb7 16. Nxd5 exd5 (16... Qxd5 17. Rd1 Qc4 18. Qxc4 bxc4 19. Bb2 $16) 17. Bb2 $14 {Cramling,P-Laveryd,P/Katrineholm 1999}) 9. O-O Nbd7 (9... Bxc5 10. cxd5 exd5 (10... Qxd5 11. Ne1 Qh5 12. Nd3 Be7 13. Nf4 $14) 11. Nb3 Bb6 12. Nbd4 $14) 10. cxd5 exd5 (10... Nxd5 11. c6 bxc6 12. Qc2 Ba6 13. Nc4 $14) 11. Nb3 (11. c6 bxc6 12. Nd4 Qb6 13. Nf5 Bd8 14. Nb3 a4 15. Nbd4 c5 16. Nf3 Re8 $13 {Aagaard,J-Martens,M/Lyngby 1990}) 11... a4 (11... Nxc5 12. Be3 Nce4 13. Rc1 $14) 12. Nbd4 Nxc5 13. Be3 (13. Bd2 Nfe4 14. Bb4 Re8 15. Rc1 Qb6 16. Qc2 Be6 17. e3 Rec8 18. Nxe6 fxe6 19. Nd4 $14 {Tihonov,J-Schneider,S/Hallsberg 1998}) 13... Re8 14. Rc1 Bf8 15. Rc2 $14 {Grivas,E-Shavtvaladze,N/Thessaloniki 2007.}) 8. O-O (8. b4 a5 9. b5 c5 10. bxc6 bxc6 11. O-O Ba6 12. Qc2 Rc8 13. Bb2 c5 $13 {Grivas,E-Mastrokoukos,G/Iraklion 1994}) 8... b6 9. cxd5 exd5 10. b4 Re8 11. Bb2 Bd6 12. Re1 Bb7 13. b5 a6 14. a4 Qe7 15. Qb3 axb5 16. axb5 Rxa1 17. Rxa1 Ne4 18. e3 $14 Ra8 $6 19. Rxa8+ Bxa8 20. Qa2 Qe8 21. Nxe4 dxe4 22. Ng5 Nf6 23. Nxf7 Bd5 24. Nxd6 cxd6 25. Qa4 Be6 26. Ba3 Qc8 27. Bf1 d5 28. Qa6 Nd7 {1-0 Grivas,E-Klimis,L/Athens 2007.}) 7. Nxc4 b6 (7... c5 8. Bf4 (8. Bg2 Nc6 9. O-O cxd4 10. Qd3 (10. Bf4 $5) 10... O-O 11. Rd1 Bd7 12. Nxd4 Nxd4 13. Qxd4 Ba4 14. Qxd8 Rfxd8 15. Rxd8+ Rxd8 16. Be3 b6 $11) (8. Bg5 $5 cxd4 9. Qxd4 O-O 10. Bg2 Nc6 11. Qxd8 Rxd8 12. Nfe5 Nxe5 13. Nxe5 h6 14. Bd2 $14) 8... b5 9. Nce5 Bb7 10. dxc5 Qxd1+ 11. Rxd1 Bxc5 12. Bg2 Nbd7 13. Nxd7 Nxd7 14. O-O $14 {Cebalo,M-Grosar,A/Maribor 1994}) (7... b5 8. Nce5 Bb7 9. Bg2 $14 {.}) 8. Bg2 Bb7 9. O-O O-O 10. Bf4 Nbd7 11. Rc1 $5 ({White has completed his development and retains a slight edge thanks to his greater control of space. He can also retain a similar edge by} 11. b4 c5 12. dxc5 bxc5 13. b5 a6 14. a4 axb5 15. axb5 Rxa1 16. Qxa1 {.}) 11... c5 12. Re1 $1 ({A difficult move, threatening 13.d6 d5 14.e4. The immediate} 12. Nd6 $6 Bd5 13. Nb5 Bc6 $1 {doesn't offer much. Black has many problems to solve, and is in danger of asphyxiating on his back two ranks.}) 12... Bd5 $5 ({An interesting idea, preventing 13.d6?? in view of 13...h5!. Instead after} 12... cxd4 $2 13. Nxd4 Bxg2 14. Kxg2 {White will occupy the outpost on c6, increasing his advantage.}) 13. Ne3 $1 Be4 ({Compulsory, as after} 13... cxd4 $2 14. Bc7 $1 Qe8 15. Nxd5 Nxd5 16. Nxd4) ({or} 13... Bb7 $2 14. dxc5 Nxc5 15. b4 Nce4 16. Rc7 {White is clearly on top.}) 14. dxc5 Nxc5 $6 ({Although apparently unpleasant, the slightly worse position after} 14... bxc5 {had to be accepted.}) 15. b4 Ncd7 (15... Qxd1 {is bad:} 16. Rexd1 Ncd7 17. Rc7 {and White is much better.}) 16. Bc7 $1 {White's superiority is growing, as the black pieces have failed to find decent posts.} Qe8 17. Nc4 Kh8 {Visually displeasing but compulsory!} 18. Nd6 Bxd6 19. Bxd6 Rg8 20. Qd4 {White's advantage is unquestionable. He commands more space and has the bishop-pair, but things are not simple as Black has no static weaknesses.} h6 ({White would retain his plus after} 20... Rc8 21. Ng5 $1 Bg6 22. Bc6 {as well.}) 21. Red1 $6 ({Time pressure!} 21. Ne5 {is enough to retain a clear advantage.}) 21... Rc8 22. Ne5 Rxc1 23. Rxc1 Bxg2 24. Kxg2 Nxe5 25. Bxe5 {White remains on top as his bishop is a better minor piece than the black knight. The power of the white bishop becomes evident both in the middlegame, where it assists White's attacking play, and in the endgame, where the pawn structure favours the bishop.} Qa8+ 26. Kg1 Nd5 $6 ({Time pressure provokes a mistake from Black.} 26... Rd8 27. Qf4 $1) ({and} 26... Ne4 $2 27. f3 f6 28. Qxe4 {are clearly unsatisfactory for Black,}) ({but} 26... Nh7 $1 27. Qc4 $1 Rd8 28. f3 {would somewhat diminish Black's inferiority.}) 27. e4 $1 {White grabs his chance, creating insoluble problems for Black.} Ne7 (27... f6 28. exd5 (28. Bd6 Rd8) 28... fxe5 29. Qxe5 Qxd5 (29... exd5 30. Rc7) 30. Qxd5 exd5 31. Rc7 {leads to a lost endgame for Black.}) 28. Qe3 $1 Kh7 29. Rc7 Ng6 30. Bc3 {The white pieces cooperate harmoniously, all of them occupying better positions than their black counterparts.} Rc8 ({An attempt to complicate the position, such as} 30... Rf8 31. h4 $1 {offers no hope.}) 31. Rxf7 e5 32. h4 $1 Kg8 33. Rf5 Rc4 34. h5 $1 Rxe4 35. Qd3 Nh4 $6 ({Naturally, after} 35... Ne7 36. Rxe5 Rxe5 37. Bxe5 {White wins easily. Black preferred to commit suicide rather than suffer a slow but certain death in the endgame.}) 36. gxh4 Rg4+ 37. Kf1 Qh1+ 38. Ke2 Re4+ 39. Kd2 Re1 40. Kc2 Qc6 41. Kb2 Qe6 42. Qd8+ Kh7 43. Rf8 (43. Rf8 {After} Re2+ 44. Kc1 {Black has no defence against mate.}) 1-0


