1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d6 3. g3 g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. O-O O-O 6. a4 a5 7. b3 Nfd7 $5 ({This well-known idea is a novelty at this stage. More common are the following options: a)} 7... c6 8. Bb2 (8. Nbd2 d5 9. Bb2 Nbd7 10. c4 b5 $2 11. axb5 cxb5 12. Ne5 e6 13. Nc6 Qb6 14. cxd5 Nxd5 15. Ne7+ Nxe7 16. Bxa8 Nd5 17. Nf3 Ba6 18. Bxd5 exd5 19. Ne5 Nb8 20. Qd2 b4 21. Rfc1 f6 22. Nd3 Rd8 23. Rc5 Nc6 24. Nf4 Bh6 25. Qe3 Bc8 26. Rac1 Bd7 27. Rxc6 {1-0 Nikolaidis,I-Gogolis,A/Athens 1997}) 8... Qc7 (8... Bg4 9. Nbd2 Re8 10. e4 Nbd7 11. e5 Nd5 12. Qe2 $14 {Vaganian,R-Bielczyk,J/Caracas 1976}) 9. Nbd2 Re8 10. e4 Na6 11. h3 e5 12. Re1 $14 {Petrosian,T-Doroshkievich,V/Yerevan 1975}) ({b)} 7... Ne4 8. Bb2 c5 9. Qc1 Na6 10. Rd1 cxd4 11. Bxd4 Bxd4 12. Nxd4 Nac5 13. Qe3 Nf6 14. Nc3 Bd7 15. Qd2 Qb6 16. e4 $14 {Vaganian,R-Chiburdanidze,M/Moscow 1981}) ({c)} 7... Nc6 8. Bb2 Bf5 9. Nh4 (9. Re1 Nb4 10. Na3 d5 11. c3 Na6 12. Nc2 c6 13. Ne3 Be4 14. Bh3 Bxf3 15. exf3 $14 {Witkowski,S-Tseshkovsky,V/Lubniewice 1995}) 9... Bd7 10. Na3 Qc8 11. Nb5 (11. e4 $5 g5 12. e5 $13 {Sherbakov,R-Nicevski,R/Cheliabinsk 1991}) 11... Nb4 12. Re1 c6 13. Na3 Bh3 14. Bh1 d5 15. Ng2 Nh5 16. c3 Na6 17. e4 e6 18. e5 f6 19. exf6 Rxf6 20. Bc1 Qf8 21. Ra2 $14 {Smyslov,V-Borisenko,G/Moscow 1955}) 8. e4 e5 9. Bb2 Nc6 10. Na3 exd4 $6 ({Black should play} 10... f5 $1 11. exf5 e4 (11... gxf5 12. dxe5 dxe5 13. Nh4 Kh8 14. f4 $14) 12. Nd2 gxf5 13. c3 Nf6 14. Qe2 {where White can demonstrate just a tiny advantage.}) 11. Nxd4 Nde5 12. f4 Nxd4 13. Bxd4 Nc6 14. Bxg7 Kxg7 15. Nb5 $16 Bd7 16. Qd2 Rc8 17. Rad1 f6 18. h3 Re8 19. Kh2 Qe7 20. Rfe1 h5 21. Nc3 Qf7 22. Nd5 {Black is left without any counterplay and his king is also rather weak.} Be6 23. Ne3 f5 $6 ({A waiting move as} 23... Rcd8 {is the only option. Opening up the position can only benefit White.}) 24. exf5 Bxf5 25. Bxc6 bxc6 26. Qc3+ Kh7 27. Nxf5 Qxf5 28. Qxc6 Kh6 29. Qc3 h4 30. Rxe8 Rxe8 31. Re1 Rf8 (31... hxg3+ 32. Kxg3 $16 Rxe1 $4 33. Qh8#) 32. Qd2 hxg3+ 33. Kxg3 Rf7 34. Re2 Kh5 35. Qe3 Qf6 36. Qf3+ Kh6 37. Qg4 Qc3+ 38. Kg2 Qd4 39. Rf2 $6 (39. Qh4+ Kg7 40. Re8 Qd2+ 41. Kf3 Qd1+ 42. Ke3 Qc1+ 43. Kd3 Qd1+ 44. Kc3 Qh5 45. Qxh5 gxh5 46. Re4 $16) 39... Re7 $2 ({A blunder in time-trouble. Black had to play} 39... Rf5 {and wait for White to show his technique.}) 40. Qh4+ 1-0


