1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. g3 Bg7 4. Bg2 O-O 5. O-O d6 6. a4 a5 7. Nc3 d5 $5 8. Ne5 c6 9. e4 ({a)} 9. Bf4 Nh5 10. Be3 (10. Bc1 Qb6 11. e4 dxe4 12. Nxe4 Nd7 13. Nxd7 Bxd7 14. c3 Nf6 15. Nc5 Bg4 {½-½ Iordachescu,V-Sutovsky,E/Medellin 1996}) 10... Nd7 11. f4 Nxe5 12. dxe5 f6 13. exf6 Nxf6 $13 {Papaioannou,I-Gelashvili,T/Korinthos 1998}) ({b)} 9. f3 Nfd7 $1 10. Nxd7 Nxd7 11. Kh1 Qb6 12. e3 e5 13. Ne2 Re8 14. c3 $11 {Peric,S-Ricci,M/Cannes 2000}) 9... dxe4 10. Nxe4 Nxe4 11. Bxe4 Bh3 12. Re1 Nd7 13. Nxd7 $1 Qxd7 14. Be3 Rad8 15. c3 Bg4 16. Qb3 Be6 17. Qc2 Bd5 18. Bxd5 cxd5 (18... Qxd5 19. Bf4 e6 20. Be5 $14) 19. Bf4 Rc8 20. Qb3 $1 {White actually holds the advantage, as Black is lacking serious counterplay.} e6 21. Qb6 Ra8 22. Ra3 Qc6 {The threat of 23.b3 forces Black to exchange queens.} 23. Qb5 $1 {After} (23. Rb3 $6 Qxa4 24. Qxb7 Qc4 {Black holds things together..}) 23... Qxb5 $2 ({A bad idea, based on a miscalculation. Black should continue with the immediate} 23... Rfc8 24. Rea1 {when White's plan of d3, b3-b5 and c2-b3 would give him the advantage.}) 24. axb5 Rfc8 25. Rea1 b6 26. b4 $1 {Black thought this was impossible, but the truth is different!} Bf8 27. bxa5 $1 ({This is an easy combination to calculate. Of course} 27. Bd2 Rab8 $1 {or}) (27. Ra4 $2 Rxc3 {would be naive.}) 27... Bxa3 ({A nice variation is} 27... g5 28. Bc7 $3 Bxa3 (28... Rxc7 29. axb6 Rxa3 30. bxc7 Rxa1+ 31. Kg2 Ra8 32. b6) 29. axb6 Bb2 30. Rxa8 Rxa8 31. b7 $18) 28. axb6 $1 Rcb8 $2 ({Black had to try} 28... Rxc3 $1 29. b7 Rf8 30. b8=Q Rxb8 31. Bxb8 Be7 32. Rb1 $16) 29. Bxb8 Rxb8 30. Rxa3 Rxb6 31. Rb3 {The endgame is won for White. The plans are well known and can be found in a lot of textbooks. White will advance his king to the centre, exchange some central pawns and invade on either flank. In the meantime, Black can do nothing active or interfere with White's plan.} Kf8 32. Kf1 Ke7 33. Ke2 Kd6 34. Kd3 e5 $6 ({This move doesn't affect the result but makes White's task easier.} 34... Kc7 35. c4 dxc4+ 36. Kxc4 Rd6 37. Ra3 Kb7 38. g4 {and White is on the right path}) 35. c4 $1 {Opening up the centre can only be to White's benefit} dxc4+ 36. Kxc4 exd4 37. Kxd4 {And White is ready to execute the final phase of his plan (king invasion)} f6 38. Kc4 Kc7 39. Re3 Kd6 40. Re8 {Black resigned, as he was aware of White's winning plan and realized the futility of his efforts} 1-0


