1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 4. Bg5 {Nicolai V. Pedersen: 'White is trying to play in a Trompowsky-inspired way against the Benko, which can be dangerous against an unprepared opponent. Superficially it resembles the line 2 Nf3 c5 3 d5 b5 4 Bg5 Ne4 in Chapter Eight, but here the weakness of the queenside dark squares (due to White's c2-c4) enables Black to obtain immediate counterplay with ...Ne4, ...Qa5+ and ...g7-g5, and in fact has good chances to gain the advantage.'} Ne4 {Nicolai V. Pedersen: '!' Nicolai V. Pedersen: 'The most testing move. White must now be careful not to fall behind in development. The most testing move.' '!'} 5. Bf4 {Nicolai V. Pedersen: '?!' Nicolai V. Pedersen: 'Surprisingly, after this obvious move Black may already have the edge.' '?!'} (5. Bh4 $2 Qa5+ 6. Nd2 g5 {is similar but even worse for White.}) ({Instead, there is} 5. h4 $5 {(a thematic idea from the Trompowsky)} Qa5+ 6. Nd2 $6 (6. Bd2 {is hardly very ambitious, and Black can get an easy game quite comfortably, but it is objectively the best move here; for example,} Nxd2 7. Qxd2 Qxd2+ 8. Nxd2 bxc4 9. Nxc4 d6 10. Nf3 Nd7 11. e4 g6 12. O-O-O Nf6 13. Bd3 Ng4 {with an equal game}) 6... bxc4 7. Qc2 Nxg5 8. hxg5 g6 9. Qc3 $6 (9. e4 Bg7 10. Bxc4 d6 {also gives Black a slight advantage}) 9... Qxc3 10. bxc3 Bg7 11. Rc1 d6 12. e4 Nd7 13. Nxc4 Nb6 14. Nf3 {was played in N.Murshed-D.Sermek, Moscow Olympiad 1994, and was shortly drawn; but after} h5 {Black must be at least slightly better.}) 5... Qa5+ 6. Nd2 g5 $1 7. Be3 {Nicolai V. Pedersen: '?!' Nicolai V. Pedersen: 'After this Black is already slightly better, but other tries are fail to give White anything either:' '?!'} (7. Be5 Rg8 {is examined in Chapter 2. and now:} 8. Z0 (8. Bc7 $6 Qxd2+ {(the simplest and best solution)} 9. Qxd2 Nxd2 10. Kxd2 bxc4 11. e3 Ba6 12. Ne2 d6 {and Black is doing fine.}) (8. b4 $6 {(fighting for the initiative, but objectively not the strongest)} Qxb4 9. Ngf3 (9. Rb1 $2 Qxd2+ {is clearly better for Black}) 9... Qa5 $1 {(planning ...g5-g4, ...d7-d6 and possibly ...b5xc4)} ({the immediate} 9... g4 $6 {allows} 10. Rb1 Nc3 11. Rxb4 Nxd1 12. Rxb5 gxf3 13. exf3 Nxf2 14. Kxf2 d6 15. Ba1 Bh6 16. Ne4 {and White had the edge in N.Murshed-J.Hodgson, London Lloyds Bank 1992}) 10. Qc2 f5 11. Rb1 a6 {and White has very little for the pawn.}) (8. Ngf3 $1 {(this development move, preparing b2-b4, seems the best here)} d6 (8... g4 9. Qc2 $1 f5 10. Nh4 {is also unclear}) 9. b4 cxb4 10. Nxe4 dxe5 11. e3 Nd7 12. cxb5 f5 13. Ng3 Nb6 14. Nd2 (14. Nxe5 $6 b3+ 15. Qd2 Qxd2+ 16. Kxd2 Bg7 {is good for Black}) 14... g4 15. Nb3 Qa3 16. Be2 {and there is still everything to play for.})) (7. Qc2 gxf4 8. Qxe4 bxc4 9. Ngf3 d6 10. Qxf4 Bg7 {and Black's position was preferable in E.Kahn-J.Brustkern, Budapest 2002.}) (7. b4 Qxb4 8. Rb1 Qc3 9. Rb3 {can be met by} Nxf2 $1 (9... Qf6 10. Nxe4 Qxf4 {, as in A.Botsari-So.Polgar, Thessaloniki Olympiad 1988, is less clear after} 11. Qb1 $1) 10. Rxc3 Nxd1 11. Bxb8 Nxc3 12. Be5 Rg8 ({or even} 12... Nxa2 $5 13. Bxh8 b4) 13. Bxc3 b4 14. Bb2 Bg7 15. Bxg7 Rxg7 {, when the queenside pawns give Black the better chances.}) 7... bxc4 8. Qc2 Nf6 ({Even stronger is Nicolai V. Pedersen: 'Also possible was'} 8... f5 $1 {Nicolai V. Pedersen: '!?' '!?'} 9. f3 (9. g4 c3 $1 10. bxc3 Qxc3 $17) 9... Nd6 10. Bxg5 Bg7 $17 11. Bf4 Na6 12. Bxd6 exd6 {and Black is doing fine with his lead in development and the bishop pair.}) 9. Bxg5 $2 {Nicolai V. Pedersen: 'The fourth indifferent move with this piece finally gives Black a clear advantage.'} ({Nicolai V. Pedersen: 'Preferable was'} 9. Qxc4 Bg7 10. Qxc5 (10. Rc1 {, although} Na6 11. Bxc5 Nxc5 12. Qxc5 Qxd2+ 13. Kxd2 Ne4+ {, followed by ...Nxc5 and ...Bxb2, would still be somewhat favourable for Black due to the bishop pair.}) 10... Qxc5 11. Bxc5 Nxd5 $15) 9... Nxd5 10. Qxc4 Nb6 $17 11. Qc3 ({There is no relief after Nicolai V. Pedersen: 'Keeping the queens on with'} 11. Qc2 Bg7 $17 {[%cal Gb8c6] either. This mighty bishop is the main factor in assessing the position in the game as well.} 12. e3 Nc6 {is no improvement for White.}) 11... Qxc3 12. bxc3 Bg7 {Nicolai V. Pedersen: 'Black is clearly better. The bishop on g7 and knight on b6 are working well together, while the b-file is always useful for the rook on a8. Black is clearly better.'} 13. Rc1 Na4 14. Nb1 {Nicolai V. Pedersen: '?!' Nicolai V. Pedersen: 'Very passive;' '?!'} ({it would have been better just to give up the pawn, with} 14. e4 {for instance.}) 14... Nc6 $19 {[%cal Ga8b8] The rest is relatively easy for Black with such supremacy on the queenside.} 15. e4 Rb8 16. Nf3 d6 17. Nfd2 Be6 18. Rc2 Kd7 19. Be2 Rb6 ({The immediate} 19... Rb2 20. Rxb2 ({or} 20. Rc1 Rxa2) 20... Nxb2 21. a3 Rb8 {should also be decisive.}) 20. O-O Rhb8 21. Rfc1 Rb2 ({This simple penetration is devastating,} 21... f5 {is also good.}) 22. a3 Ba2 23. Rxb2 Rxb2 24. Bd1 Nb6 25. f3 Ne5 {Nicolai V. Pedersen: 'White is completely tied down and it could hardly be long before Black won material somewhere. In desperation White gives up two knights for a rook, but it doesn't change the inevitable result.'} 26. Rc2 Rxb1 27. Nxb1 Bxb1 28. Rc1 Bd3 29. a4 Nbc4 30. Bb3 Na5 31. Ba2 c4 32. Be3 Nec6 33. Bb1 Bxb1 34. Rxb1 Nb3 35. Rb2 Bxc3 36. Rc2 Bd4 {Nicolai V. Pedersen: '. --- Game summary: The bishop's excursion to g5 doesn't achieve a great deal in the Benko. In fact, as we saw in the game, Black can just use it as a target to generate counterplay by ...Ne4 and ...g7-g5. By the time Grivas had made four moves with this bishop in the opening, Khalifman had obtained a clear advantage as Black and went on to win comfortably. --- Although White still has a few ways of achieving equality after 4 Bg5, I don't think we will see much of this line in the future. If White really wants to play in this style, it is better to play Bg5 on move two.'} 0-1


