1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 dxc4 5. e3 b5 6. a4 b4 7. Nb1 Ba6 8. Be2 e6 9. Nbd2 $6 c3 $1 10. bxc3 bxc3 ({The natural follow-up, as the} 10... Nd5 $6 11. Bxa6 Nxc3 (11... Nxa6 $6 12. c4 Nf6 13. c5 $16) 12. Qc2 Nxa6 13. Bb2 (13. Ne4 $2 b3 $1 14. Qd3 Nxe4 15. Qxe4 Qd5 $17 {Hackel,M-Reefschlaeger,H Germany 2005}) 13... c5 14. Bxc3 bxc3 15. Qxc3 Rc8 16. Qc4 $1 Nb4 17. O-O cxd4 18. Qb5+ Qd7 19. Nxd4 $14 {fails to satisfy Black.}) 11. Nb1 Bb4 $1 ({Best, as now Black's dark-squared bishop can be developed to a much better square, also protecting his extra pawn.} 11... Bxe2 $6 {is not accurate:} 12. Qxe2 Nbd7 (12... Bb4 13. Qc4 Qa5 14. Ba3) 13. O-O $1 (13. Nxc3 Bb4 14. Bd2 Qa5 15. Qd3 (15. Nb1 Rb8 16. O-O O-O 17. Rc1 c5 $11 {Blees,A-Hector,J Katerini 1992}) 15... O-O 16. O-O Rfd8 17. Ne4 c5 $11) 13... Be7 14. Ba3 O-O 15. Nxc3 c5 16. Rfd1 cxd4 17. Nxd4 $14 {Kapnisis,S-Kokolias,K Kavala 2004.}) 12. O-O c5 13. Ba3 O-O 14. Bxa6 Nxa6 15. Qd3 Qa5 16. Rc1 Rfc8 ({Black's alternatives are: a)} 16... Nd5 17. Qb5 Qb6 (17... Rab8 18. Bxb4 Rxb5 (18... Qxb5 19. axb5 cxb4 20. Rxa6 Rxb5 21. Rxa7 h6 (21... b3 $2 22. e4 $18) 22. Ne5 $14) 19. Bxa5 Rxa5 20. Nxc3 Nxc3 21. Rxc3 Rb8 22. Kf1 $11) 18. dxc5 Nxc5 19. Bxb4 Nxb4 20. Rxc3 Rac8 21. Na3 (21. Nbd2 Nxa4) 21... Rfd8 22. a5 $13 {.}) ({b)} 16... Rac8 17. Qb5 Nd5 18. Bxb4 Qxb5 19. axb5 Naxb4 20. Nxc3 Nxc3 21. Rxc3 cxd4 22. Rb3 a5 23. bxa6 (23. g3 $5 dxe3 (23... Ra8 24. Nxd4 $14) 24. Rxa5 exf2+ 25. Kxf2 $44) 23... Nxa6 24. Nxd4 Nc5 $11 {.}) ({c)} 16... Rfd8 17. Nxc3 cxd4 18. Nxd4 Bxa3 19. Rxa3 e5 20. Qf5 $1 (20. Qb5 $2 Qxb5 21. Ndxb5 Nc5 $17) 20... Qc5 (20... Rac8 21. Nde2 Nd5 22. Qb1 $11) 21. Ndb5 Nb4 (21... e4 22. Qxc5 Nxc5 23. Nd4 $11) 22. h3 (22. Rb3 Nd3 23. Rcb1 a6 24. Na3 Rac8 25. h3 e4 26. Qxc5 Nxc5 27. Rb6 Kf8 $17) 22... a6 23. Ne2 $1 Qe7 24. Nc7 (24. Nbc3 Nd3 25. Rca1 Rab8 26. Ne4 Nxe4 27. Qxe4 Rb4 28. Qc6 Rb2 29. Qxa6 e4 30. Nf4 Nxf2 31. R3a2 Rxa2 32. Rxa2 $13) 24... Ra7 (24... Nbd5 25. Nxa8 Qxa3 26. Nc7 Nxc7 27. Rxc7 Qxa4 28. Rc8 Re8 29. Nc3 $11) 25. Rb3 Na2 26. Ra1 Rxc7 27. Rxa2 $11 {.}) 17. Nxc3 cxd4 ({Another Black's option is} 17... Bxa3 18. Rxa3 cxd4 19. Nxd4 Rab8 {and it must be 'better' as White must be on the alert in order to keep the equilibrium:} 20. Rb3 $5 (20. Qd1 Nb4 21. Ncb5 $6 (21. Na2 Rxc1 22. Qxc1 Nxa2 23. Rxa2 $11) 21... a6 22. Nc3 $6 (22. Rxc8+ Rxc8 23. Nd6 Rc7 $15) 22... Rd8 23. Qf3 Nd3 24. Rca1 Ne5 25. Qd1 Rbc8 $17 {Socko,M-Zhukova,N Groningen 1998}) 20... Qxa4 (20... Nb4 21. Qd1 a6 22. Rcb1 $13) 21. Qf1 Qa5 (21... Qc4 22. Nce2 Qd5 23. Rxb8 Rxb8 24. Nc6 Re8 25. Nf4 Qd2 26. Rd1 Qc2 27. Rc1 Qa4 28. Nxa7 $11) 22. Ncb5 Rxc1 23. Qxc1 h6 24. Rb1 $1 Nb4 25. Ra1 $11 {.}) 18. Bxb4 Nxb4 19. Qxd4 Rd8 ({Equally good is} 19... Qc5 20. Qxc5 Rxc5 21. Nb5 Ne4 22. Rxc5 Nxc5 23. Ne5 f6 24. Nc4 Nc6 $11 {.}) 20. Qe5 Qxe5 ({Or} 20... Nfd5 21. Nxd5 Rxd5 22. Qc3 Rad8 23. Rab1 Nd3 24. Qxa5 Rxa5 25. Rd1 h6 26. Ne1 Rad5 $11 {.}) 21. Nxe5 Rac8 $6 ({Black could keep an equal game by exchanging the strong e5-knight for his 'useless' f6-knight:} 21... Nd7 $1 22. Nxd7 Rxd7 23. Ne4 Nd3 24. Nc5 Nxc5 25. Rxc5 Kf8 $11 {but not by exchanging his other knight with}) (21... Nd3 $6 22. Nxd3 Rxd3 23. Nb5 Kf8 24. Rc7 a6 25. Nd4 Nd5 26. Rb7 $14 {.}) 22. Nb5 $1 a6 $2 ({A terrible mistake. Black could not defend also with} 22... Nfd5 $2 23. Rxc8 Rxc8 24. Nxf7 a6 25. Nbd6 Rc2 26. Ng5 $16 {but he should do it with}) (22... Rxc1+ 23. Rxc1 Nfd5 $1 (23... a6 $2 24. Nd6 $16) 24. Kf1 $1 $14 (24. Nxa7 $6 Nc3 25. Kf1 Nxa4 26. Rc7 f6 27. Nac6 Nxc6 28. Nxc6 Rd1+ 29. Ke2 Nc3+ 30. Kf3 Nd5 $11 {.})) 23. Nd6 $1 Nc2 $2 {Black was shocked and he did not find the most stubborn defence with} (23... Rxc1+ 24. Rxc1 Na2 25. Rc6 (25. Rc4 $2 Ne4 $3) 25... Ne8 26. Nexf7 Rb8 27. Kf1 Nb4 28. Rc1 $16 {. Actually, his last move is a blunder.}) 24. Nxc8 Nxa1 25. Ne7+ Kf8 26. Rxa1 $1 {Simple and effective.} ({Black was only counting on} 26. N7c6 $2 Nb3 {although White still keeps some advantage:} 27. Nxd8 Nxc1 28. Ndxf7 {.}) 26... Kxe7 27. Nc6+ Kd7 28. Nxd8 Kxd8 29. Kf1 Kc7 30. Rb1 Ne4 31. Rb4 1-0


