1. d4 {Grivas} Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. g3 Ba6 5. Qb3 c6 6. Bg5 $1 ({The automatic} 6. Bg2 d5 {would fully justify Black's last move. Since the h1-a8 diagonal will be blocked after ...d5, the white bishop will have no targets on g2.}) 6... d5 (6... Be7 7. Nc3 d5 (7... O-O 8. e4 $16) 8. Bxf6 Bxf6 9. e4 Bb7 (9... dxc4 10. Bxc4 b5 11. Be2 $16 Bxd4 $6 12. O-O-O $18 {Postl,A-Hentunen,A/Izmir 2004}) 10. cxd5 cxd5 11. Bb5+ $16 {Tunik,G-Sorokin,M/Sochi 2004.}) 7. cxd5 $1 cxd5 (7... exd5 8. Bxf6 $1 Qxf6 9. Nc3 Nd7 (9... Bd6 10. Bg2 O-O 11. O-O Bc4 12. Qc2 Nd7 13. Rfe1 $14 {Marques,V-Comp Shredder 7/Vicente Lopez 2003}) 10. Bg2 {followed by 0-0, fe1 and e4 promises a nice advantage to White.}) 8. e3 $1 (8. Bxf6 Qxf6 9. Nc3 Qe7 $1 (9... Qd8 $6 10. Ne5 Bd6 11. Qa4+ Kf8 12. e4 $16 {Kulaots,K-Alekseev,E/Moscow 2004}) 10. a3 Qb7 11. Bg2 Nd7 12. O-O Be7 $11 {Halkias,S-Postny,E/Mureck 1998.}) 8... Bxf1 9. Kxf1 Be7 10. Kg2 Nc6 ({Seems best. Black has also tried: a)} 10... Nbd7 $6 11. Rc1 O-O 12. Nc3 a6 13. Na4 b5 14. Bxf6 Nxf6 15. Nc5 $16 {.}) ({b)} 10... h6 $6 11. Bxf6 Bxf6 12. Rc1 O-O 13. Nc3 Qd7 14. Rc2 Nc6 15. Qa4 Rfc8 16. Rac1 $16 {Grivas,E-Tsouktakos,N/Athens 2004.}) ({c)} 10... O-O 11. Nc3 $6 (11. Rc1 $1 Nbd7 12. Nc3 Ne4 13. Bxe7 Qxe7 14. Rc2 $14) 11... Nc6 12. Rhc1 Qd7 13. Qa4 Rfc8 $11 {Grivas,E-Ivanchuk,V/Iraklion blz 2004.}) 11. Rc1 Na5 12. Qb5+ $1 Qd7 13. Qa6 $1 {Threatening 14.e5!.} Bd6 14. Bxf6 gxf6 15. Nc3 Qb7 16. Qe2 ({The exchange of queens would significantly relieve Black (} 16. Qxb7 $2 Nxb7 17. Nb5 Kd7 $1 {), who now faces a multitude of problems: not only must he cater for the c-file, but also for his kingside weaknesses.}) 16... O-O 17. Rc2 $1 {What we practically have here is a case of an outpost (the c3-knight) very close to the white camp. White will double rooks on the c-file and at the same time develop an initiative on the flank where the exposed black king resides. At the appropriate moment the outpost will be removed in such a way that Black will be unable to defend against all of White's threats. Simple plan, but the execution is difficult!} Rac8 18. Rac1 Kg7 19. Ne1 $1 {A strong move, aiming at the transfer of the knight(s) to the f4-square; from there, in combination with the approach of the white queen (h5) they will be able to create direct threats against the black king.} f5 20. Nd3 Nc4 $6 ({This appears strong, but in reality only serves to complicate Black's defensive task, as this knight works as a second outpost for White. Better is} 20... Nc6 {and ...e7, assigning the knight to the defence of the king.}) 21. Qh5 h6 22. Ne2 $1 Qa6 $2 ({With the false impression of imminent material gain, thanks to the double threat 23...xa2 and 23...xe3+. The defensive} 22... Qd7 {was essential.}) 23. Nef4 $1 Be7 (23... Qxa2 {is no improvement:} 24. Qh4 $1 Rc7 25. Nh5+ Kh7 26. Nf6+ Kg7 27. Nf4 Rfc8 (27... Bxf4 28. gxf4 {intending g1 and h3+}) 28. Kh1 $1 Be7 29. g4 $1 {.}) 24. b3 Nd6 25. Ne5 $1 Bg5 ({This move loses in spectacular fashion, but anyway there was no salvation. Black could not free his position by} 25... Rxc2 26. Rxc2 Rc8 {in view of} 27. Nxf7 Nxf7 (27... Rxc2 28. Qg6+ Kf8 29. Nxe6+ Ke8 30. Ne5+ $1) 28. Qg6+ Kf8 (28... Kh8 29. Rxc8+ Qxc8 30. Qxf7) 29. Nxe6+ Ke8 30. Rc7 {, winning for White.}) 26. Nxe6+ $3 {White's great positional superiority creates the basic requirements for tactical combinations!} fxe6 27. Rc7+ Kh8 28. Qg6 {Black cannot avoid checkmate.} 1-0


