1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nbd2 Bf5 5. g3 Nbd7 6. Bg2 Qc7 $6 ({Black's idea of an early central pawn advance should find no followers. Instead of the text-move he should try: a)} 6... e6 7. O-O (7. Nh4 Bg6 (7... Bg4 $5) 8. O-O Be7 9. cxd5 exd5 10. Nxg6 hxg6 11. e4 $14 {Balinov,I-Draganova,P/Sunny Beach 2005}) (7. Qb3 Qc7 8. O-O Be7 9. h3 O-O 10. Nh4 Bg6 11. Nxg6 hxg6 12. e4 $14 {Stehlik,J-Pfeffer,D/Stare Mesto 2007}) 7... Bd6 (7... Be7 8. b3 Ne4 (8... O-O 9. Bb2 Ne4 10. Rc1 Qa5 11. a3 b5 $11 {Peredy,F-Bartha,S/Hungary 1994}) 9. Bb2 h5 10. Ne5 Nxe5 11. dxe5 h4 12. Nxe4 dxe4 13. Qxd8+ Rxd8 14. Rfd1 O-O $11 {Levitan,Y-Bijoux,C/Jakarta 1993}) 8. Nh4 (8. Re1 O-O 9. Nh4 Bg4 10. Qc2 e5 11. dxe5 Nxe5 12. cxd5 Nxd5 13. Ne4 Be7 $11 {Mueller,W-Karl,H/Hockenheim 2007}) 8... O-O (8... Bg4 9. Qb3 Qb6 10. c5 Qxb3 11. Nxb3 Bc7 12. f3 Bh5 13. g4 Bg6 14. g5 Ng8 15. Bd2 $13) 9. Nxf5 exf5 10. Qb3 $14 {Kurajica,B-Marin,L/Benasque 1997.}) ({b)} 6... h6 $1 {as you may easily understand it is important for Black to preserve his light-squared bishop, especially on the diagonal b1-h7} 7. O-O e6 8. b3 Be7 (8... Ne4 9. Bb2 Be7 10. Nxe4 Bxe4 11. Qc1 O-O 12. Re1 Rc8 {½-½ Slobodjan,R-Rabiega,R/Berlin 1999}) (8... Bd6 9. Bb2 Qb8 10. Qc1 (10. e3 O-O 11. Qe2 b5 12. c5 Bc7 13. Nh4 Bh7 14. f4 $13 Ne4 $2 15. Nxe4 Bxe4 16. Bxe4 dxe4 17. d5 $1 $16 {Kurajica,B-Gonzalez de la Torre,S/Mondariz 2000}) 10... a5 11. a3 O-O 12. Qc3 b5 $11 {Hort,V-Pelletier,Y/Zuerich 1999}) (8... Bb4 9. Bb2 O-O 10. a3 Ba5 11. Rc1 Re8 12. b4 Bc7 13. Re1 a5 14. Qb3 axb4 15. axb4 Ne4 $11 {Tin,H-May Aung Hlaing/Yangon 1999}) 9. Bb2 O-O 10. Ne5 (10. h3 Ne4 (10... Bh7 11. Ne5 Rc8 12. Kh2 b5 13. c5 a5 14. a3 Ne4 15. Ndf3 f6 16. Nxd7 Qxd7 17. Ne1 Bd8 18. f3 Ng5 19. Nd3 Bc7 20. h4 Nf7 21. e4 Rcd8 22. Nf2 {½-½ Rashkovsky,N-Popov,R/Krasnodar 1997}) 11. Nh2 Ndf6 12. Ndf3 a5 13. Ne5 a4 14. g4 Bh7 $15 {Del Rio Angelis,S-Perez,R/Linares 2002}) (10. e3 a5 11. Qe2 a4 12. Rfc1 Ne4 13. Nxe4 Bxe4 14. Bc3 Nf6 15. c5 Nd7 16. b4 Bf6 $11 {Hort,V-Illescas Cordoba,M/Tilburg 1992}) 10... a5 (10... Nxe5 11. dxe5 Ne4 $1 (11... Nd7 12. cxd5 cxd5 13. e4 dxe4 14. Nxe4 Bxe4 15. Bxe4 $14 {Vaulin,A-Grabarczyk,M/Pardubice 1994}) 12. Nxe4 dxe4 13. Qd4 Qxd4 14. Bxd4 Rfd8 15. Rad1 Kf8 16. Be3 Ke8 17. f4 exf3 18. exf3 Rxd1 19. Rxd1 Rd8 20. Rxd8+ Kxd8 21. Bxa7 Bb1 22. c5 Bxa2 23. b4 Kc8 24. Bf1 f6 {½-½ Van der Sterren,P-Cuijpers,F/Roosendaal 1983}) 11. Nxd7 Qxd7 12. Nf3 b5 $11 {Koch,E-Hoenig,A/Germany 1998.}) 7. O-O e5 $6 (7... e6 $14 {is a must.}) 8. Nxe5 Nxe5 9. dxe5 Qxe5 10. cxd5 cxd5 11. Nf3 Qc7 12. Nd4 (12. Bf4 Bd6 13. Rc1 Qe7 14. Nd4 Bd7 15. Bg5 $16 {Drabek,M-Domlatil,J/Czech Rep. 1999.}) 12... Bd7 13. Bf4 Bd6 14. Rc1 Qb6 15. Bxd6 Qxd6 16. Qb3 O-O {White holds a pleasant advantage due to the weak isolated black d5-pawn and his better placed pieces. Important is also the fact that Black cannot become active, thus he cannot claim any compensation for his inferior pawn-structure.} 17. Rfd1 (17. Qxb7 $2 {can only help Black:} Rfb8 18. Qc7 Qxc7 19. Rxc7 Rxb2 20. a3 Be6 $14 {but maybe}) (17. e3 b6 18. Rc2 $16 {is a fair alternative try.}) 17... Rfe8 18. Nb5 $1 {Although the white knight seems to be a better piece than the black d7-bishop, the latter can defend the isolani, so it is not a bad idea at all to exchange it. When playing against the isolani, most of the time it is a good idea to exchange the light pieces.} Bxb5 19. Qxb5 Rad8 $2 ({Although Black's position is difficult, his last move loses material. He should opt for} 19... Qb6 20. Qxb6 axb6 21. Rc2 Rxa2 22. Bxd5 Nxd5 23. Rxd5 $16 {or}) (19... a6 20. Qd3 Qe5 21. Rd2 Rad8 22. Rdc2 $16 {.}) 20. Qxb7 $1 Rxe2 ({The main alternative is} 20... Rb8 21. Qxa7 Rxb2 22. Bf3 Qf8 $1 23. Rb1 $1 Rc2 (23... Ra8 24. Qxa8 Qxa8 25. Rxb2) (23... Rxb1 24. Rxb1 Ra8 25. Qc7 $16 Rxa2 $4 26. Rb8) 24. Qa4 $1 $16 {.}) 21. Bxd5 $1 {An easy combination which wins material; the useless d5 isolani!} Rd7 ({All the alternatives equally lose:} 21... Nxd5 22. Rxd5 Qxd5 (22... Qf8 23. Rxd8 Qxd8 24. Rc8) 23. Qxd5 Rxd5 24. Rc8+) (21... Re7 22. Bxf7+ Kxf7 23. Rxd6 Rxb7 24. Rxd8) (21... Kh8 22. Bb3 Rd2 23. Rxd2 Qxd2 24. Rd1 Qa5 25. Rxd8+ Qxd8 26. Qxa7 {.}) 22. Rc8+ Re8 (22... Ne8 23. Bxf7+ Rxf7 24. Rxe8+ Rxe8 25. Qxf7+ Kxf7 26. Rxd6 $18 {.}) 23. Rxe8+ Nxe8 24. Qc8 Kf8 (24... Qe7 25. Bxf7+ Qxf7 26. Rxd7 {.}) 25. Bf3 {Black resigned as after} (25. Bf3 Qxd1+ 26. Bxd1 Rxd1+ 27. Kg2 Rd6 28. b4 a6 29. a4 {White's material advantage will tell in the end.}) 1-0


