) 17. Nxh7 Bc5 $1 (17... Ba6 18. Nxf8 Bxd3 19. Ne6 Nxe6 20. Rxe6 $16) 18. Nxf8 Qxf8 19. Nf3 $1 (19. Nf1 Bc8 $1 20. Ne3 a4 $1 $44) 19... Ng4 (19... Nxf3+ 20. Qxf3 Ne4 21. Bxe4 dxe4 22. Qxf8+ Rxf8 23. Be3 $18) 20. Bf4 Ne6 $5 (20... Nxf3+ 21. Qxf3 Bxf2+ 22. Kg2 Bxe1 23. Qxg4 $18) 21. Ne5 $1 (21. Nh4 Bxf2+ 22. Kf1 $18 {Tkachiev,V-Sulskis,S/Istanbul 2003}) 21... Bxf2+ 22. Kf1 Nxh2+ 23. Kxf2 Nxf4 24. Kg1 Qc5+ 25. Kh1 Nxd3 26. Nxd3 $18) 16. h3 Nh6 17. b4 Nf5 $5 (17... Bf6 18. Nb3 Qd7 19. Qc2 Qxh3 20. Bxh6 gxh6 (20... Qxh6 21. Kg2 $18) 21. b5 $16 {Laznicka,V-Polak,T/Czech Rep. 2006}) 18. Bb2 a6 19. Rc1 $14 {.}) 8. Qc2 c5 $146 ({White keeps a slight advantage also with the other options: a)} 8... Bb4 {Ü 43/(666)} 9. Bd3 c5 (9... O-O 10. O-O Bxd2 11. Bxd2 d5 12. cxd5 exd5 13. e5 Ne4 14. Bxa5 bxa5 15. Nd2 $16 {Tancik,K-Mirkovic,S/Vrnjacka Banja 2006}) 10. dxc5 (10. a3 $5 Bxd2+ 11. Bxd2 b5 $1 12. b3 cxd4 13. Nxd4 bxc4 14. bxc4 Nc6 15. Nxc6 Bxc6 16. O-O $14) 10... Bxc5 11. O-O Rc8 12. Qd1 Ng4 13. a3 Qf6 14. Rb1 Nc6 15. b4 Bd6 16. Bb2 $14 {Barlov,D-Benjamin,J/New York 1987.}) ({b)} 8... d5 9. cxd5 exd5 10. e5 Ne4 11. Bb5+ c6 12. Bd3 f5 13. exf6 Qxf6 14. O-O Nxd2 15. Nxd2 O-O-O (15... Qxd4 $2 16. Nf3 Qc5 17. Re1+ Be7 18. b4 $1 $18) 16. Bf5+ Kb8 17. Nf3 h6 18. Ne5 $14 {Sargissian,G-Shetty,R/Dubai 2005.}) 9. e5 $5 ({White could instead play} 9. d5 $5 $14 {, with a slightly better and secure position:} exd5 10. exd5 Bd6 11. Bd3 $14 {.}) 9... Ng4 10. h3 Nh6 11. Ne4 Bxe4 $2 ({Black had to play} 11... Nf5 $1 12. Bg5 Qb8 (12... Be7 13. Bxe7 Qxe7 14. dxc5 bxc5 15. g4 $1 $16 Nd4 16. Nxd4 cxd4 17. O-O-O O-O 18. f4 $14) 13. dxc5 (13. d5 $1 exd5 14. cxd5 Bxd5 15. O-O-O $1 Bxa2 16. Bb5 $1 $18) 13... Bxc5 14. O-O-O Bxf2 15. Qxf2 Bxe4 16. g4 $44) ({but not} 11... f5 $6 12. exf6 gxf6 13. Bxh6 (13. Bg2 $13) 13... Bxh6 14. Nd6+ Ke7 15. Nxb7 Nxb7 16. Bg2 $16 {.}) 12. Qxe4 cxd4 13. Bxh6 gxh6 14. O-O-O Rc8 15. Kb1 $3 ({A very strong move, after which Black cannot continue with 15...xc4 16.xd4 b5 (16...a5 17.b5 and ad1, with powerful pressure on the backward d7-pawn) 17.xc4 bxc4 18.xc4 +/-. The immediate} 15. Rxd4 $6 Bc5 $1 16. Rd2 b5 $1 $13 {would give Black plenty of hope.}) 15... Bg7 $6 ({White retains his advantage after} 15... Nc6 $1 16. Nxd4 Nxd4 17. Rxd4 Bc5 18. Rd2 Qc7 {thanks to the backward d7-pawn and the weakened black king, but this line had to be preferred anyway.}) (15... Nxc4 16. Rxd4 b5 (16... Na5 17. Bb5 { Rhd1}) 17. Bxc4 bxc4 18. Rxc4 $16) 16. Nxd4 $1 f5 17. Qe3 $1 Qe7 ({Naturally,} 17... Nxc4 $2 18. Bxc4 Rxc4 19. Nxe6 $1 {would be disastrous for Black.}) 18. Nb5 $1 O-O 19. Nd6 Rc7 {White has an excellent position, having fixed the backward black d-pawn with both knight and pawn. Moreover, White's overall pawn structure is superior and he has a significant space advantage. As a result of the above, his position is almost winning. The only thing White must cater for is possible counterplay by means of 20...f4!? 21.gxf4 h4.} 20. f4 $1 $16 {Not only stopping the aforementioned counterplay but also preparing h2-d2!, increasing the pressure on the backward d-pawn. The f1-bishop will be developed later, wherever and whenever it will be necessary.} Nb7 {Threatening 21...xd6! 22.exd6? f6!.} 21. Rh2 $1 Qd8 ({Black is hardly in an enviable position, but could at least prolong the game with} 21... Nc5 {.}) 22. Nb5 $1 Rc5 23. Qf3 $1 Rxb5 ({And at the same time Black resigned, in view of} 23... Rxb5 24. Qxb7 $1 Rc5 25. Rxd7 {.}) ({No relief was offered by} 23... Na5 24. b4) ({or} 23... Qb8 24. Rxd7 Rf7 25. Rxf7 Kxf7 26. Qxb7+ $1 {.}) 1-0


