1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Be2 e5 7. Be3 exd4 8. Nxd4 Re8 9. f3 c6 10. Bf2 a6 11. O-O b5 12. a3 Nh5 $5 {A rather unexplored try, but with similar motives.} 13. Qd2 Qf6 $6 ({As the text move loses precious time I cannot really suggest it.} 13... Bb7 {is natural.}) 14. g3 $6 ({There is no need to weaken the king. White could 'safely' go for} 14. Be3 $1 Nf4 15. Rfd1 $1 (15. cxb5 $6 Nxe2+ (15... axb5 16. Bxb5 cxb5 17. Ndxb5 Ne6 18. Nxd6 Rd8 (18... Qd8 $6 19. Nxe8 Qxe8 20. Nd5 Ba6 21. Rfd1 Nd7 22. Rac1 $16) 19. Nd5 Qxb2 20. Nxc8 Qxd2 21. Nce7+ Kf8 22. Bxd2 Bd4+ 23. Kh1 Bxa1 24. Rxa1 Nd7 $14) 16. Ndxe2 axb5 17. Bd4 Qe7 18. Bxg7 Kxg7 19. Rad1 Rd8 $14) 15... Nxe2+ 16. Ndxe2 bxc4 17. Bd4 Qe7 18. Bxg7 Kxg7 19. Qxd6 $16 {.}) 14... Bh3 $6 (14... bxc4 $1 15. Bxc4 c5 16. Nc2 Nc6 $13 {was another choice.}) 15. Rfe1 bxc4 16. Be3 $6 ({Now this is not the best. White should have played} 16. Bxc4 Nd7 (16... c5 17. e5 $1 Rxe5 18. Rxe5 dxe5 19. Ne4 Qd8 20. Nb3 Qxd2 21. Nbxd2 $14) 17. f4 Nb6 18. Be2 c5 19. Nf3 Bg4 20. Rad1 $14 {.}) 16... d5 $1 17. Nc2 Nd7 $1 ({Completing the development. White's activity should have been proved great after} 17... dxe4 $2 18. Nxe4 Qxb2 19. Bxc4 $16 {.}) 18. g4 $6 ({A 'logical' but dangerous continuation. The other option was} 18. exd5 cxd5 (18... Ne5 $5 19. f4 Nd3 20. Bxd3 cxd3 21. Qxd3 Bf5 22. Qd2 Bxc2 23. Qxc2 cxd5 $13) 19. Nxd5 (19. g4 Rab8 $1 $13) 19... Qxb2 $13 {.}) 18... Ne5 $1 ({This is Black's main idea to compensate for his lost h5-knight.} 18... Rab8 $5 {was also interesting.}) 19. gxh5 (19. Nd4 $2 Nf4 $1 20. Bxf4 Nd3 $1 21. Be3 Qxd4 $17 {is a nice and instructive example of Black's attacking possibilities.}) 19... Nxf3+ $6 ({Black had a better continuation at his disposal:} 19... dxe4 $1 20. Nxe4 (20. fxe4 $2 Rad8 $17 {or}) (20. Bg5 Nxf3+ 21. Bxf3 Qxf3 $44) 20... Nxf3+ 21. Bxf3 Qxf3 22. Ng5 Qxh5 23. Nxh3 Qxh3 {where White faces problems.}) 20. Bxf3 Qxf3 21. Qf2 ({White could have 'forced' a draw with} 21. Bd4 Qg4+ 22. Kh1 Qf3+ $11 {or tried for more with}) (21. Qe2 {but probably Black should feel happy:} Qxe2 22. Rxe2 Rab8 $44 {.}) 21... Qxh5 {Black's compensation for the sacrificed piece is obvious: three strong pawns and a weak white king.} 22. exd5 (22. Bd4 $5 Qg4+ 23. Kh1 dxe4 24. Bxg7 Kxg7 $13 {.}) 22... cxd5 23. Bd4 Re6 ({Black could have opted for} 23... Qg4+ 24. Kh1 Qf5 25. Kg1 Reb8 $5 $44 {or}) (23... Rab8 $5 $44 {.}) 24. Bxg7 Kxg7 25. Nd4 ({The alternative was} 25. Qd4+ Kg8 (25... Kh6 $6 26. Re3 Bf5 27. Nb4 $14) 26. Qxd5 Qg4+ 27. Kh1 Rb8 28. Rg1 Qf5 29. Qxf5 Bxf5 $44 {.}) 25... Qg4+ 26. Kh1 Rf6 27. Qg1 Rb8 $1 28. Re2 $1 (28. Qxg4 $2 Bxg4 29. Nxd5 Rd6 30. Re4 f5 31. Re5 Rxb2 $17 {.}) 28... Rf4 29. Qxg4 Rxg4 ({Black could consider sacrificing a rook with} 29... Bxg4 $5 30. Rd2 Rxb2 $1 31. Rxb2 Rxd4 $44 {with excellent compensation.}) 30. Rd2 $6 ({Forcing the draw by} 30. Nc6 Rb6 31. Ne5 Rd4 32. Nf3 Rd3 33. Ne5 {was the safest alternative.}) 30... Re8 ({Interesting was} 30... Bg2+ $5 31. Rxg2 Rxd4 32. Rd1 Rxd1+ 33. Nxd1 d4 $44 {.}) 31. Rg1 $6 ({Now, due to mutual time trouble a series of inaccurate moves started. The obvious continuation was} 31. Nc2 Rb8 $11 32. Nd4 Bg2+ $5 {.}) 31... Rh4 $2 (31... Bg2+ $1 32. Rdxg2 Rxd4 $15 {.}) 32. Nf3 $2 (32. Nxd5 $16 {.}) 32... Rf4 33. Nd4 Re5 $2 (33... Be6 $1 $44 {was a must, as now White has the upper hand.}) 34. Nc6 $16 Re6 35. Nxd5 Rf3 $2 {Time trouble can be cruel and a close friend of disaster...} 36. Nd4 Ree3 37. Nxf3 Rxf3 38. Nb6 Rf6 39. Nxc4 Bc8 40. Nd6 Bd7 41. Rc1 Bh3 $6 42. Ne8+ 1-0


