1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. f3 a6 6. Be3 c6 7. Bd3 b5 8. Nge2 Nbd7 9. b3 O-O 10. Qd2 bxc4 (10... e5 11. d5 b4 (11... cxd5 12. cxd5 Nc5 13. Bc2 Nh5 (13... b4 14. Na4 Nxa4 15. bxa4 Rb8 16. Rb1 Qc7 17. O-O Nd7 18. Rfc1 $14) 14. O-O f5 15. b4 Nd7 16. exf5 gxf5 17. Rac1 Nb6 18. Bb3 Nf6 19. Kh1 f4 20. Bxb6 Qxb6 21. Bc2 Qe3 22. Qxe3 fxe3 {½-½ Timman,J-Petrosian,T/Rio de Janeiro IZT 1979}) 12. Na4 cxd5 13. cxd5 Nxd5 14. Bg5 N5f6 (14... Qa5 15. O-O Nf4 16. Be7 Bh6 17. Kh1 Re8 18. Bxd6 Nxd3 19. Qxd3 Qb5 $11) 15. Qxb4 h6 16. Bh4 d5 17. O-O a5 18. Qd6 Bb7 19. exd5 Re8 20. Rac1 Bxd5 $11 {Lane,G-Reilly,T/Queenstown 2006}) 11. bxc4 (11. Bxc4 Bb7 (11... a5 12. Rc1 Nb6 13. Bd3 Ba6 14. Nb1 Qd7 15. O-O Qb7 16. Bxa6 {½-½ Belotti,B-Hug,W/Istanbul OL 2000}) 12. O-O d5 13. Bd3 dxe4 14. Nxe4 Nd5 15. Bh6 Qb6 16. Bxg7 Kxg7 17. Bc4 Rad8 18. Kh1 N5f6 19. Nxf6 {½-½ Sakaev,K-Yrjola,J/Helsinki 1992}) 11... c5 12. O-O (12. d5 $6 Ne5 13. Nc1 Nfd7 14. f4 Nxd3+ 15. Nxd3 Qa5 $15 {Hausner,I-Hulshof,P/Benasque 1999}) 12... cxd4 13. Nxd4 (13. Bxd4 Nc5 (13... Rb8 14. Rab1 Rxb1 15. Rxb1 e6 $11) 14. e5 Nfd7 15. exd6 Bxd4+ 16. Nxd4 Ne5 17. Be2 Qxd6 $13) 13... Ne5 14. Be2 Bd7 (14... e6 $5) 15. Nd5 Nc6 (15... e6 16. Nxf6+ Bxf6 17. f4 Nc6 18. Rab1 Qc7 19. Nb3 $14) 16. Rab1 Nxd4 17. Bxd4 Nxd5 18. Bxg7 (18. cxd5 Bxd4+ 19. Qxd4 Qa5 $11) 18... Kxg7 19. cxd5 Qc7 20. Qd4+ f6 21. Rfc1 Qa7 22. Qxa7 Rxa7 23. Rb6 {A very interesting position, that at first glance seems to be favourable for White, due to his possession of the only open files (b- and c-). However, the battlefield is not restricted to the open files, but also includes the part of the board where Black has a fundamental breakthrough, the f5-square.} Bb5 $1 24. Rc2 $2 ({White had to avoid} 24. Bxb5 $6 axb5 25. Rc2 Rfa8 26. Rxb5 Rxa2 27. Rbb2 Ra1+ 28. Kf2 f5 $1 {, when Black would have the initiative and some winning chances, but he should have preferred}) (24. Kf2) ({or even} 24. Bd1 $5 {, with equal chances}) 24... Bxe2 25. Rxe2 Rc8 $1 26. Kf2 Rc5 $1 ({Preparing the ...f5 break, as the immediate} 26... f5 27. e5 $1 dxe5 28. Re6 {would not trouble White}) 27. Reb2 f5 28. Rc6 ({After} 28. Rb7 $2 Rxb7 29. Rxb7 Rc2+ 30. Kg3 Kf6 {White would be facing multiple problems}) 28... Ra5 $1 29. Rc4 Rb5 $1 {[White was threatening 30.a4!, locking in the Ra5. Black will now be able to use the "shy" a7-rook as well]} 30. Rbb4 (30. Rxb5 $2 axb5 31. Rc2 fxe4 32. fxe4 Kf6 {would bring Black a quick victory, as the white pawns on a2 and e4 will prove very weak and one of them will soon be captured}) 30... Rab7 31. a3 a5 $1 32. Rxb5 Rxb5 33. Rc7 Kf6 34. Ra7 Rc5 35. g3 h5 36. h4 $2 ({White's position is clearly inferior, but after his last move it becomes easily lost. A better try was} 36. Kg2 fxe4 37. fxe4 g5 $1 38. Kg1 g4 39. Kg2 Rc4 40. Rxa5 Rxe4 {with an obvious advantage for Black, who however will have to prove it}) 36... Rc2+ $1 37. Kg1 Rc3 $1 38. Rxa5 Rxf3 39. exf5 Rxg3+ 40. Kh2 Rg4 41. fxg6 Rxh4+ 42. Kg3 Rg4+ 43. Kh3 Kxg6 0-1


