1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. g3 Bg7 4. Bg2 O-O 5. Nf3 d6 6. O-O Nc6 7. Nc3 Bf5 8. Bg5 Ne4 $6 ({A mediocre reaction to a rather mediocre line (8.g5).} 8... h6 9. Bxf6 Bxf6 {is preferable.}) 9. Nxe4 (9. Bf4 {is not a logical follow-up to 8.g5:} e5 10. dxe5 dxe5 11. Bd2 Nxc3 12. Bxc3 Be6 $11 {Erceg,S-Armanda,I/Omis 2003}) 9... Bxe4 10. d5 $1 (10. Be3 $2 d5 11. Qd2 dxc4 12. Rfd1 Qd5 13. Ne1 Bxg2 14. Nxg2 e5 $17 {Prulentsov,D-Zolotukhin,V/Dagomys 2004}) 10... Bxf3 $2 ({Black fails to understand the problems of the position.} 10... Nb8 {or even}) (10... Na5 {should be preferred.}) 11. exf3 $1 {(D)  Intending to apply pressure on the semi-open e-file and the backward e7-pawn in particular.} Ne5 ({Or} 11... Nd4 12. Re1 Re8 13. Re4 c5 14. dxc6 Nxc6 15. Qd2 $14 {Wojtkiewicz,A-Maiffret,P/Corsica 1997}) 12. Rc1 b6 $6 ({The immediate} 12... Bf6 {is better. Black mistakenly feared White's c5 advance.}) 13. Re1 Bf6 14. h4 $1 ({Naturally,} 14. Bxf6 $2 exf6 {would immediately solve Black's problems.}) 14... a5 15. f4 $1 Nd7 16. Re2 $1 {Black's position is already lost. White threatens to double rooks on the e-file and place his light-squared bishop on h3, while Black is devoid of any substantial prospects.} Nc5 17. Bh3 Kg7 18. h5 h6 {Ugly, but what else is there?} 19. Bxf6+ exf6 20. Qd4 $1 {If Black were given time to play 20...f5, shutting out the white bishop, a great part of his difficulties would vanish.} Re8 21. Rce1 Rxe2 22. Rxe2 Qf8 23. hxg6 fxg6 $2 ({Black's only chance lay in} 23... Re8 $1 24. Rxe8 Qxe8 25. gxf7 Kxf7 {, retaining some chances of survival despite the material deficit.}) 24. Be6 $1 {The outpost! Now the black rook will be aimlessly moving to and fro, while White will have all the time in the world to organize his future plans.} Re8 25. Re3 Re7 26. f5 g5 $2 ({The last error.} 26... gxf5 27. Qf4 Kh8 {was essential.}) 27. b3 $1 Qe8 28. a3 Nd7 29. Bxd7 $1 Qxd7 30. Re6 $1 Rf7 ({No better is} 30... Rxe6 31. fxe6 Qe7 32. g4 $1 {. White will bring his king to f5 and then advance his queenside pawns, while in the meantime Black will run out of useful moves.}) 31. Qd1 $1 Rf8 32. Qe2 $1 {Black resigned due to 32...f7 33.h5!. A very "clean" game, despite (or rather thanks to!) Black's mistakes, where several strategic elements were encountered: open and semi-open files, outpost and passed pawn!} 1-0


