1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. g3 Bg7 4. Bg2 O-O 5. Nc3 d6 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. O-O Bf5 8. d5 Na5 9. Nd4 Bd7 10. b3 c5 {(D) } 11. Nc2 a6 12. Qd3 Rb8 13. Bb2 (13. Bd2 {is the alternative choice.}) 13... b5 14. Rab1 Qc7 15. h3 ({Similar alternatives are: a)} 15. e4 Rb7 (15... bxc4 16. bxc4 e6 17. Ba1 exd5 18. Nxd5 Nxd5 19. Bxg7 Kxg7 20. exd5 $14 {Straub,P-Klinova,M/Gibraltar 2006}) 16. Ne3 Rfb8 17. cxb5 axb5 18. Qd2 b4 19. Ne2 Bb5 20. Rfc1 Qb6 21. Rc2 Qa6 22. Nc1 c4 23. Nxc4 Nxc4 24. bxc4 Bxc4 $11 {Manninen,M-Kaabi,M/Moscow 1994}) ({b)} 15. Ba1 bxc4 16. bxc4 Rxb1 17. Rxb1 Rb8 18. Rxb8+ Qxb8 19. f4 Be8 20. Bh3 Nd7 $11 {Nepomniashchy,Y-Sultangareev,M/Vladimir 2002}) 15... Rb6 16. Ba1 {(D)  White would feel happy if he could now play be1, planning a central pawn advance, leaving the black rooks wondering on the b-file.} bxc4 $1 17. bxc4 Rxb1 18. Rxb1 Rb8 19. Re1 (19. Rxb8+ Qxb8 $11) 19... Be8 $1 {Preparing a f6-d7-a4 manoeuvre.} 20. e3 Nd7 21. f4 Nb6 22. Na3 Bd7 23. g4 Rb7 24. Bf1 {Black could go on, as his position is more than fine (24...c8!?, planning ...b4 and ...b6).} 1/2-1/2


