1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nf3 Bg7 4. g3 O-O 5. Bg2 d6 6. Nc3 Nc6 7. O-O Bf5 8. Ne1 Qd7 9. e4 Bh3 {(D) } 10. f4 Bxg2 11. Kxg2 e5 $6 (11... Na5) 12. fxe5 dxe5 13. d5 Nd4 14. Nd3 Qe7 (14... Ne8 15. Be3 Qe7 (15... Nd6 16. Nxe5 Bxe5 17. Bxd4 Nxc4 18. b3 Ne3+ 19. Bxe3 Bxc3 20. Rc1 Be5 21. Bf4 $14) 16. Qd2 c5 (16... Nd6 17. b3 f5 $13) 17. b3 b6 18. Rae1 Nd6 $13 {Zoler,D-Sidorenko,I/Ramat Aviv 2004}) 15. Nxe5 $5 Nxe4 $6 (15... Nxd5 {is unclear but} 16. Nxg6 fxg6 17. Rxf8+ Rxf8 18. cxd5 Rf3 $44) (15... Qxe5 $1 16. Bf4 Nxd5 17. Bxe5 (17. exd5 Qe7 18. Qa4 Ne2 $11) (17. cxd5 Qe7 $11) 17... Ne3+ 18. Kh3 Nxd1 19. Bxg7 Kxg7 20. Raxd1 c5 $11 {is OK for Black. Note that}) (15... c5 $6 16. Nf3 Nxe4 17. Re1 f5 18. Ng5 Rae8 19. Bf4 $14 {is pleasant for White.}) 16. Qxd4 Nxc3 17. Re1 $1 Rfe8 18. Bf4 Na4 (18... Nxa2 19. Rxa2 g5 20. Rxa7 $16) 19. Qd2 Nxb2 $1 (19... Nb6 20. Rac1 Qd8 21. Re2 Re7 22. Nf3 Rxe2+ 23. Qxe2 $14) 20. Qxb2 g5 21. Kh1 $1 gxf4 $2 (21... Qf6 $1 22. Rf1 (22. Re4 Qf5 23. Rae1 gxf4 24. g4 (24. gxf4 f6) 24... Qg5 $13) 22... Qb6 23. Qg2 Bxe5 24. Rab1 Qc5 25. Bxg5 Qxc4 26. Rxb7 $14) 22. gxf4 Qf6 23. Rg1 $1 $16 Kh8 (23... Qxf4 24. Rxg7+ Kxg7 25. Nd3+) 24. Rxg7 $1 Rxe5 (24... Qxg7 25. Rg1 Qf6 26. Nxf7#) 25. Rag1 $2 (25. fxe5 Qxg7 26. Rg1 Qf8 27. e6+ f6 28. Qxb7 $18) 25... Qxf4 26. Qg2 (26. Rxf7 Qe4+) 26... Qe4 27. Rxf7 Qxg2+ 28. Kxg2 (28. Rxg2 Re1+ 29. Rg1 Rxg1+ 30. Kxg1 Rg8+ 31. Kf2 Rg7 $11) 28... Rc8 (28... Rg8+ 29. Kf2 Rxg1 30. Kxg1 Rg5+ 31. Kf2 Rg7 $11) 29. Kf3 b5 30. Rgg7 bxc4 31. Rxh7+ Kg8 32. Rhg7+ Kh8 33. Rh7+ Kg8 34. Rfg7+ Kf8 35. Rd7 Kg8 36. Rxc7 Rxc7 37. Rxc7 Rxd5 38. Rxc4 Rd2 39. Rg4+ Kf7 40. Rg2 Rd4 41. Re2 {White is a pawn up, but in reality he has no winning chances. The black king will stop the white h-pawn and the black rook will attack the white a-pawn and defend its own pawn.} a5 42. Rf2 Kg6 43. Ke3 Rh4 44. Kd3 Kg5 45. Kc3 Kg6 46. Kd3 Kg5 47. Ke2 Ra4 48. Kf3 Rf4+ 49. Ke3 Ra4 50. Rg2+ Kf5 ({Although Black wants to stay centralised with his king,} 50... Kh5 {is also enough for the draw.}) 51. Kd3 Rh4 52. Kc3 Kf6 53. Rb2 Ke6 54. Rf2 Ke5 55. Kd2 Rb4 56. Ke2 Rb1 57. Kf3 Kf5 58. Kg3+ Kg6 59. Rf4 Rg1+ 60. Kf3 Rh1 61. Kg2 Rc1 62. Ra4 Rc5 63. Kf3 Rc3+ (63... Kh5 {is more accurate, but the text-move does not do any serious harm to Black.}) 64. Kg4 Rc5 65. h4 Rb5 66. a3 Rc5 67. Rf4 Rc3 68. Ra4 Rc5 69. Kf4 Kf6 70. Ke3 Rh5 71. Rf4+ Kg6 72. Kd4 Kg7 73. Kc4 Kg6 74. Kb3 Kg7 75. Ka4 Kg6 76. Rf1 Kg7 ({Not falling into the obvious trap} 76... Rxh4+ $2 77. Kxa5 {when White is simply winning.}) 77. Rf4 Kg6 78. Kb3 ({White cannot make any progress with either} 78. Rg4+ Kf6) ({or} 78. Rf8 Kg7 79. Rb8 Rxh4+ 80. Kxa5 Rh5+ 81. Rb5 Rh8 82. a4 Ra8+ 83. Kb4 Kf6) 78... Kg7 79. Kc4 Kg6 80. Kd4 Kg7 81. Ke4 Kg6 82. Kf3 Rc5 83. Kg4 Rc3 84. a4 Rb3 85. Re4 Kf6 86. h5 Rb4 87. Kf3 (87. Rf4+ Ke5 88. Rxb4 axb4 89. h6 Kf6 90. a5 $11) 87... Rb3+ 88. Kg4 Rb4 89. Kf3 Rb3+ 90. Kf4 Rh3 (90... Rb4 $2 91. Rxb4 axb4 92. Ke4 $18) 91. Kg4 Rb3 92. Rf4+ Kg7 93. Kf5 Rh3 94. Kg4 Rb3 95. Kg5 Rg3+ 96. Kh4 (96. Rg4 Rxg4+ 97. Kxg4 Kh6 $11) 96... Rb3 97. Rg4+ Kh6 98. Rg6+ Kh7 99. Kg5 {A last try! It must be mentioned that White tortured Black for many moves, which is not such a common practice between Grandmasters. During the game I felt a bit offended but in the end I must confess that it was my mistake that I ended up in a slightly worse endgame!} Rb4 100. Rh6+ Kg8 101. Ra6 Rxa4 102. Ra8+ Kh7 103. Ra7+ Kg8 104. Kh6 Ra1 105. Kg6 1/2-1/2


