1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. g3 Bg7 4. Bg2 O-O 5. Nc3 d6 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. O-O Bf5 8. Ne1 Qd7 9. e4 Bh3 {(D) } 10. f4 Bxg2 (10... e5 11. fxe5 dxe5 12. d5 Nd4 13. Nd3 Rae8 (13... Bxg2 14. Kxg2 Ne8 $1) 14. Bg5 $1 (14. Nxe5 Rxe5 15. Qxd4 Rh5 16. Rxf6 (16. e5 Bxg2 $17) 16... Bxg2 17. Kxg2 c5 18. Qf2 Qh3+ 19. Kg1 Bxf6 $17) (14. b3 Bg4 15. Qd2 Qe7 16. Nf2 Bd7 17. Qd1 $11 {Janjgava,L-Banikas,H/Panormo 1998}) 14... Nh5 15. Be3 Bxg2 16. Kxg2 Qe7 17. Qd2 $14) 11. Kxg2 Na5 $5 {A typical idea, creating counterplay on the queenside.} 12. Qd3 c5 13. d5 (13. dxc5 dxc5 14. e5 Qc6+ 15. Nf3 Rad8 16. Qe2 Ne8 17. b3 Nc7 18. Be3 a6 $11) 13... e6 $6 (13... a6 14. Rb1 (14. a4 Nb3) 14... b5 {and Black has at least equal chances.}) 14. Bd2 exd5 15. exd5 a6 16. Nd1 Qc7 17. Rc1 b5 18. b3 Rfe8 19. Nf2 Rab8 20. Nf3 {Now Black is facing problems with his a5-knight and the opening of the e-file is not to his benefit.} Nd7 21. Rfe1 bxc4 22. Rxe8+ Rxe8 23. bxc4 Nb7 24. Rb1 Rb8 25. Qa3 Nd8 26. Ba5 Qc8 27. Re1 $16 Nb7 28. Bd2 Ra8 29. Rb1 f5 30. Qe3 Nd8 31. Ba5 Nf7 32. Qe6 Nf8 33. Qxc8 Rxc8 34. Rb6 {White is winning a pawn, leaving Black in a critical position.} Nd7 35. Rxa6 Nf6 36. Ng5 Nxg5 37. fxg5 Nd7 38. Rxd6 Ne5 39. Rd8+ Rxd8 40. Bxd8 Nxc4 41. Kf3 Kf7 42. Nd3 Bd4 43. a4 Ke8 44. Bf6 Kd7 45. Nf4 $2 (45. Bxd4 $1 cxd4 46. g4 Kd6 (46... fxg4+ 47. Ke4) 47. gxf5 gxf5 48. Kf4 Kxd5 49. Kxf5 $18) 45... Kd6 46. Bxd4 cxd4 47. h4 Kc5 {Black's position seems critical. Apart from the material disadvantage, he must always keep in mind the xg6 "sacrifice", which could, under favourable circumstances, end the game immediately.} 48. Ke2 {Of course, the afore-mentioned sacrifice is not available yet, as the black knight can quickly return to the kingside via e5. On the other hand Black has centralized well-placed pieces and a passed d-pawn.} Na5 49. Nxg6 $5 ({White proves impatient, but} 49. Kd2 Nc4+ 50. Kc2 Ne3+ 51. Kd3 Nc4 {leads nowhere as well.}) 49... d3+ $2 ({Wrong move order. Black should play} 49... hxg6 50. h5 Nc4 51. hxg6 d3+ 52. Kxd3 Ne5+ 53. Ke3 Nxg6 54. a5 {with a draw.}) 50. Kxd3 $1 ({A blunder would be} 50. Kd1 $2 hxg6 51. h5 Nc4 52. hxg6 Kd4 $1 53. g7 Kc3 $1 $11 {, illustrating a "hidden" advantage of Black's position: his superbly placed centralized king.}) 50... hxg6 51. h5 Nc4 52. h6 $2 (52. hxg6 $2 Ne5+ 53. Ke3 Nxg6 {is just a transposition to a line mentioned above, but White could win with}) (52. a5 $1 Ne5+ 53. Ke3 Kxd5 54. a6 {.}) 52... Ne5+ 53. Kc3 Kxd5 54. h7 Nf7 55. Kb4 Kc6 56. a5 Nh8 57. Kc4 Nf7 58. Kb4 ({Black has created a fortress, denying White any winning chances.} 58. Kd4 Kb5 59. Kd5 Kxa5 60. Kc6 (60. Ke6 Nxg5+ 61. Kf6 Nxh7+ 62. Kxg6 f4 63. gxf4 Nf8+) 60... Nh8 $1 61. Kd6 Kb6 62. Ke6 Kc6 63. Kf6 Kd6 64. Kg7 Ke7 65. Kxh8 Kf8 {is the main variation of the drawing concept.}) 58... Nh8 59. Kc4 Nf7 60. Kb4 Nh8 1/2-1/2


