1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nf3 Bg7 4. g3 O-O 5. Bg2 d6 6. O-O Nc6 7. Nc3 Bf5 8. b3 Ne4 9. Bb2 Nxc3 10. Bxc3 Be4 {(D) } 11. Rc1 d5 12. e3 ({This is a strategical continuation, aiming in long manoeuvres. White gets nothing with} 12. c5 b5 13. cxb6 cxb6 14. Qd2 Qd6 15. Rfd1 Rac8 $11 {Majer,D-Euler,G/Giessen 1991}) 12... e6 13. Qe2 a5 ({After} 13... Qe7 {White can get something as the black queen is not terribly well placed on the e7-square:} 14. Rfd1 a5 15. cxd5 exd5 16. Bh3 g5 17. Nd2 Bg6 18. Qb5 Qd6 19. Bg2 Rfd8 20. Nf3 $14 {Neverov,V-Wang Rui/Dubai 2005.}) ({Equally good is} 13... Ne7 14. Rfd1 c6 15. Bf1 Bxf3 16. Qxf3 Nf5 17. b4 a6 18. Bd3 Nd6 19. c5 Nb5 20. Bb2 Qe7 21. Qf4 Nc7 22. a4 Rfe8 23. Qd6 e5 $11 {Dautov,R-Martinovic,S/Germany 1995}) 14. Rfd1 (14. Ne1 Bxg2 15. Nxg2 Qd7 16. Nf4 Rfd8 17. Rfd1 Ne7 18. Nd3 b6 19. Be1 $11 {Panno,O-Valerga,D/Vicente Lopez 2004}) 14... a4 15. Ne1 ({Not very ambitious. White has tried the following alternatives: a)} 15. b4 dxc4 16. Qxc4 Na7 (16... Qd5 17. Qxd5 exd5 18. Ne5 Bxg2 19. Kxg2 Na7 $11) 17. a3 c6 18. Bb2 Nb5 19. Qe2 Qe7 20. Bf1 Bd5 $11 {Roiz,M-Mittelman,G/Beersheba 1997}) ({b)} 15. Bf1 axb3 16. axb3 {b1)} g5 ({b2)} 16... Bxf3 $6 17. Qxf3 Ne7 (17... Ra3 $6 18. cxd5 exd5 19. Bg2 Ne7 20. Bb4 Rxb3 21. Bxe7 Qxe7 22. Qxd5 Rb6 23. Qc5 $2 (23. Qa5 $1 $16) 23... Qxc5 24. dxc5 Rb4 25. c6 bxc6 26. Bxc6 Be5 27. Rd7 Bd6 28. Bd5 Kg7 29. e4 Rbb8 30. Ra1 {½-½ Beil,Z-Tseitlin,M/Olomouc 1973}) 18. Bb4 c6 19. Ra1 Re8 $14) ({b3)} 16... Qe7 17. Ne1 h5 18. Nd3 dxc4 $6 19. bxc4 Bxd3 $6 20. Qxd3 Ra7 21. Qb1 Rfa8 22. Bg2 Nd8 23. Bb4 Qd7 24. Qe4 $16 {Najdorf,M-Spassky,B/Gothenburg 1955}) 17. Nd2 Bg6 18. Bg2 Ne7 $13) ({c)} 15. cxd5 exd5 16. Ne5 {and now: c1)} Ne7 ({c2)} 16... Bxg2 17. Nxc6 bxc6 18. Kxg2 axb3 19. axb3 $14) ({c3)} 16... Nxe5 17. dxe5 (17. Bxe4 dxe4 18. dxe5 Qg5 19. Rd7 axb3 20. axb3 Bxe5 21. Bxe5 Qxe5 22. Rdxc7 Ra1 $11) 17... Bxg2 18. Kxg2 axb3 19. axb3 c6 20. e4 $14) 17. f3 Bf5 18. e4 Be6 19. Kh1 axb3 20. axb3 $11 {Potomak,V-Rojicek,V/Ostrava 2005}) 15... Bxg2 16. Nxg2 Ne7 $11 {Draw agreed as both players were afraid to break the equilibrium!} 1/2-1/2


