1. Nf3 {Efstratios Grivas Efstratios Grivas} Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. g3 Bg7 4. Bg2 O-O 5. O-O d6 6. Nc3 e5 7. d3 Nc6 8. Rb1 a5 9. a3 Nd4 10. Bg5 h6 ({Black can also play} 10... Ne6 11. Bxf6 (11. Bd2 Ne8 (11... c6 12. b4 axb4 13. axb4 Nd4 14. b5 Bg4 15. bxc6 {½-½ Dzindzichashvili,R-Ivanov,A/Modesto 1995}) 12. b4 axb4 13. axb4 f5 14. Qb3 Kh8 15. Ra1 Rxa1 16. Rxa1 c6 17. Rb1 Nf6 18. b5 e4 $13 {Erdelyi,T-Hebden,M/Bern 1992}) 11... Bxf6 12. b4 axb4 13. axb4 Bg7 14. b5 (14. Qb3 Kh8 15. Ra1 Rb8 16. Ra7 f5 17. Qa3 g5 18. Nd2 g4 $13 {Brekke,O-Hoi,C/Gausdal 1994}) 14... Bd7 (14... f5 $5 15. Nd5 Kh8 16. Nd2 Ra2 17. Nb3 h5 $13 {Foisor,C-Brustman,A Yerevan OL 1996}) 15. Ra1 c6 16. Rxa8 Qxa8 17. Qb3 Qa5 18. Rb1 Nc5 $13 {Adianto,U-Pavlovic,M Biel 1998.}) 11. Bxf6 Qxf6 ({The main alternative is} 11... Bxf6 12. b4 (12. Nd2 Bg7 13. e3 Ne6 14. b4 axb4 15. axb4 c6 16. Qc2 f5 17. b5 Bd7 $13 {Dzindzichashvili,R-Sutovsky,E/Philadelphia 1993}) (12. Nd5 $6 Bg7 13. b4 axb4 14. axb4 c6 15. Ne3 Bd7 16. Nxd4 exd4 17. Nc2 Re8 $15 {Rueda,L-Chase,C/Boylston 1995}) 12... axb4 13. axb4 c6 (13... Bg4 14. e3 (14. Nxd4 exd4 15. Ne4 Ra2 16. Re1 Bg7 17. Ra1 Qa8 18. Rxa2 Qxa2 $11 {Anastasian,A-Akopian,V/Yerevan 1989}) 14... Ra3 15. Nd5 Nxf3+ 16. Bxf3 Bh3 $13 {Benjamin,J-Watson,W/Hastings 1984}) (13... Ra3 14. Nd5 Bg7 15. b5 Bg4 16. Nxd4 exd4 17. h3 Bd7 18. Nb4 Qc8 19. Kh2 Re8 20. Qd2 c6 $11 {Hakulinen,E-Houtsonen,P/Kuopio 1991}) (13... Bg7 14. b5 Bg4 15. Nxd4 exd4 16. Ne4 Qd7 17. Re1 Rfe8 18. Rb2 Re7 19. Nd2 c6 20. bxc6 bxc6 21. Rb6 d5 22. cxd5 cxd5 23. Nf3 Ra2 24. Rb4 Qa7 {½-½ Link,M-Mohaupt,S/Goch 1995}) 14. b5 Bg7 15. bxc6 bxc6 16. Nxd4 {½-½ Hulak,K-Vukic,M/Reggio Emilia 1983.}) ({Another playable and good move is} 11... Nxf3+ 12. Bxf3 Bxf6 13. Nd5 (13. b4 axb4 14. axb4 c6 (14... Bg7 15. b5 f5 16. Qb3 Kh7 $11 {Nesterov,J-Makarjev,I/Protvino 1992}) 15. b5 Qc7 16. Qb3 Bh3 17. Rfc1 Ra5 18. bxc6 bxc6 19. Qb6 Rc8 20. Qxc7 Rxc7 21. Bg2 Bxg2 22. Kxg2 Kg7 23. h4 d5 24. cxd5 cxd5 25. Nd1 Rxc1 26. Rxc1 {½-½ Dzindzichashvili,R-Smyslov,V/New York 1989}) 13... Bg7 14. b4 c6 15. Ne3 axb4 16. axb4 Bh3 17. Re1 f5 18. b5 Qe8 19. bxc6 bxc6 $13 {Rian,M-Fairclough,N/Dubai OL 1986.}) 12. b4 (12. Nd2 c6 13. e3 Ne6 14. b4 axb4 15. axb4 Bd7 16. Ra1 Qe7 17. Ra4 f5 18. Qa1 Rxa4 19. Qxa4 f4 $13 {Jacobsen,B-Taulbut,S/Silkeborg 1980.}) 12... axb4 13. axb4 c6 14. b5 Ra3 $2 (14... Bg4 15. bxc6 bxc6 16. Nxd4 exd4 {is fine for Black.}) 15. bxc6 bxc6 16. Nxd4 exd4 17. Na4 $1 ({Clearly better than} 17. Ne4 Qe7 18. Rb6 d5 19. Nd2 Bg4 20. Re1 Qc5 {with unclear play, Bareev,E-Beliavsky,A Ubeda 1997.}) 17... c5 ({Almost forced, as} 17... Bd7 18. Nb6 Be8 19. Ra1 $1 {promises White the advantage.}) 18. Nb6 Be6 19. Nd5 Bxd5 $2 ({The d5-knight is menacingly placed but Black should delay its exchange as much as possible.} 19... Qd8 {was compulsory.}) 20. Bxd5 Re8 21. Rb7 Re7 22. Qb1 Bf8 23. Qb2 Rxb7 24. Qxa3 Re7 25. Bf3 h5 26. Rb1 {White has a stable advantage as transformations of the pawn-structure are highly unlikely. This advantage is owed to his superior bishop that controls vital squares, particularly the sensitive a2-g8 diagonal (from d5). Black's main problem is to find an active plan and improve the f8-bishop which lacks targets. It must be noted that the presence of major pieces is particularly important; were we to remove them from the board, the position would be drawn. Thus, this exchange of the major pieces must be Black's plan, even if he has to offer material (a pawn) to achieve it.} Qe5 27. Qa4 Bg7 28. Qa8+ Re8 29. Qc6 Re6 30. h4 Kh7 31. Kg2 Re7 32. Ra1 Re6 33. Ra8 Rf6 34. Be4 Re6 35. Qd7 Re7 36. Qd8 f5 {Black has been forced to weaken his king with his last move. The lack of counterplay suits White who, with slow, "mostly pointless" manoeuvres gradually but steadily improves his position.} 37. Bf3 Qf6 38. Ra6 Re6 39. Qd7 Re7 40. Qxd6 Qxd6 41. Rxd6 {White has won a pawn while keeping the rooks on the board. His position is won, unless Black succeeds in exchanging these rooks under favourable circumstances.} Bf8 42. Rc6 Re5 43. Bd5 Kg7 44. Kf3 Re7 $2 {This eases White's task as it allows the exchange of the important black c5-pawn for the weak white one on e2. As a consequence, White also obtains a passed pawn; this proves decisive. The end of the game is instructive for the slow but sure way in which White secured the point:} 45. Rxc5 Rxe2 46. Rc7+ Re7 47. Rc8 Re1 48. Bb7 Re5 49. Rd8 Bc5 50. Bd5 Kf6 51. Rc8 Ba3 52. Ra8 Bb4 53. Ra4 Bc5 54. Ra6+ Kg7 55. Ra5 Bb4 56. Rb5 Ba3 57. Rb3 Be7 58. Rb7 Kf6 59. Rd7 Re1 60. Bb7 Bc5 61. Rc7 Bf8 62. c5 Rc1 63. c6 Bd6 64. Rc8 Rc2 65. Ba6 Rc5 66. Bc4 g5 67. hxg5+ Kxg5 68. Bb3 Kf6 69. Ba4 Ra5 70. Rd8 Be5 71. Bb3 Rc5 72. Bd5 Kg5 73. Kg2 f4 74. gxf4+ Kxf4 75. Be4 Kg5 76. Rf8 Bf4 77. Kh3 Bd6 78. Rf7 Bf4 79. Re7 Bd6 80. Re6 Bb8 81. Rg6+ Kf4 1-0


