1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. g3 Bg7 4. d4 O-O 5. Bg2 d6 6. Nc3 Nc6 7. O-O Bf5 {(D) } 8. d5 ({There do exist some alternative, not very often played lines: a)} 8. Nh4 Bd7 9. b3 (9. f4 Na5 $1 (9... a6 $2 10. e4 Rb8 11. e5 Ne8 12. Be3 $16 {Khakhanov,V-Kopylov,A/Salekhard 2006}) 10. Qd3 c5 11. d5 a6 $13) 9... e5 (9... Ne8 $6 10. Nf3 Bg4 11. Be3 e5 12. dxe5 dxe5 13. Bc5 $14 {Volodin,A-Savickas,A/Tallin 2006}) 10. dxe5 dxe5 11. Ba3 Re8 $11) ({b)} 8. Bf4 Ne4 9. Nd5 (9. d5 $2 Nxc3 10. bxc3 Na5 11. Qa4 c5 $17 {Orekhov,N-Kopylov,A/Salekhard 2006}) 9... Bd7 10. Rc1 f5 11. Be3 e6 12. Nc3 Nxc3 13. Rxc3 $11 {Lehner,O-Sutovsky,E/Feugen 2006}) 8... Na5 9. Nd4 Bd7 10. b3 c5 11. Nc2 a6 12. Rb1 Qc7 13. Bb2 b5 {(D) } 14. cxb5 {This cannot be the way to search for the advantage.} axb5 15. b4 Nc4 $1 16. Ba1 Rfc8 $6 (16... Rfb8 $1 $15) 17. bxc5 Qxc5 18. Nb4 $6 (18. Nxb5 $1 Ng4 (18... Bxb5 19. Bd4 Qc7 20. Rxb5 Qd7 21. Rb1 Rxa2 $11) 19. Bxg7 Kxg7 20. Nbd4 Rxa2 $11) 18... Ng4 19. Ne4 Qb6 20. Bxg7 Kxg7 21. Rb3 Kg8 22. Qd3 Nge5 23. Qd1 Ra4 ({More dangerous for White is} 23... Bf5 $1 24. h3 Bxe4 25. Bxe4 Ra4 $17) 24. Nc3 Ra7 25. Nc6 $6 ({Not of a help was} 25. Qc2 Rac7) ({but White had to try} 25. Ne4 Bf5 $17) 25... Nxc6 26. Rxb5 Qa6 27. dxc6 Bxc6 28. Bxc6 Qxc6 29. Qd4 (29. a4 Ne3 30. fxe3 Qxc3 $17) 29... Rac7 $2 (29... Rxa2 $1 {is simply winning a pawn!}) 30. a4 Nd2 31. Qxd2 Qxc3 32. Qxc3 Rxc3 33. Rb7 e6 34. Ra1 Rc1+ 35. Rxc1 Rxc1+ 36. Kg2 Ra1 37. Ra7 Kg7 {This rook ending is drawn, as White cannot exploit his passed pawn. Naturally, the material balance means that there is no 5:4 ending to be examined, but this example is an important illustration of the possibility of defeat (!) existent in a seemingly harmless rook ending with 5:5 pawns.} 38. e4 $6 ({Dangerous, as it will help Black obtain active play. Waiting with} 38. e3 {is more normal.}) 38... Kf6 39. Ra5 h5 40. h4 Ra3 41. Kf1 Ra2 42. Ke1 $2 ({A serious mistake.} 42. Kg2 {is fine.}) 42... e5 $1 {This is Black's idea. He will proceed with the ...f5 break, obtaining a passed d-pawn and an active king.} 43. Ra8 Ke6 44. a5 f5 45. exf5+ ({Compulsory, as} 45. f3 fxe4 46. fxe4 Ra4 $1 47. a6 Rxe4+ 48. Kf1 Ra4 49. a7 Kd5 {would be won for Black. The significance of the white king's misplacement is evident in this line.}) 45... gxf5 46. a6 Kd5 47. a7 Ke4 48. Rd8 ({White has no other useful move. Both} 48. Kf1 Kf3 $1) ({and} 48. f4 Ke3 $1 49. Kd1 e4 {are even worse.}) 48... Rxa7 49. Rxd6 Kf3 $1 50. Rf6 {White must harass the black pawns, as passivity would lead to a quick defeat.} Ra1+ 51. Kd2 Ra2+ 52. Ke1 f4 $1 53. gxf4 exf4 $6 ({This doesn't spoil things, but} 53... e4 $1 54. f5 Re2+ 55. Kd1 Kxf2 56. Re6 e3 57. f6 Rd2+ 58. Kc1 Rd7 $1 {would have won quickly.}) 54. Rf5 Re2+ 55. Kd1 Rxf2 56. Rxh5 Rh2 57. Rh8 Ke3 58. h5 f3 59. Re8+ Kf2 60. Rh8 Kf1 $2 ({Incomprehensible. Black lost a valuable tempo, allowing White to survive.} 60... Kg1 $1 61. h6 f2 62. Rg8+ Rg2 {really wasn't that hard!}) 61. h6 f2 62. h7 Rh6 63. Kd2 Rd6+ 64. Kc2 Rd7 65. Kc3 Rg7 66. Kd2 Rf7 67. Kc2 Rd7 68. Kc3 Ra7 69. Kd2 Re7 70. Kd1 Rg7 71. Kd2 Rf7 1/2-1/2


