1. e4 {Efstratios Grivas} c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d6 4. O-O Bd7 5. Re1 Nf6 6. c3 a6 7. Bxc6 {A very sharp line, where White sacrifices material in the fight for the initiative.} Bxc6 8. d4 ({Anything else would be too passive for White and not 'connected' with 7.xc6:  a)} 8. e5 dxe5 9. Nxe5 Rc8 10. Na3 (10. d4 cxd4 (10... e6 11. Be3 Nd5 12. Qh5 g6 13. Qf3 f6 14. Nxc6 Rxc6 15. Nd2 $13 {Kiselev,G-Sakaev,K/Krasnoyarsk 2007}) 11. cxd4 e6 12. Nc3 Be7 13. Be3 O-O 14. Qb3 Bd5 $15 {Fruteau,S-Georgiev,K/Saint Affrique 2007}) 10... e6 11. Nc2 Be7 12. Nxc6 Rxc6 13. d4 $11 {Vijayalakshmi,S-Vuckovic,B/Catalan Bay 2004.}) ({b)} 8. d3 e6 (8... g6 9. e5 dxe5 10. Nxe5 Qd5 11. Nxc6 Qxc6 12. d4 cxd4 13. cxd4 Bg7 14. Nc3 Qd7 15. Qf3 O-O $11 {Beikert,G-Boensch,U/Germany 2008}) 9. Nbd2 (9. Bg5 Be7 10. a4 b6 11. c4 O-O 12. Nc3 Qc7 $11 {Minakova,O-Lutsko,I/Voronezh 1997}) 9... Be7 10. a3 O-O 11. b4 b5 12. Qe2 Nd7 $11 {Paehtz,E-Muse,D/Germany 2002.}) 8... Bxe4 9. Bg5 Bd5 $5 ({Of course Black has some options at his disposal:  a)} 9... d5 10. Nbd2 Bxf3 (10... Bg6 11. Qb3 c4 12. Qxb7 Qc8 13. Qb6 e6 14. b3 $14 {Zaitsev,I-Epishin,V/Podolsk 1992}) 11. Qxf3 e6 12. Bxf6 Qxf6 (12... gxf6 13. c4 $44 {Beltran Rueda,S-Polugaevsky,L/Oviedo 1991}) 13. Qxd5 Qe7 14. Qe5 cxd4 15. cxd4 Qd6 16. Qe4 Qb4 17. Nf3 Be7 $13 {Giorgadze,T-Tal,M/Tbilisi 1978.}) ({b)} 9... Bc6 10. Bxf6 gxf6 11. d5 (11. Nh4 cxd4 12. cxd4 d5 13. Qf3 e6 14. Nc3 h5 15. Re3 Kd7 16. g3 Bh6 $17 {Arngrimsson,D-Cheparinov,I/Kallithea 2008}) 11... Bd7 12. Nbd2 Qc7 13. a4 O-O-O 14. b4 e6 15. Nc4 cxb4 16. cxb4 Kb8 $13 {Orlov,A-Areshchenko,A/Dresden 2007.}) 10. Nbd2 (10. c4 $5 {is the sharpest move here, but sacrificing two pawns in just ten moves constitutes a very heavy commitment:} Bxf3 (10... Bxc4 11. Bxf6 (11. Nc3 cxd4 12. Qxd4 Rc8 13. Bxf6 gxf6 14. Ne4 e5 15. Rac1 b5 $17 {Ristic,N-Grivas,E/Athens 1999}) 11... gxf6 12. d5 Bb5 13. Nc3 f5 14. Nh4 Bd7 15. Qh5 Qb6 16. Nxf5 O-O-O 17. Qxf7 Kb8 18. Re2 Be8 19. Qe6 Bd7 20. Qf7 Be8 21. Qe6 Bd7 {½-½ Rozentalis,E-Hansen,C/Copenhagen 2004}) 11. Qxf3 cxd4 12. Qxb7 Qc8 (12... Rb8 13. Qxa6 e6 14. Bxf6 gxf6 15. Nd2 Bg7 16. Nb3 O-O 17. Nxd4 Rxb2 $13 {Wu Kaiyu-Wang Yaoyao/Xiapu 2005 and Moutousis,K-Grivas,E/Khania 1992}) 13. Qf3 e5 (13... e6 14. Bxf6 gxf6 15. Nd2 Be7 $11 {Damaso,R-Grivas,E/Yerevan 1996}) 14. Nd2 Nd7 15. Nb3 f6 16. Bd2 Be7 $13 {Ivanchuk,V-Topalov,V/Monte Carlo 2003.}) 10... e6 11. c4 Bxf3 12. Qxf3 ({White is just a pawn down after} 12. Nxf3 Be7 13. Qb3 Qc7 14. dxc5 dxc5 15. Qa4+ Qd7 {Baerwinkel,T-Grischuk,A/Mainz 2006.}) 12... cxd4 $1 13. Bxf6 ({White can also try} 13. Qxb7 Qc8 $5 (13... Be7 14. Qc6+ Nd7 15. Bxe7 Kxe7 16. Nf3 Qb6 17. Qxb6 Nxb6 18. b3 Rhc8 19. Nxd4 d5 20. cxd5 Nxd5 21. Nf5+ Kf6 22. Ne3 Nxe3 23. Rxe3 Rc2 $11 {Svidler,P-Topalov,V/Prague 2002}) 14. Qb6 ({or} 14. Qf3 Be7 15. Nb3 h6 $1 16. Bh4 O-O 17. Qd3 $1 {with equality}) 14... Qc5 $11 {Timoshchenko,G-Kupreichik,V/Ashkhabad 1978.}) 13... gxf6 14. Qxb7 Bg7 ({Also possible is} 14... Rb8 15. Qc6+ Qd7 16. Qe4 f5 17. Qxd4 Rg8 18. Rab1 Qc6 19. g3 a5 $13 {Wen,Y-Wang Yue/Shandong 2007 or}) (14... Be7 15. Qc6+ Kf8 16. Nf3 e5 17. Nh4 Rc8 18. Qf3 Rg8 $13 {Sebag,M-Bu Xiangzhi/Cannes 2004.}) 15. Qc6+ (15. Rxe6+ $6 fxe6 16. Qxg7 Rf8 17. Qxh7 Rc8 {, as in Buchal,S-Ribli,Z/Hofheim 1989, is not good for White.} (17... f5 18. Nb3 Qe7 19. Qh5+ Qf7 20. Qf3 Rc8 21. Nxd4 e5 22. Re1 Rxc4 23. Qa8+ Ke7 24. Nc6+ Kf6 25. Qxa6 Qd5 26. Na7 Ra8 27. Qb5 Qc5 28. Rd1 Rc1 {0-1 Nemes,S-Murariu,A/Felix Spa 2007})) 15... Ke7 $1 16. Nb3 ({The black king has been "self-imprisoned" in the centre, but White's attack has run out of steam. Thanks to the central pawn mass the black king is adequately protected, while the reduced material does not help White. Moreover, Black's minor piece (bishop vs knight) will prove superior in any endgame. White will most likely capture Black's temporary extra pawn. In view of all this, the position is unclear and dynamically balanced, though I tend to prefer Black. Other moves chosen by White are:  a)} 16. Nf3 f5 17. Rad1 Qd7 (17... Qc8 18. Qxc8 (18. Nxd4 Bxd4 19. Qxc8 $2 Bxf2+ $17 {Pomerleano,D-Vigorito,D/Philadelphia 2004}) 18... Rhxc8 19. Nxd4 Rc5 $11) 18. Qd5 Rac8 19. Nxd4 Bxd4 20. Qxd4 Rhg8 $13 {Hammer,J-Lie,K/Tonsberg 2008.}) ({b)} 16. Qe4 Kf8 (16... Re8 17. Qxh7 Kf8 18. Nf3 f5 19. Rad1 Rc8 20. b3 $14 {Magem Badals,J-Gallego Jimenez,V/Palencia 1999}) (16... Qb6 17. Nf3 Rhd8 18. Qxh7 Kf8 19. h4 Ra7 20. Rad1 f5 21. Ng5 $14 {Socko,M-Dziuba,M/Warsaw 2008}) 17. Nf3 f5 18. Qd3 Qb6 19. b3 Bf6 $11 {Zarnicki,P-Hoffman,A/Buenos Aires 1999.}) 16... f5 17. Rad1 Qc8 $1 {Black always welcomes a transition to an ending. If now 18.xc8?! hxc8 19.xd4 d7! 20.b3 c5 Black has a small but permanent plus.} (17... Rc8 18. Qxa6 Qc7 19. Nxd4 Bxd4 20. Rxd4 Ra8 21. Qb5 Qc5 22. Qxc5 dxc5 23. Rd5 Kf6 24. Rxc5 Rhb8 25. Rb1 Rxa2 26. f4 Rbxb2 27. Rxb2 Rxb2 28. Rc8 {½-½ Grafl,F-Dvoirys,S/Bad Wiessee 2002 is another story.}) 18. Qf3 $6 ({Best was} 18. Qd5 $1 Be5 $5 19. Rxe5 dxe5 20. Qxe5 Qb8 $1 21. Qxd4 Rd8 22. Qh4+ Ke8 {, with White retaining compensation for the sacrificed material.}) 18... Qxc4 $1 {Brave, but at the same time also compulsory! Without this move Black's position would be very unpleasant.} 19. Rc1 $2 {An "easy" but ineffective move.} ({I believe that White should have gone down the following line:} 19. Qxf5 Rac8 20. Qg4 Rhg8 21. Nxd4 Bxd4 22. Qxd4 Qxd4 23. Rxd4 Rc2 24. Rb4 Rg5 $1 $15 {. Of course, when viewed from a practical angle, it is hardly easy for White to admit the error of his ways and accept transition to an inferior ending!}) 19... Qb4 $1 20. Rc7+ ({Equally bad was} 20. a3 Qb8 {, when the b3-knight has lost its firm support.}) 20... Kf6 $1 21. Rf1 ({A sad square for the rook, but the alternative} 21. Rec1 Rac8 $1 {(exploiting the weakness of White's back rank)} 22. a3 (22. Rxc8 Rxc8 23. Rxc8 Qe1#) (22. g3 Rxc7 23. Rxc7 Qe1+ 24. Kg2 Qe4) 22... Qb8 {would not improve White's critical situation.}) 21... h5 {Defending against White's threat of 22.h5.} 22. a3 Qa4 {Preventing the activation of the white knight, while at the same time preparing ...ab8. White's position is desperate because he has failed to coordinate his pieces, while Black is utilizing his extra material to defend his king. The position does not offer White any hope for survival any more and all that is required from Black is some care and accuracy!} 23. Nd2 d5 $1 24. Qf4 $2 {A blunder in a lost position.} Bh6 $1 25. Qd6 Bxd2 26. Qe7+ Ke5 $1 {The black king is perfectly safe in the centre of the board.} 27. Rd7 (27. Qxf7 Qe8 28. Qg7+ ({or} 28. f4+ Ke4 $1) 28... Kd6 {would not change anything.}) 27... Rh7 28. Qd6+ Kf6 0-1


