ewice 1981.}) ({c)} 14. Bg5 Bxf3 15. exf3 (15. Bxf3 Nxf3+ 16. exf3 Qd7 17. Na4 Qf5 $15 {Roca,A-Bronstein,L/Buenos Aires 1985}) 15... h6 16. Be3 Ra3 17. Bxd4 exd4 18. Ne4 Nxe4 19. fxe4 $11 {Woerdemann,M-Pfrommer,C/Wuerzburg 1991.}) 14... exd4 {Efstratios Grivas: 'transposes to the lines above.'} 15. Ne4 Nxe4 16. Bxe4 (16. dxe4 $2 Ra2 17. Rb2 Qa5 $1 $17 (17... Rxb2 18. Bxb2 d3 19. Bxg7 $1 dxe2 20. Qd4 exf1=Q+ 21. Bxf1 $44)) 16... d5 (16... Ra6 17. Bf4 (17. Re1 Re8 18. Bf4 g5 19. Bd2 Bf6 $11 {Hernandez,R-Martin del Campo,R/Bayamo 1990}) 17... f5 18. Bg2 g5 19. Bd2 f4 $13 {Larsen,B-Portisch,L/Montreal 1979.}) (16... Re8 17. Re1 d5 18. cxd5 cxd5 19. Bf3 Qd7 20. Bf4 Bf5 {½-½ Rosiak,A-Kujawski,R/Porabka 1986}) (16... Qd7 17. Re1 (17. Rb6 $6 d5 18. cxd5 cxd5 19. Bg2 Rfe8 20. Re1 Ra1 $17 {Anikaev,Y-Tal,M/Minsk 1979}) 17... d5 18. cxd5 cxd5 19. Bg2 Rfe8 20. Qc2 h5 21. h4 Ra6 22. Bf4 Rae6 $11 {Besser,H-Bade,H/Germany 1988}) 17. cxd5 cxd5 18. Bf3 Bxf3 19. exf3 $11) ({For} 13. Bg5 {see the game Andersson,U-Yrjola,J/Helsinki 1991.}) 13... exd4 14. Ne4 (14. bxc6 $5 dxc3 (14... bxc6 {transposes to the lines above.}) 15. cxb7 Rb8 16. Be3 Qd7 17. Ba7 d5 18. Bxb8 Rxb8 19. Qc2 Rxb7 20. Rxb7 Qxb7 21. Rb1 Qc7 22. cxd5 $13 {.}) 14... Nxe4 15. Bxe4 d5 $1 $146 {Efstratios Grivas: '!'} ({Efstratios Grivas: 'Black takes advantage of the placement of the e4-bishop, gaining important central space. Possible also is'} 15... Re8 16. Rb2 d5 17. cxd5 cxd5 18. Bg2 Ra1 {Augustin,J-Tal,M/Moscow 1977.}) 16. cxd5 ({After} 16. Bg2 dxc4 $1 17. dxc4 (17. bxc6 cxd3 18. Qxd3 bxc6 19. Bxc6 Ra2 20. Re1 Bf5 21. Be4 Bxe4 22. Qxe4 Re8) 17... Ra2 $1 18. Re1 ({or} 18. Rb2 Rxb2 19. Bxb2 d3 $3 20. Bxg7 dxe2) 18... d3 $1 {Black is much better} {(} 19. Qxd3 Rxe2 $1 {).}) 16... cxd5 17. Bf3 $2 ({Efstratios Grivas: 'Practically 'forced', as after any other retreat of the e4-bishop the white e2-pawn would come under unbearable pressure (...a2 and ...e8). An example is'} 17. Bg2 $15 {×d5} Re8 18. Re1 Qd7 19. Qc2 h6 20. b6 Re7 21. Bf4 Rae8 $15 {Marschner,J-Klundt,K/Germany 1989.}) 17... Bxf3 18. exf3 Qd7 $1 {Efstratios Grivas: 'Black's advantage is considerable. The doubled d-pawns control important central squares, in sharp contrast to the white doubled f-pawns that don't contribute much. Moreover, the presence of the b-pawns favours Black as the white pawn on b5 is easier to get at and thus weaker than the black one on b7. Finally, the c1-bishop is only apparently a better piece than the g7-bishop (due to the presence of the d4-pawn); a more careful examination reveals that the c1-bishop does not have a satisfactory square to move to as it must keep a3 and c3 under control, preventing an invasion by the black rook. '} 19. Re1 Rfc8 $17 {Efstratios Grivas: '!' Efstratios Grivas: 'Black cannot expect anything special from using the e-file; in fact, White could in that case proceed with relieving exchanges. '} 20. Qe2 ({White is running out of satisfactory moves, as neither} 20. Bd2 Ra3 $1) ({nor} 20. Bb2 Rc5 $1 {is of much help. Now, the threat of 21.e7! with counterplay against the b7-pawn forces Black's hand.}) 20... Re8 21. Qd2 h5 $1 {Opening another front, as the threatened ...h4-h3 can only be met by a further weakening of the white pawn-structure.} 22. h4 Rac8 $1 {Threatening an invasion by 23...c3.} 23. Rxe8+ Qxe8 $1 {All of Black's pieces are optimally placed, maximizing the dynamic potential in his position. On e8, the queen controls the e-file while also eyeing the b-pawn, while the c8-rook is ready to penetrate White's ranks.} 24. Kg2 Rc3 25. Qg5 $2 ({A mistake in time trouble. White ought to remain passive with} 25. Qd1 {when his position is unpleasant, but Black would have to work to prove his superiority} {(} Qc8 $5 {, intending ...f5 or ...c2,} ({or} 25... Kh7 $5 {intending ...h6).})) 25... Qe1 $1 {The threat of 26...c2! forces White to retreat.} 26. Qd2 Qxd2 27. Bxd2 Rxd3 28. Bb4 Bf8 $1 {The resulting rook ending is won for Black as the passed d-pawns are very powerful and the black king will quickly be centralized.} 29. f4 Bxb4 30. Rxb4 Kf8 31. Kf1 Ke7 32. Ke2 Ra3 $1 {Black returns his "optical" material advantage. The white f4-pawn is hardly a worthy opponent for the black passed d-pawn as it is doubled and devoid of prospects. In effect, Black has an extra pawn.} 33. Rxd4 Kd6 34. Rb4 f5 $1 {Preventing any counterplay involving a future sacrifice with f5.} 35. Rb2 d4 36. Kd2 Kd5 {0-1 (36) Dedes,N (2310)-Grivas,E (2465) Iraklion 1992 CBM 121 [Efstratios Grivas] The ending is easily won as Black enjoys several advantages: centralized king, passed extra pawn, more active rook.} *


