wska,J/Krynica 1995.}) ({c)} 10. Bg5 {see the game Velikov,P-Grivas,E/Khania 1992.}) ({d)} 10. Ne1 c6 11. b3 (11. e3 Nf5 12. e4 Nd4 13. Nc2 Nb3 14. Bg5 h6 15. Bxf6 Bxf6 16. Ne3 Nd4 17. Nc2 Bg7 $15 {Martinovic,S-Velimirovic,D/Zemun 1980}) 11... Be6 12. e3 Nf5 13. Nf3 h6 14. e4 Ne7 15. d4 Qc7 16. h3 a4 $13 {Petrosian,T-Sax,G/Vrbas 1980.}) 10... axb4 11. axb4 c6 ({Also possible is} 11... Nxf3+ 12. Bxf3 c6 13. Bg5 Bh3 14. Re1 Qc7 15. Bxf6 Bxf6 16. Qb3 Be7 17. b5 Rfc8 18. Ra1 h5 19. Ra4 h4 20. Rea1 Rxa4 21. Qxa4 Be6 22. gxh4 Bxh4 23. bxc6 bxc6 24. c5 Be7 25. cxd6 Qxd6 26. Ne4 Qd4 27. Qxd4 exd4 {½-½ Gausel,E-Malisauskas,V/Oslo 1992.}) 12. b5 ({The alternative is} 12. Nd2 d5 (12... Bd7 13. Bb2 Qc7 14. e3 Nf5 $11 {Vaganian,R-Kantsler,B/Moscow 1991}) (12... Bg4 13. h3 Bd7 14. Bb2 Nh5 15. e3 Ne6 16. Nb3 f5 $13 {Pasman,M-Taulbut,S/Groningen 1977}) 13. Bb2 (13. b5 Be6 14. Bb2 Re8 15. Re1 h5 16. e3 Nf5 17. bxc6 bxc6 18. cxd5 cxd5 $11 {Perez,R-Martin del Campo,R/Santa Clara 1997}) 13... Be6 14. Re1 b5 15. cxb5 cxb5 16. e3 Nc6 17. Nxb5 Qb6 18. Nc3 Nxb4 19. Nf3 Nd7 $11 {Hickl,J-Nijboer,F/Venlo 2000.}) 12... Bg4 13. Nxd4 ({This natural move is the start of White's problems. Instead, he should proceed with the exchange of the b-pawns (now or in the next move) and, more concretely with} 13. bxc6 bxc6 (13... Bxf3 $2 14. c7 $1 (14. exf3 bxc6 15. f4 exf4 16. Bxf4 Ra3 17. Ne2 Nxe2+ 18. Qxe2 Re8 19. Qc2 $14 {Woerdemann,M-Fleger,H/Germany 1988}) 14... Qxc7 {(½-½ Skalkotas,N-Grivas,E Athens 1992) but White is better:} 15. exf3 Qa5 16. Nb5 Nxb5 17. Rxb5 Qc7 18. f4 $16) {d)} 14. Nxd4 ({and now: a)} 14. e3 Nxf3+ 15. Bxf3 Bxf3 16. Qxf3 d5 (16... Qc7 $5 17. Bd2 Nd7 18. Qd1 Ra6 19. Qc2 Rfa8 $13 {Zielinska,J-Dworakowska,J/Warsaw 1995}) 17. cxd5 cxd5 18. e4 d4 (18... Qa5 19. Bd2 (19. Rb3 $2 d4 20. Nb1 Rfc8 21. Ra3 Qb4 22. Rxa8 Rxa8 23. Nd2 Nd7 $17 {Spiridonov,N-Akopian,V/Yerevan 1989}) 19... d4 20. Nd5 Qxd2 21. Nxf6+ Bxf6 22. Rfd1 $11) 19. Nd1 Nd7 20. Bd2 Nc5 21. Rb5 Ne6 22. Nb2 Rb8 $11 {Negulescu,A-Kasparov,G/Dortmund 1980.}) ({b)} 14. Re1 Rb8 15. Rxb8 Qxb8 16. Nxd4 exd4 17. Ne4 Nxe4 18. Bxe4 c5 $11 {Rosiak,A-Sygulski,B/Lubniewice 1981.}) ({c)} 14. Bg5 Bxf3 15. exf3 (15. Bxf3 Nxf3+ 16. exf3 Qd7 17. Na4 Qf5 $15 {Roca,A-Bronstein,L/Buenos Aires 1985}) 15... h6 16. Be3 Ra3 17. Bxd4 exd4 18. Ne4 Nxe4 19. fxe4 $11 {Woerdemann,M-Pfrommer,C/Wuerzburg 1991.}) 14... exd4 {Efstratios Grivas: 'transposes to the lines above.'} 15. Ne4 Nxe4 16. Bxe4 (16. dxe4 $2 Ra2 17. Rb2 Qa5 $1 $17 (17... Rxb2 18. Bxb2 d3 19. Bxg7 $1 dxe2 20. Qd4 exf1=Q+ 21. Bxf1 $44)) 16... Ra6 (16... Re8 17. Re1 d5 18. cxd5 cxd5 19. Bf3 Qd7 20. Bf4 Bf5 {½-½ Rosiak,A-Kujawski,R/Porabka 1986}) (16... Qd7 17. Re1 (17. Rb6 $6 d5 18. cxd5 cxd5 19. Bg2 Rfe8 20. Re1 Ra1 $17 {Anikaev,Y-Tal,M/Minsk 1979}) 17... d5 18. cxd5 cxd5 19. Bg2 Rfe8 20. Qc2 h5 21. h4 Ra6 22. Bf4 Rae6 $11 {Besser,H-Bade,H/Germany 1988}) 17. Bf4 (17. Re1 Re8 18. Bf4 g5 19. Bd2 Bf6 $11 {Hernandez,R-Martin del Campo,R/Bayamo 1990}) 17... f5 18. Bg2 g5 19. Bd2 f4 $13 {Larsen,B-Portisch,L/Montreal 1979.}) ({For} 13. Bg5 {see the game Andersson,U-Yrjola,J/Helsinki 1991.}) 13... exd4 14. Ne4 (14. bxc6 $5 dxc3 (14... bxc6 {transposes to the lines above.}) 15. cxb7 Rb8 16. Be3 Qd7 17. Ba7 d5 18. Bxb8 Rxb8 19. Qc2 Rxb7 20. Rxb7 Qxb7 21. Rb1 Qc7 22. cxd5 $13 {.}) 14... Nxe4 15. Bxe4 d5 $1 ({Black takes advantage of the placement of the e4-bishop, gaining important central space. Possible also is} 15... Re8 16. Rb2 d5 17. cxd5 cxd5 18. Bg2 Ra1 {Augustin,J-Tal,M/Moscow 1977.}) 16. cxd5 ({After} 16. Bg2 dxc4 $1 17. dxc4 (17. bxc6 cxd3 18. Qxd3 bxc6 19. Bxc6 Ra2 20. Re1 Bf5 21. Be4 Bxe4 22. Qxe4 Re8) 17... Ra2 $1 18. Re1 ({or} 18. Rb2 Rxb2 19. Bxb2 d3 $3 20. Bxg7 dxe2) 18... d3 $1 {Black is much better} {(} 19. Qxd3 Rxe2 $1 {).}) 16... cxd5 17. Bf3 ({Practically 'forced', as after any other retreat of the e4-bishop the white e2-pawn would come under unbearable pressure (...a2 and ...e8). An example is} 17. Bg2 Re8 18. Re1 Qd7 19. Qc2 h6 20. b6 Re7 21. Bf4 Rae8 $15 {Marschner,J-Klundt,K/Germany 1989.}) 17... Bxf3 18. exf3 Qd7 {Black's advantage is considerable. The doubled d-pawns control important central squares, in sharp contrast to the white doubled f-pawns that don't contribute much. Moreover, the presence of the b-pawns favours Black as the white pawn on b5 is easier to get at and thus weaker than the black one on b7. Finally, the c1-bishop is only apparently a better piece than the g7-bishop (due to the presence of the d4-pawn); a more careful examination reveals that the c1-bishop does not have a satisfactory square to move to as it must keep a3 and c3 under control, preventing an invasion by the black rook.} 19. Re1 Rfc8 $1 {Black cannot expect anything special from using the e-file; in fact, White could in that case proceed with relieving exchanges.} 20. Qe2 ({White is running out of satisfactory moves, as neither} 20. Bd2 Ra3 $1) ({nor} 20. Bb2 Rc5 $1 {is of much help. Now, the threat of 21.e7! with counterplay against the b7-pawn forces Black's hand.}) 20... Re8 21. Qd2 h5 $1 {Opening another front, as the threatened ...h4-h3 can only be met by a further weakening of the white pawn-structure.} 22. h4 Rac8 $1 {Threatening an invasion by 23...c3.} 23. Rxe8+ Qxe8 $1 {All of Black's pieces are optimally placed, maximizing the dynamic potential in his position. On e8, the queen controls the e-file while also eyeing the b-pawn, while the c8-rook is ready to penetrate White's ranks.} 24. Kg2 Rc3 25. Qg5 $2 ({A mistake in time trouble. White ought to remain passive with} 25. Qd1 {when his position is unpleasant, but Black would have to work to prove his superiority} {(} Qc8 $5 {, intending ...f5 or ...c2,} ({or} 25... Kh7 $5 {intending ...h6).})) 25... Qe1 $1 {The threat of 26...c2! forces White to retreat.} 26. Qd2 Qxd2 27. Bxd2 Rxd3 28. Bb4 Bf8 $1 {The resulting rook ending is won for Black as the passed d-pawns are very powerful and the black king will quickly be centralized.} 29. f4 Bxb4 30. Rxb4 Kf8 31. Kf1 Ke7 32. Ke2 Ra3 $1 {Black returns his "optical" material advantage. The white f4-pawn is hardly a worthy opponent for the black passed d-pawn as it is doubled and devoid of prospects. In effect, Black has an extra pawn.} 33. Rxd4 Kd6 34. Rb4 f5 $1 {Preventing any counterplay involving a future sacrifice with f5.} 35. Rb2 d4 36. Kd2 Kd5 {The ending is easily won as Black enjoys several advantages: centralized king, passed extra pawn, more active rook.} 0-1


