1. d4 d5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Bg5 Nbd7 4. e3 {Nigel Davies: '!?' '!?'} ({This looks rather harmless but there are some subtle effects compared with} 4. Nf3 {. For one thing White keeps open the option of advancing his f-pawn; in some positions he might also bring his queen out to f3...}) 4... g6 ({After} 4... e6 {I suggest} 5. Qf3 $5 {which prepares queenside castling but also supports a pawn storm with a later g2-g4. Meanwhile White's queen is relatively safe from harassment because the e6-pawn restricts the activity of Black's light-squared bishop. A sample variation is} Be7 6. O-O-O O-O 7. g4 c5 8. h4 {with what I think is quite a promising position for White. Tests are required!}) ({For} 4... c6 {see Bricard-Todorov. Nigel Davies: 'see Bricard-Todorov. '}) 5. Bd3 ({For the immediate} 5. f4 {see the next game. It's not clear why Ermenkov delays this advance for so long; perhaps he wanted Black to castle first.}) 5... Bg7 6. Qd2 $5 $146 {Nigel Davies: '!?' '!?'} ({Nigel Davies: 'White can still transpose to Miles-Andersson with'} 6. Nf3 {Nigel Davies: '. The text lends the game an independent flavour.'}) 6... O-O 7. f4 c5 $1 ({Nigel Davies: 'Grivas felt that'} 7... c6 $6 {Nigel Davies: 'would have been poor in view of'} 8. O-O-O $40 {Nigel Davies: 'when White has dangerous attacking chances. While I'm not sure that Black is without resources in this position, the idea of castling long is certainly worth noting.'}) 8. Nf3 b6 9. Ne5 Bb7 10. Rd1 $1 ({Nigel Davies: 'According to Grivas'} 10. O-O $2 {Nigel Davies: 'is punished by'} Ne4 $1 11. Bxe4 $8 dxe4 12. Nxd7 Qxd7 13. Ne2 cxd4 14. exd4 ({Nigel Davies: 'or'} 14. Nxd4 e5 $17) 14... Ba6 $17 {Nigel Davies: '. Certainly White's position has no great appeal here.'}) 10... Ne8 $5 ({In this position} 10... Ne4 {fails to} 11. Bxe4 dxe4 12. Nxd7 Qxd7 13. dxc5 {etc.}) ({Gallagher mentions the possibility of} 10... cxd4 11. exd4 Ne4 {but this seems better for White after} 12. Nxe4 dxe4 13. Bb5 ({rather than Gallagher's} 13. Bc4 {, which is well met by} Nxe5 {followed by 14...Qc7}) 13... Nxe5 14. fxe5 Qc7 15. O-O {with more space and the better pawn structure.}) 11. O-O ({Nigel Davies: 'The attempt to win the d5-pawn with'} 11. Nxd7 $6 Qxd7 12. dxc5 bxc5 13. Bb5 {Nigel Davies: 'falls flat after' Nigel Davies: 'falls flat after '} Qc7 $1 14. Nxd5 ({Nigel Davies: 'or'} 14. Bxe8 Rfxe8 15. Nxd5 Bxd5 16. Qxd5 Rad8 $17) 14... Bxd5 15. Qxd5 Qa5+ 16. c3 Nc7 17. Qxc5 Nxb5 18. Bxe7 Rfc8 (18... Rfe8 {, when the piece is worth far more than the three (weak) pawns. Nigel Davies: ', when the piece is worth far more than the three (weak) pawns. '}) 19. Qb4 Qb6 $17) 11... Nd6 12. Bh4 Rc8 $1 {[ cd4, c4 c]} 13. Nb5 $1 {} Nxb5 14. Bxb5 Nxe5 15. fxe5 c4 $5 {Nigel Davies: 'Almost always a controversial decision because it presents White with an e3-e4 pawn lever.' Nigel Davies: 'Almost always a controversial decision because it presents White with an e3-e4 pawn lever. '} 16. c3 (16. Qb4 Rc7 17. Ba4 Bc8 $1 $11) 16... Bc6 17. Bxc6 Rxc6 18. e4 $1 $14 {Nigel Davies: '!' '!'} f6 $1 {} ({Nigel Davies: 'After'} 18... dxe4 $2 19. d5 (19. Qe2 {White wins the e4-pawn.}) 19... Rc5 20. d6 $16) 19. exf6 Bxf6 20. Qe1 $1 Bxh4 $1 21. Qxh4 ({Nigel Davies: 'White can also interpose'} 21. Rxf8+ Qxf8 {Nigel Davies: 'before playing'} 22. Qxh4 {Nigel Davies: 'but then Black can hang on with'} dxe4 $1 23. Qxe4 Rf6 24. Qd5+ Qf7 25. Qa8+ Kg7 26. Qxa7 Qe6 $44 {Nigel Davies: 'with adequate counterplay.'}) 21... Rcf6 22. Rxf6 Rxf6 23. exd5 ({Nigel Davies: 'After'} 23. Re1 {Nigel Davies: 'Black has'} e6 $1 $11 {Nigel Davies: '!' '!' Nigel Davies: ', gaining time with the threat of 24...Rf1+.'}) 23... Qxd5 24. Qg3 Qd6 $1 25. Qe3 Kf7 $1 26. Re1 Qe6 27. Qg3 ({Nigel Davies: 'In the pawn endgame Black can draw by eliminating his e-pawn:'} 27. Qxe6+ Rxe6 28. Rxe6 Kxe6 29. Kf2 Kd5 30. Ke3 e5 $1 $11 {Nigel Davies: '!' '!' Nigel Davies: 'with equality.'}) 27... Qf5 28. h3 Qf4 29. Kh2 h5 {[ g5, h4]} ({Nigel Davies: 'Another possibility was'} 29... g5 $5 {Nigel Davies: '.'}) 30. h4 Qf2 $1 $11 {[ f4] [ f4] Nigel Davies: '!' '!'} 31. Re4 $1 {} Qf5 ({Nigel Davies: 'Better than'} 31... Qxb2 32. Qc7 Qa3 33. Qxc4+ $14 {Nigel Davies: 'when White retains some chances.'}) 32. Qe3 Re6 33. Rxe6 Qxe6 34. Qf4+ ({Nigel Davies: 'Or'} 34. Qxe6+ Kxe6 35. Kg3 Kf5 36. Kf3 b5 $11 {Nigel Davies: 'etc.'}) 34... Kg7 1/2-1/2


