1. d4 f5 2. e4 fxe4 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bg5 Nc6 5. d5 (5. f3 e5 $1 6. dxe5 (6. d5 Nd4 7. fxe4 Be7 8. Nf3 Nxf3+ 9. Qxf3 O-O 10. Bc4 d6 11. O-O Nd7 12. Bxe7 Qxe7 $11) 6... Nxe5 7. fxe4 (7. Nxe4 $6 Be7 8. Bxf6 Bxf6 9. f4 Ng6 $15) 7... Bb4 8. Qd4 Qe7 9. Bxf6 Bxc3+ 10. Qxc3 Qxf6 11. O-O-O O-O $11) 5... Ne5 6. Qe2 {Glenn Flear: '!?' '!?' Glenn Flear: 'An interesting try to vary from the better known 6 Qd4.'} ({Glenn Flear: 'After the normal moves'} 6. Qd4 d6 $5 (6... Nf7 7. Bxf6 exf6 8. Nxe4 f5 9. Ng3 g6 10. O-O-O Bh6+ 11. f4 O-O {Black is doing OK, he has a safe-enough king and the bishop pair in the coming double-edged struggle, Panchenko, AG-Dovzik, J Uzhgorod 2007}) 7. Nxe4 (7. O-O-O) 7... c6 8. f4 Neg4 9. Bxf6 Nxf6 10. Nxf6+ gxf6 11. O-O-O Qb6 $13) 6... Nf7 (6... d6 7. O-O-O (7. Nxe4 Bf5 8. Ng3 Bg6 $13) 7... Bg4 (7... g6 {Ü 98/52}) 8. f3 exf3 9. gxf3 Bf5 10. f4 Ng6 11. Nf3 Qd7 $13) 7. h4 (7. Bxf6 exf6 8. Nxe4 Qe7 (8... Be7 9. d6 cxd6 10. O-O-O O-O {is also quite messy}) (8... Bb4+ $1 9. c3 Be7 10. d6 cxd6 11. O-O-O O-O {is recommended by Valeri Beim but White should then try} 12. Nh3 {heading for d5 with the other knight. The position is still unclear.}) 9. d6 Qe6 10. dxc7 d5 11. Nd2 Bd6 12. Qxe6+ Bxe6 13. Bb5+ Ke7 14. Ngf3 {was acceptable for Black who has the bishop pair to compensate for his isolani, Nemet, I-Cherniaev, A Biel 2006. However in this line Black could also consider throwing in a check with 8...Bb4+! as White, after playing c2-c3, is then unable to later use the c3-square to transfer his knight to d5. Beim recommends this approach but it's still far from clear-cut that this improves Black's chances that much.}) 7... c6 $5 (7... e5 8. dxe6 dxe6 9. Nh3 Be7 10. Nxe4 Nxe4 11. Qxe4 Qd5 12. Qxd5 exd5 13. Bxe7 Kxe7 $11) 8. O-O-O (8. Bxf6 gxf6 9. Qxe4 Qb6 (9... Bh6 10. Bc4 Qc7 11. dxc6 bxc6 12. Bxf7+ Kxf7 13. Nf3 Qf4 $11) 10. O-O-O Qxf2 11. Nf3 $44) 8... Qa5 ({Glenn Flear: 'Or perhaps more simply'} 8... cxd5 $5 9. Bxf6 (9. Nxd5 Nxd5 10. Rxd5 b6 11. g3 $6 Bb7 12. Rd4 Nxg5 13. hxg5 e6 14. Bg2 $6 Qxg5+ 15. Kb1 O-O-O {and Black was doing well and went on to win in Hrabusa, M-Potapov, P Salekhard 2007}) 9... gxf6 10. Nxd5 e6 11. Qxe4 Bh6+ 12. Kb1 O-O $13) 9. Bxf6 gxf6 10. Qxe4 {Glenn Flear: 'Beim (in his book Understanding the Leningrad Dutch) prefers White as Black has difficulty finding a satisfactory continuation. This game only partially bears him out.'} e6 $5 (10... Nd6 11. Qg4 c5 12. Kb1 Kd8 13. Nf3 b5 14. Nd2 Bb7 15. Nde4 Nxe4 16. Nxe4 d6 17. Be2 $14) (10... Kd8 $5 11. dxc6 bxc6 12. Qxc6 Rb8 13. Nf3 Bh6+ $44) 11. g4 (11. Nf3 cxd5 12. Nxd5 f5 13. Qe2 Bg7 14. Kb1 Kf8 $13) 11... Be7 (11... Bb4 $5 12. dxe6 dxe6 13. Nge2 Bd7 14. Qd4 O-O-O 15. Qxf6 Ne5 $44) 12. dxe6 dxe6 13. f4 Bd7 {Glenn Flear: '!?' '!?'} ({It's less provocative to cover the bishop first with say} 13... Nd6 $1 14. Qe3 Bd7 {when Black is ready to castle into safety and equality.}) 14. Rxd7 $5 (14. Nf3 O-O-O 15. Bd3 Bc5 $13) 14... Kxd7 15. Bc4 Nd8 16. Nf3 Kc7 $1 $146 (16... Re8 $2 17. Rd1+ Kc7 18. Qxh7 $16 (18. Qd3 Nf7 19. Qd7+ Kb6 20. Qxe6 Qxc3 21. bxc3 Ba3+ 22. Kd2 $16)) 17. f5 (17. Bxe6 $2 Ba3 $1 18. Kb1 Nxe6 19. Qxe6 Qb4 $17) (17. Rd1 $5 Bb4 18. Ne2 Rc8 19. a3 Bd6 20. Qd3 Bf8 21. g5 $44) ({After} 17. Nd4 {White will be able to capture the e-pawn and thus obtain some material compensation for the exchange.}) 17... Ba3 $1 {Glenn Flear: '!?' '!?' Glenn Flear: 'A counterattack from nowhere!'} (17... e5 18. g5 $16) 18. Qd3 (18. bxa3 Qxc3 19. fxe6 Qa1+ 20. Kd2 Qxh1 21. e7 Re8 $19) (18. Ne2 exf5 19. gxf5 Bd6 20. Rd1 Rc8 21. Qg4 Re8 22. Qg7+ Re7 23. Qxf6 Qc5 $13) 18... exf5 $1 19. bxa3 (19. gxf5 Bb4 20. Rg1 Rc8 $15) 19... fxg4 20. Nd4 Rc8 {Glenn Flear: 'The material balance has changed: White has two pieces for a rook but Black is ahead on pawns. Who is better?'} (20... Qxa3+ $5 21. Kd2 Qc5 22. Qg3+ Qe5 23. Qxg4 Re8 $13) 21. Qg3+ $6 (21. Ne4 $1 Kb8 (21... f5 22. Qg3+) (21... Qe5 22. Rf1 Rf8 (22... Kb8 23. Nxf6 Rc7 24. Nxg4 Qh5 25. Qf5 Qxh4 26. Qe5) 23. Rf5 Qh2 24. Nc5 $16) 22. Nxf6 h5 23. Kb2 Ka8 24. Rf1 c5 $13) 21... Qe5 22. Qxg4 f5 $1 {Glenn Flear: 'As the pawn cannot be captured White is obliged to regroup.'} 23. Qd1 (23. Nxf5 $4 Qxc3) 23... Kb8 24. Kb2 Rf8 25. Re1 (25. Rf1 f4) ({White could retain a solid grip on some key squares with} 25. Qd3 {followed by Rf1 and Nf3. White shouldn't be worse.}) 25... Qf4 26. Rf1 $2 {Glenn Flear: '?!' '?!'} (26. h5 c5 27. Nb3 Nc6 $15) ({White has a neat tactical continuation which may offer her a slight riskless edge:} 26. Be6 $1 Rc7 (26... Nxe6 $2 27. Nxe6) 27. Bxf5 Qxh4 (27... Rxf5 $2 28. Nxf5 Qxf5 29. Qxd8+) 28. Rh1 Qf6 29. Rxh7) 26... Qxh4 27. Rh1 (27. Nxf5 Qxc4 28. Qd6+ Ka8 29. Ne3 Qxf1 30. Nxf1 Rxf1 31. Qd7 Rb8 32. Qxh7 Nf7 $17) 27... Qe7 28. Bd3 {Glenn Flear: 'Krush has rather panicked into giving up her h-pawn for nothing, probably as a result of her chronic addiction to time trouble.'} Qe5 29. Nf3 Qg7 30. Qe1 Rc7 $1 $17 31. Qe5 {Glenn Flear: '?' '?' Glenn Flear: 'White should keep queens on as now it becomes much easier for Black to use his rooks actively.'} Qxe5 32. Nxe5 {Glenn Flear: 'White's chances would have been better if Black no longer had his kingside pawns!'} Ne6 33. Kc1 Nc5 34. Nf3 Rg7 $1 35. Kd2 Rg2+ 36. Be2 (36. Ke3 Re8+ 37. Kf4 Nxd3+ 38. cxd3 Rc2 $17) 36... Ne4+ 37. Nxe4 fxe4 38. Ng1 $6 (38. Nd4 Rd8 39. Ke3 Rxd4 40. Kxd4 Rxe2 $19) (38. Ne1 Rd8+ 39. Ke3 Rg3+ 40. Kf4 Rdg8 $17) 38... e3+ $6 (38... Rf1 $1 $19 {Glenn Flear: 'is also rather strong!'}) 39. Kxe3 $6 (39. Ke1 Rff2 40. Bd3 h5 (40... Rxc2 41. Bxc2 Rxc2 42. Ne2 Rxa2 43. Rxh7 Rxa3 $17) 41. Ne2 Rh2 $17) 39... Rfg8 $1 40. Rxh7 (40. Nf3 Re8+ $19 {Glenn Flear: 'also wins material and leaves Black with a decisive advantage.'}) 40... Rxg1 {[ 9/o]} 41. Kd4 R1g7 42. Rh6 {Glenn Flear: 'Even without damaged pawns White is unlikely to be able to hold as in most cases 'Rook and Three Pawns versus Bishop and Three Pawns' on the same wing is a win.'} Kc7 43. Kc3 a5 44. a4 Rg3+ 45. Kb2 Kb6 46. Bc4 R8g6 47. Rh7 Rg7 48. Rh8 R3g4 49. Bb3 Kc5 (49... c5 $2 50. c4 Rg2+ 51. Ka3 $11) 50. Ra8 b6 51. Rf8 R7g5 52. Ra8 Rh4 53. a3 $6 (53. Ra7 Rgh5 54. Rg7 (54. Ra8 Rh8 55. Ra7 R4h7) 54... b5 $19) 53... Rg6 54. Ra7 Rhg4 55. Ra8 Rg7 {Glenn Flear: 'There is no hurry!'} 56. Kc3 Rh7 57. Kb2 Rgh4 58. Rg8 R7h5 59. Rf8 Re5 60. Ra8 Kd6 61. Rd8+ Kc7 62. Rg8 c5 $1 {Glenn Flear: 'Finally! Black finds a good plan.'} 63. Rg7+ Kd8 64. Bg8 (64. Rb7 c4 65. Ba2 Re6 66. Rf7 (66. Kc3 Kc8 67. Ra7 Re3+ 68. Kb2 c3+ 69. Kb3 Kb8 70. Rg7 b5 $19)) 64... Rxa4 65. Rb7 (65. c4 Re3) 65... Rg4 66. Rxb6 Kc7 67. Re6 Rxe6 68. Bxe6 Rg3 69. Bc4 Kd6 70. Be2 {Glenn Flear: 'After'} Kd5 {Glenn Flear: 'White had had enough.'} 71. Bb5 c4 72. Bd7 Kd4 73. Bb5 Rg6 {White has a choice between two hopeless continuations:} 74. Be8 ({or} 74. a4 Rg3 75. Bd7 Kc5 76. Bb5 Kb4 77. Bc6 Re3 78. Bd7 c3+ 79. Ka2 Re2 {and something has to give}) 74... Rb6+ 75. Kc1 Kc3 76. Ba4 Rh6 77. Kb1 Rh1+ 78. Ka2 Rc1 0-1


