1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. g3 Bb7 5. Bg2 Be7 6. O-O O-O 7. Nc3 Ne4 8. Qc2 Nxc3 9. Qxc3 d6 ({Of course Black can vary: a)} 9... Be4 10. b3 {and now: a6)} d6 ({a1)} 10... f5 11. Bb2 Bf6 12. Ne1 Bxg2 13. Nxg2 c5 {(½-½ Hort,V-Petrosian,T/Las Palmas 1973)} (13... Nc6 14. Qd2 Ne7 15. Rad1 Ng6 16. f3 h5 17. e4 h4 18. exf5 exf5 19. f4 $14 {Nogueiras,J-Quezada,Y/Merida 2005}) 14. Qd2 Nc6 15. dxc5 (15. e3 {½-½ Popov,N-Mnatsakanian,E/Yerevan 1977}) 15... Bxb2 16. Qxb2 bxc5 17. Rad1 $14 {.}) ({a2)} 10... c6 11. Bb2 d5 12. Ne5 (12. cxd5 cxd5 13. Ne5 Bxg2 14. Kxg2 f6 15. Nc6 Nxc6 16. Qxc6 Kf7 17. Rfc1 Qb8 18. Qb5 Qb7 19. Rc6 Rac8 20. Rac1 Rfd8 21. a4 Rxc6 22. Qxc6 Qxc6 23. Rxc6 Bd6 24. Bc1 {½-½ Gheorghiu,F-Browne,W/Manila 1976}) 12... Bxg2 13. Kxg2 Bd6 (13... Bf6 14. Rfd1 $1 (14. Ng4 Nd7 15. cxd5 cxd5 16. Nxf6+ Nxf6 17. Rac1 Rc8 18. Qd3 Qd7 {½-½ Panno,O-Najdorf,M/Netanya 1975}) 14... Bxe5 15. dxe5 Qe7 16. e4 dxe4 17. Qe3 Na6 18. Qxe4 Rac8 19. Rd6 $16) 14. Rfd1 f6 15. Nd3 Nd7 16. cxd5 cxd5 17. Qc6 Qe7 18. Rac1 $14 {Graf,A-Nguyen Anh Dung/Jakarta 1997.}) ({a3)} 10... Nc6 11. Bb2 (11. Ne5 Bxg2 12. Kxg2 Nxe5 13. dxe5 d6 14. Bf4 $14) 11... d5 12. Rad1 (12. Rfd1 Rc8 13. Ne5 Nxe5 14. Bxe4 Nxc4 15. Bxh7+ Kxh7 {½-½ Gheorghiu,F-Keene,R/Netanya 1977}) 12... Qd7 13. Ne5 Nxe5 14. dxe5 Bxg2 15. Kxg2 c6 16. e4 $14 {.}) ({a4)} 10... d5 11. Bb2 Nd7 12. cxd5 exd5 (12... Bxd5 13. Rac1 Rc8 14. Rfd1 c5 15. Ne5 Nf6 16. Qd3 Bxg2 17. Kxg2 Qd5+ 18. Qf3 cxd4 19. Nc6 Bc5 20. Nxd4 a6 21. a3 $14) 13. Bh3 (13. Rac1 Bd6 14. Rfd1 Re8 15. e3 Qf6 16. Ne1 Bxg2 17. Kxg2 {½-½ Gheorghiu,F-Rashkovsky,N/Sochi 1976}) 13... Bxf3 14. Qxf3 Nf6 15. Rac1 $14 {Morais,V-Dias,P/Lisbon 1999.}) ({a5)} 10... Qc8 11. Bb2 Qb7 (11... d6 12. Qe3 (12. Ne1 Bxg2 13. Nxg2 Bf6 14. Qd2 Qb7 15. Rad1 Nd7 16. Rfe1 Rfe8 17. e4 $14 {Steinberg,M-Fucak,E/Sochi 1968}) 12... d5 13. Bh3 Qd8 14. cxd5 Bxd5 15. Qd3 $14 {Guimard,C-Rossetto,H/Buenos Aires 1942}) (11... Bf6 12. Ne5 (12. Ne1 Bxg2 13. Nxg2 c5 {(½-½ Gufeld,E-Taimanov,M/Sukhumi 1972)} 14. Qd2 Nc6 15. d5 Bxb2 16. Qxb2 exd5 17. cxd5 Nd4 $13 {Popov,L-Udovcic,M/Tel Aviv 1964}) 12... Bxg2 13. Kxg2 Qb7+ 14. f3 d6 15. Ng4 Nd7 16. e4 $14) 12. Bh3 (12. Ne1 Bxg2 13. Nxg2 Bf6 14. Rad1 c5 15. e3 Qf3 16. Qc2 Na6 17. dxc5 Bxb2 18. Qxb2 Nxc5 $14 {½-½ Osnos,V-Khasin,A/Leningrad 1956}) 12... Bf6 (12... Bxf3 13. exf3 c5 14. Qd2 Bf6 15. Bg2 $14) 13. Nd2 Bf5 14. Bg2 $14 {.}) 11. Bb2 Nd7 12. Ne1 (12. Nd2 $5 Bxg2 13. Kxg2 e5 14. dxe5 dxe5 15. Rad1 $14 {Jakob,S-Ernst,R/Switzerland 1993}) (12. Rac1 f5 13. Rfd1 Bf6 14. Ne1 e5 15. dxe5 Bxe5 16. Qd2 Bxb2 {½-½ Grivas,E-Stefansson,H/Athens 1993}) 12... Bxg2 13. Nxg2 (13. Kxg2 c6 14. Nf3 d5 15. Rac1 Rc8 16. Rfd1 $14 {Malich,B-Barcza,G/Decin 1975}) 13... c6 14. e4 (14. Rfd1 d5 15. cxd5 cxd5 16. Rac1 Rc8 17. Qxc8 Qxc8 18. Rxc8 Rxc8 19. Rc1 Rxc1+ 20. Bxc1 $11 {Tkachiev,V-Jobava,B/Benidorm 2007}) 14... d5 15. e5 $14 {.}) ({b)} 9... f5 10. b3 Qe8 (10... d6 {transposes to the main game}) 11. Bb2 Bf6 12. Qd2 (12. Rad1 d6 13. Qd2 (13. Ne1 Bxg2 14. Nxg2 Nd7 15. Qf3 a5 16. Nf4 g5 17. Nd3 Bg7 18. e4 $14 {Filip,M-Bobekov,P/Prague 1950}) 13... Nd7 14. Rfe1 Qh5 15. Ne5 Nxe5 16. dxe5 $14 {Stark,M-Santasiere,A/Baltimore 1948}) 12... Nc6 (12... a5 13. Rac1 (13. Ne1 Bxg2 14. Nxg2 Nc6 {½-½ Gruenfeld,E-Pirc,V/Belgrade 1952}) 13... Na6 14. c5 $14) 13. d5 exd5 (13... Nd8 14. Nd4 d6 15. f4 exd5 16. cxd5 Qf7 17. Rac1 $16 {Dizdarevic,E-Atalik,S/Sarajevo 2004}) 14. cxd5 Ne7 15. Ne5 d6 16. Nc4 $14 {.}) ({c)} 9... Bf6 10. b3 d6 (10... Be4 11. Bb2 d6 12. Rfd1 Nd7 13. Qd2 $14 {Schuh,F-Pokojowczyk,J/Tapolca 1986}) (10... c5 {transpose to 9...c5}) 11. Qd3 (11. Bb2 Nd7 12. Qc2 g6 13. Rad1 Bg7 14. e4 $14 {Mikhalchishin,A-Rotstein,A/Austria 2007}) 11... Qc8 12. Ng5 g6 13. Ne4 Bg7 14. Bg5 f5 15. Nc3 Bxg2 16. Kxg2 Nc6 17. d5 Nb4 18. Qd2 $14 {Visier Segovia,F-Pomar Salamanca,A/Palma de Mallorca 1966.}) 10. b3 Nd7 11. Bb2 f5 12. Qe3 ({Also good is} 12. Ng5 Bxg5 (12... Bxg2 $2 13. Nxe6 Qc8 14. Kxg2 Rf6 15. d5 $18 {Georgiev,K-Schneiders,A/San Bernardino 1988}) 13. Bxb7 Rb8 14. Bg2 Bf6 (14... Qe7 15. f4 Bf6 16. e4 $14 {Kretchetov,A-Manukian,G/Las Vegas 2005}) (14... Nf6 15. Qd3 $14 {Rodgaard,J-Celis,S/Turin 2006}) 15. Qc2 g6 16. e4 $14 {Meduna,E-Reznicek,J/Prague 1979.}) 12... Kh8 $1 ({A forced move as} 12... Be4 13. Nd2 (13. Ne1 d5 14. f3 f4 15. gxf4 Bf5 16. Nd3 $16 {Pakleza,Z-Praxmarer,C/Aschach 2006}) 13... d5 14. f3 f4 15. gxf4 Bf5 16. Qc3 Bd6 17. e3 $16 {McNab,C-Ellison,D/Isle of Man 1993}) ({or} 12... Kf7 13. Ne5+ Nxe5 (13... dxe5 14. Bxb7 Rb8 15. Bc6 $16 {Lobo Rodriguez,J-Nachon Menendez,G/Candas 1997}) 14. Bxb7 Rb8 (14... Ng4 15. Qf3 Rb8 16. d5 $16 {Prameshuber,A-Reilly,B/Munich 1958}) 15. Bg2 Ng4 16. Qd3 Kg8 17. e4 $16 {Levin,J-Yanofsky,D/Ventnor City 1942 are not satisfactory.}) 13. Qxe6 Be4 14. c5 $1 bxc5 (14... d5 $2 15. c6 Nf6 16. Ne5 $18 {.}) 15. dxc5 Nxc5 16. Qc4 Bf6 17. Bd4 (17. Nd4 $5 {.}) 17... Bxd4 18. Nxd4 Bxg2 19. Kxg2 $14 a5 20. Qd5 (20. Ne6 $5 Nxe6 21. Qxe6 Qe8 22. Qxe8 Rfxe8 23. e3 a4 24. b4 a3 25. Rfc1 $14 {.}) 20... Qf6 21. Rac1 Qf7 22. Qxf7 Rxf7 23. Rc2 Kg8 24. Nc6 Ra6 25. Nxa5 $1 Rxa5 26. b4 Rb5 27. bxc5 Rxc5 28. Rxc5 dxc5 29. Rc1 Re7 30. Kf3 Re5 31. Rd1 (31. a4 $5 Kf7 32. a5 c4 33. Rxc4 Rxa5 34. Rxc7+ Kf6 35. g4 $1 $16 {.}) 31... c4 32. Rc1 Ra5 33. Rxc4 Rxa2 34. Rxc7 Ra4 35. Rc5 g6 36. Rc7 Rb4 37. Rd7 Ra4 {If Black's f-pawn were on f7, then the draw would be simple and easy, with the ...h5 advance on some appropriate move. Now, this position if full of poison for him, so he must be very careful. White must opt for the thematic g4 or e4 advance (depending on Black's reactions), under favourable circumstances. But there are also two important minuses in White's position: the active black rook and the presence of his pawn on g3, which is not allowing the manoeuvre g3, with f3 and e4 to follow.} 38. e3 ({White would like not to push his e-pawn so early, as he needs manoeuvring space around his king. But} 38. h3 h5 $1 39. h4 Kf8 40. Ke3 Re4+ 41. Kd3 Ra4 42. f3 Ra1 43. Ke3 Ra4 44. Rd4 Ra2 {is not helping. White's problem is the activity of the black rook. If this rook had been placed passively (let's say on a7-square) then White could proceed with f4 and f3, e4, achieving a won position.}) 38... Rb4 39. h3 h5 $1 {A somehow forced reaction. Black must exchange as many pawns as possible. Also, his king must be liberated from the protection of his "weak" h-pawn.} 40. Rd4 ({White would feel happy if he could emerge with a passed e-pawn, but this cannot be achieved. After} 40. h4 Rb2 $1 (40... Rb6 $2 41. Kf4 Ra6 42. f3 Rb6 43. e4 fxe4 44. fxe4 $18) 41. Rd1 Kf7 42. Re1 Kf6 43. Re2 Rb4 {he cannot make any serious progress.}) 40... Rb2 41. g4 hxg4+ 42. hxg4 fxg4+ ({Here comes the first serious question: what happens if Black just stays put? Well, after} 42... Kf7 43. g5 ({there is no meaning on} 43. Kg3 Re2 44. Rd3 Kf6 45. f3 Kg5 46. gxf5 gxf5 47. Ra3 Rxe3 $11) 43... Ke6 44. Ra4 Kf7 45. Kg3 Rb7 (45... Rb3 46. Kf4) 46. Kf4 Rc7 47. f3 Rc5 $1 ({a forced continuation, avoiding the immediate penetration of the white king. After} 47... Rb7 $2 48. Ra5 Rb4+ 49. Ke5 Rb3 50. Ra7+ Ke8 51. Kf6 Rxe3 52. Ra8+ Kd7 53. Kxg6 Rxf3 54. Kf7 {White wins}) 48. Ra7+ Kg8 49. e4 fxe4 50. fxe4 Kf8 51. Rd7 (51. e5 Rc4+ 52. Kf3 Rc1 $1 (52... Rc5 $2 53. Ke4 Rb5 (53... Rc4+ 54. Kd5 Rg4 55. e6 $18) 54. Kd4 Kg8 55. Rc7 Ra5 56. Rc5 Ra7 57. Kd5 Ra1 58. Kd6 $18) 53. Ke4 Rg1 54. Kd5 Rxg5 55. Kd6 Rg1 56. Ra8+ Kg7 57. e6 Rd1+ 58. Ke7 g5 $1 (58... Rb1 $2 59. Ke8 g5 60. e7 $18) 59. Ke8 Kf6 60. e7 Re1 61. Ra6+ Kf5 $11) 51... Ra5 52. Rd5 Ra7 53. Ke5 Ke7 54. Rb5 Rc7 $1 (54... Kf7 $2 55. Kd6 Ra6+ 56. Kd5 Ra1 57. Rb7+ Kf8 58. Rc7 Rg1 59. Ke6 $18) {White cannot make any progress:} 55. Kd5 ({or} 55. Rb6 Rc5+) 55... Rd7+ {.}) 43. Rxg4 Kf7 44. Ra4 Kf6 45. Kg3 Rb3 46. Kf4 Rb2 47. Ra6+ Kf7 48. f3 Rb3 49. e4 ({White would be happy if he could place his king on e5 square with his pawn on e4 and f4, as then he will get winning chances. But this is only an illusion:} 49. Rd6 g5+ $1 50. Ke4 Rb1 51. Kf5 Rg1 $1 (51... Rf1 $2 52. Rf6+ Ke7 53. Kxg5) 52. e4 Rg3 53. Rf6+ Ke7 54. Ke5 Rh3 55. Rf5 Rg3 $11 {.}) 49... Rc3 50. Ra7+ Ke6 51. Kg4 Re3 52. Ra6+ Kf7 53. Rb6 ({Nothing can be achieved with} 53. Ra4 {trying to achieve a position with f4 and Kg5, as again Black's active rook is on the alert:} Re1 $1 54. Ra3 (54. f4 Rg1+ 55. Kf3 Rf1+ 56. Ke3 Ke7 (56... Re1+ $2 57. Kd4 Rf1 58. Ke5 $18) 57. Ra6 Kf7 58. Rc6 Kg7 59. Rc7+ Kf6 60. e5+ Ke6 61. Rg7 Rg1 $11) 54... Kf6 55. Kf4 g5+ 56. Kg3 Rg1+ 57. Kf2 Rb1 58. Ra6+ Kf7 $11 {.}) 53... Re1 54. Kg5 Rg1+ 55. Kf4 Ra1 56. Rd6 (56. Rb3 Kf6 {.}) 56... Ra3 57. e5 {If White is not able to penetrate into Black's camp through the kingside, then he needs the e5-square for his king. If he cannot do that also, then at some point he has to try the e5 advance.} Ra1 58. Rd7+ Ke6 59. Rd6+ Kf7 60. Rf6+ Kg7 61. Rc6 Kf7 62. Kg3 Ra5 63. Kf4 Ra1 64. Rb6 Ra2 65. Ke3 Ra4 66. f4 Ra3+ 67. Ke4 Ra4+ 68. Kf3 Ra1 $1 {This is the right defence for Black, not allowing g4-g5-h6. If the white king were already on g4, then he would win with 69.b7+ e6 70.g5.} 69. Rf6+ Kg7 70. Rd6 Kf7 71. Rd7+ Kf8 72. Rc7 Ra2 73. Ke3 Ra4 74. Rd7 Ra3+ 75. Ke4 Ra4+ 76. Rd4 Ra5 77. Rd7 Ra4+ 78. Kf3 Ra1 $1 79. Rc7 Ra2 80. Kg3 Ra1 81. Rb7 Ra2 82. Rd7 Ra1 83. Kf3 Ra2 84. f5 {"Accepting" the draw, as White has already tried every possible idea. The end was easy:} gxf5 85. Kf4 Ke8 86. Rb7 Ra6 $1 87. Kxf5 Rc6 88. e6 Rc1 $1 {Black defended in an excellent way, a model one for this kind of positions. He kept his rook active and he was not afraid of any ghosts. White was unlucky that his pawn structure did not help him.} 1/2-1/2


