1. Nf3 Nf6 2. d4 e6 3. c4 Bb4+ 4. Nbd2 b6 5. g3 ({White's main option is} 5. a3 {- see game Grivas,E-Gazis,E/Kallithea 2002.}) 5... Bb7 (5... O-O 6. Bg2 c6 $5 7. O-O d5 8. Qc2 Nbd7 (8... Bb7 9. e4 Na6 10. a3 Be7 11. b4 c5 12. cxd5 exd5 13. e5 $14 {Eljanov,P-Werle,J/Wijk aan Zee 2007}) (8... Be7 9. e4 Bb7 10. b3 Nbd7 11. Bb2 Rc8 12. Rad1 $14 {Kaidanov,G-Seirawan,Y/Key-West 1994}) 9. e4 Bb7 10. e5 Ne8 11. a3 Be7 (11... Bxd2 12. Bxd2 dxc4 13. Ng5 $16) 12. Rd1 Nc7 13. b3 c5 14. Bb2 $14 {Grivas,E-Maksimovic,B/Khania 1992.}) 6. Bg2 O-O ({For} 6... c5 {see game Kummer,H-Knoll,H/Hartberg 2003.}) 7. O-O d5 ({Black's options are various: a)} 7... Bxd2 8. Bxd2 {and now: a5)} d6 ({a1)} 8... Be4 9. Rc1 d6 10. b4 (10. Re1 Nbd7 11. Bc3 Qc8 12. Bf1 Re8 13. Nd2 Bb7 14. e4 $14 {Jeremic,V-Lajthajm,B/Backa Palanka 2002}) 10... Nbd7 11. Qb3 Qe7 12. Rfd1 c6 13. Bh3 h6 14. Ne1 Bh7 15. Bg2 Ne4 16. Be3 e5 17. a3 $14 {Almeida Quintana,O-Comas Fabrego,L/Manresa 2004.}) ({a2)} 8... Ne4 9. Bf4 d6 10. Qc2 (10. Ng5 d5 11. Nxe4 dxe4 12. Qc2 f5 13. Rad1 Nd7 14. f3 Nf6 15. Be5 $14) 10... Qc8 11. Rfd1 f5 12. Rac1 $14 {Charkhalashvili,I-Khotenashvili,B/Tbilisi 2001.}) ({a3)} 8... a5 9. Rc1 (9. a3 d6 10. Qc2 Nbd7 11. Rfd1 Qc8 12. Rac1 Ne4 13. Be1 f5 14. d5 $1 $14 {Saenz,J-Bruned,Y/San Sebastian 2000}) (9. Bg5 d6 10. c5 Na6 11. cxb6 cxb6 12. Rc1 $14 {Nazarenus,M-Lipok,C/Willingen 2004}) 9... Be4 10. c5 $14 {.}) ({a4)} 8... d5 9. Rc1 (9. cxd5 $5 Bxd5 (9... exd5 10. Ne5 Nbd7 11. Bg5 {transpose to Grivas,E-Managadze,N/Athens 2001}) 10. Bf4 $14) 9... dxc4 10. Rxc4 Bd5 11. Rc1 Nbd7 12. Bf4 c5 13. Bd6 Re8 14. dxc5 Nxc5 15. Bxc5 bxc5 16. Qa4 $14 {Morais,V-Aguiar,C/Lisbon 2004.}) 9. b4 (9. Qa4 Nbd7 10. Rfd1 a6 11. Rac1 Re8 12. Ne1 Bxg2 13. Nxg2 e5 14. dxe5 Nxe5 15. Bc3 $14 {Grivas,E-Schinis,M/Limmasol 1997}) (9. Qc2 Be4 (9... Nbd7 10. Ne1 (10. Rad1 Be4 (10... a5 $6 11. Rfe1 Be4 12. Qc1 Qc8 13. Bh3 d5 14. Ne5 dxc4 15. f3 Bb7 16. Nxc4 $16 {Ftacnik,L-Donaldson Akhmilovskaya,E/Portland 1991}) 11. Qa4 Qc8 12. Bg5 $14 {Grivas,E-Tzoumbas,A/Aegina 1996}) 10... Bxg2 11. Nxg2 c5 12. dxc5 Nxc5 13. Rad1 Qe7 14. Bg5 Nb7 15. Rd4 h6 16. Bxf6 Qxf6 17. Rfd1 $14 {Grivas,E-Halkias,S/Iraklion 1993}) 10. Qa4 Qe8 11. Qa3 Nbd7 12. Rac1 Qe7 13. Rfd1 c5 14. dxc5 dxc5 15. Qe3 $14 {Grivas,E-Gogolis,A/Athens 1999}) (9. b3 Nbd7 10. Bc3 Qc8 11. Qd3 Be4 12. Qe3 $14 {Mascarinas,R-Rogers,I/Cebu 1992}) 9... Nbd7 10. Qc2 Be4 11. Qb2 Qe7 12. a4 c5 13. Rfd1 Rfd8 14. a5 $14 {Mamedyarov,S-Postny,E/Mainz 2006.}) ({b)} 7... Be7 {transposes to Topalov,V-Gelfand,B/Monte Carlo 1999.}) ({c)} 7... a5 8. Qc2 Na6 (8... Bxd2 9. Nxd2 $5 (9. Bxd2) 9... Bxg2 10. Kxg2 d5 11. Nf3 Ne4 12. Be3 Na6 13. Rac1 c5 14. Rfd1 $14 {Grivas,E-Zoler,D/Panormo 2001}) 9. e4 Bxd2 10. Nxd2 d6 11. b3 e5 12. d5 Nc5 13. a3 Qe7 14. Bb2 Rfe8 15. Rae1 Ncd7 16. f4 $14 {Grivas,E-Efstathiou,D/Khania 1987.}) 8. cxd5 exd5 9. Ne5 Bd6 ({Black can also prefer: a)} 9... Be7 10. b3 (10. Qc2 c5 11. Ndf3 Na6 $1 12. Bf4 (12. Bg5 Ne4 13. Bxe7 Qxe7 14. dxc5 bxc5 15. Nd3 Rac8 $13 {Grivas,E-Rodriguez Cespedes,A/Athens 1984}) 12... Ne4 13. Qa4 $14 {Grivas,E-Stoica,V/Sofia 1986}) 10... c5 (10... a5 11. Bb2 Na6 12. e3 (12. Re1 Ne4 13. Nxe4 dxe4 14. Rc1 f6 15. Nc6 Bxc6 16. Rxc6 Nb4 17. Rc1 (17. Bxe4 $5 f5 18. Bf3 Nxc6 19. Bxc6 Rc8 20. Qd3 $44) 17... f5 18. a3 Nd5 19. e3 Qd7 20. Qc2 Rad8 21. Qc6 Qc8 22. Re2 Rd6 23. Qc4 Qd7 24. Rec2 {½-½ Ivanchuk,V-Polgar,J/Wijk aan Zee 2008}) 12... c5 13. Qe2 Re8 14. Rfd1 Bf8 15. Rac1 $14 {Ivanchuk,V-Markus,R/Turin 2006}) 11. dxc5 (11. Bb2 Nc6 12. Nxc6 Bxc6 13. Rc1 Bb5 14. dxc5 Bxc5 15. Nb1 Ba6 16. a3 Re8 17. Re1 Ne4 18. e3 Qg5 19. f4 Qe7 20. Be5 Bb7 21. b4 Bd6 22. Bxd6 Qxd6 23. Nc3 Nxc3 24. Rxc3 a5 25. Qd4 axb4 26. axb4 Ra4 27. Rb1 Qe6 28. Rb2 h6 29. Kf2 Ra1 30. Rc7 {½-½ Ivanchuk,V-Nisipeanu,L/Las Vegas 1999}) 11... bxc5 12. Bb2 Nbd7 13. Nxd7 Qxd7 14. e4 $1 Rfd8 (14... d4 15. Re1 Qe6 16. e5 Nd5 17. Nc4 $14) 15. exd5 Bxd5 16. Nc4 Bxg2 17. Kxg2 Qb7+ 18. Qf3 Qxf3+ 19. Kxf3 $14 {Topalov,V-Gelfand,B/Monte Carlo 1999.}) ({b)} 9... Re8 10. Ndf3 (10. a3 $5 Bf8 (10... Bxd2 11. Bxd2 c5 12. Be3 $14) 11. b4 Nbd7 12. Bb2 c5 13. bxc5 bxc5 14. Rb1 $14 {Gelfand,B-Goldin,A/Moscow 1989}) 10... Ne4 (10... Nbd7 11. Bf4 Bd6 12. Rc1 $14 {Jankovic,A-Kjartansson,D/Balatonlelle 2000}) (10... Bd6 11. Bf4 c5 12. Rc1 $14 {Sakaev,K-Balashov,Y/Ekaterinburg 2002}) (10... h6 11. Bf4 Nh5 12. Bd2 Bd6 13. Qc2 $14 {Gurevich,D-Chernin,A/New York 1988}) 11. Be3 (11. Bf4 Bf8 12. Qc2 c5 13. dxc5 bxc5 14. Rfd1 $14 {Paunovic,D-Polugaevsky,L/Belgrade 1988}) 11... Bd6 12. Nd3 c5 13. dxc5 bxc5 14. Rc1 Na6 15. Nd2 d4 16. Bf4 Bxf4 17. Nxf4 $14 {½-½ Grivas,E-Kurajica,B/Elista 1998.}) ({c)} 9... Bxd2 10. Bxd2 Nbd7 11. Bg5 {transpose to Grivas,E-Managadze,N/Athens 2001} Nxe5 12. dxe5 h6 13. Bxh6 gxh6 14. exf6 Qxf6 15. Rc1 (15. Qb3 Rad8 16. Rfd1 Rfe8 17. e3 c5 18. Rd2 Re6 19. Rad1 $14 {Grivas,E-Managadze,N/Athens 2001}) 15... c5 (15... Qd6 16. e3 c5 17. Rc4 $14) 16. b4 cxb4 17. Rc7 $14 {.}) 10. Ndc4 $1 Be7 (10... Ne4 11. Nxd6 Nxd6 (11... cxd6 12. Nd3 Nd7 13. Qb3 a5 14. Bf4 $16 {Kopylov,M-Seils,J/Germany 2007}) 12. Qc2 c6 13. b3 Re8 14. Ba3 $16 {Gurevich,D-Landenbergue,C/Geneve 1992}) (10... Re8 11. Bg5 Be7 12. Ne3 h6 13. Bxf6 Bxf6 14. f4 Na6 15. Nf5 c5 16. e3 Nc7 17. Qg4 $16 {Gelfand,B-Giorgadze,G/Uzhgorod 1987.}) 11. Ne3 ({The white knight has significantly improved its prospects by its transfer to e3, from where it both pressurizes the d5-pawn and eyes the f5-square. Also good seems to be} 11. Bg5 c6 12. Ne3 h6 13. Bxf6 Bxf6 14. f4 Nd7 (14... Na6 15. N3g4 Re8 16. Rc1 Rc8 17. e3 $14 {Poluljahov,A-Obukhov,A/St Petersburg 1997}) 15. Rc1 Nxe5 16. dxe5 Be7 17. Qd2 a5 18. Kh1 Re8 19. Nf5 Bb4 20. Qc2 Bf8 21. Rfd1 $14 {Lputian,S-Collutiis,D/Montecatini Terme 1999 or}) (11. b3 Qc8 12. Ne3 Rd8 13. Qc2 g6 14. Bb2) 11... Qc8 (11... Ne4 12. Nf5 $14 {Gassmann,V-Alkhazashvili,O/Germany 2005.}) 12. Qc2 $1 g6 13. b3 $1 {Since Black was forced to weaken his kingside with 12...g6, White places his dark-squared bishop on the long diagonal.} c5 14. Bb2 Na6 (14... Rd8 15. Rac1 {transposes to the aforementioned game Dizdar,G-Stucl,B/Celje 2003.} a5 16. Nd3 $1 $16 Na6 $6 17. dxc5 bxc5 18. Bxf6 Bxf6 19. Nxc5 $18 {Dizdar,G-Stucl,B/Celje 2003.}) 15. Rac1 Qe6 16. Nd3 $1 {Black is facing serious problems as White has some direct threats (dxc5, xf6 and f4) against the d5-pawn.} Nb4 $6 ({I believe that Black should have acquiesced in an inferior position with} 16... cxd4 17. Bxd4 {.}) 17. Nxb4 cxb4 18. Qc7 $1 {White wishes to bring about a favourable ending, as the doubled black b-pawns offer him a 5:4 majority in the centre and on the kingside. White has effectively "won" a pawn.} Rab8 19. Qe5 Bd6 20. Qxe6 fxe6 21. Rc2 Rbc8 22. Rfc1 Kf7 23. Rxc8 Bxc8 $1 {The exchange of a second pair of rooks, as well as any other exchange, would favour White, whose ultimate aim is a pawn ending! The c-file is hardly important, as White cannot make use of it in the near future.} 24. Rc2 Ke7 25. f3 Bb7 26. Nd1 Nd7 27. Bh3 a5 28. Bc1 e5 $6 {Black defends against White's threats (g5, f2 and e4) but creates further structural weakness (the isolated d5-pawn) in the process; as compensation he obtains the c5-square. It is hard to suggest anything better for Black, as he is condemned to defence in a passive position.} 29. Bg5+ Ke8 30. Be3 exd4 31. Bxd4 Bc5 $6 ({Black should therefore have opted for the immediate} 31... Nc5 {. Piece exchanges only help White.}) 32. Bxc5 $1 ({Black's play would be justified after the very weak} 32. Bxd7+ $2 Kxd7 33. Bxc5 Rc8 $1 {and 34...bxc5, with the advantage!}) 32... Nxc5 33. Rd2 Ke7 34. Ne3 Rd8 35. Nc2 Bc6 36. Bg2 Ne6 37. f4 $1 Nc5 38. Kf2 Rd6 39. Ke1 Ne6 40. Nd4 $1 Bd7 41. Kd1 {During the last few moves White has improved the scope of his king and bishop. The next step is to exchange one more piece, but White is in no rush as Black cannot improve his position.} Nc5 42. Nc2 Be6 43. Bf3 Bf7 44. Rd4 Na6 45. Rd2 Nc5 46. e3 Be6 47. Nd4 Bd7 48. g4 $1 {White sets the correct plan in motion, namely the advance of the kingside majority (3:2).} Ne6 $6 {Black hopes to pressurize White's queenside pawns with his light-squared bishop, but this plan fails to materialize and therefore Black should have refrained from exchanging more pieces.} 49. g5 $1 Nxd4 50. Rxd4 Be6 {Having nailed down Black's kingside pawns, White plans the h4-h5 advance, which will either lead to an open file for the white rook to invade or to a further weakening of Black's kingside structure. In both cases White's advantage will reach decisive proportions.} 51. h4 $1 {Setting in motion the natural break!} Rd7 52. h5 gxh5 ({After} 52... Rd6 {White can continue either by bringing his king to d4 and his rook to h2, or by the direct} 53. h6 $1 Rd7 54. e4 dxe4 55. Rxd7+ Kxd7 56. Bxe4 Bg8 57. Kd2 {followed by d3-d4 and f5, winning easily.}) 53. Bxh5 Bf5 54. Bf3 Ke6 55. Rd2 Rd6 56. Ke1 $1 {The last detail! White will bring his king to g3, from where it will endeavour to exchange the light-squared bishops. Black is unable to react.} Rd7 57. Kf2 Rd6 58. Kg3 Ke7 59. Bg4 Be4 {Black desperately tries to avoid exchanges.} 60. f5 h6 $5 {Attempting to set up a defence on the dark squares after 61.g6 f6!.} 61. Kf4 $1 hxg5+ 62. Kxg5 Rf6 63. Rh2 $1 {White now wins easily as the "extra" pawn on f5 is very powerful.} Rf8 64. Rh6 Bb1 65. Rxb6 Bxa2 66. f6+ Rxf6 67. Rxf6 Bxb3 68. Rb6 1-0


