1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Nbd2 b6 5. a3 Bxd2+ (5... Be7 $6 {is not recommended:} 6. e4 Bb7 (6... O-O 7. e5 Ne8 8. Bd3 Bb7 9. Qc2 h6 10. O-O c5 11. Bh7+ Kh8 12. Be4 Qc7 13. d5 $16 {Topalov,V-Korfmacher,L/Frankfurt 1997}) (6... d5 7. e5 Ne4 8. Bd3 f5 (8... Nxd2 9. Bxd2 $16) (8... Bb7 9. O-O Nd7 10. cxd5 exd5 11. Re1 $16 Ng5 12. Nxg5 Bxg5 13. Qg4 O-O 14. Nf3 Bxc1 15. Raxc1 Re8 16. Bxh7+ Kxh7 17. Ng5+ Kg8 18. Qh5 Bc8 19. Qxf7+ Kh8 20. Qh5+ Kg8 21. Qh7+ Kf8 22. Qh8+ {1-0 Grivas,E-Papandreou,N/Ikaros 1995}) 9. exf6 Nxf6 10. O-O O-O 11. b4 $16 {Gonda,L-Fodor,T/Budapest 2006}) 7. Bd3 O-O (7... d6 8. Qe2 a5 9. e5 dxe5 10. dxe5 Nfd7 11. O-O $16 {Dzindzichashvili,R-Coudari,C/New York 1980}) 8. Qc2 g6 9. O-O d5 10. cxd5 exd5 11. e5 Ne8 12. b4 $16 {Grivas,E-Mitsakos,A/Athens 2006.}) 6. Qxd2 Bb7 7. e3 d6 (7... Ne4 8. Qd3 d5 9. b3 c5 10. Be2 O-O 11. O-O cxd4 12. exd4 Nd7 13. a4 $14 {Gelfand,B-Adams,M/Dos Hermanas 1995}) (7... O-O 8. Be2 Ne4 9. Qd3 f5 10. O-O Nc6 $5 (10... d6 {transposes to the main game}) 11. Nd2 Qh4 12. f3 Nf6 13. b4 Rae8 14. Bb2 d6 15. b5 Nd8 16. a4 $14 {Grivas,E-Pavlovic,M/Athens 1995.}) 8. Be2 Nbd7 9. b4 O-O 10. Bb2 Ne4 11. Qd3 f5 ({The main alternative is} 11... c5 12. O-O f5 13. dxc5 (13. Nd2 Qg5 14. f3 $1 {(here lies the difference between 11.d3! and 11.c2 - the e3-pawn is protected)} Nef6 15. Rad1 Rae8 16. dxc5 dxc5 17. Nb3 e5 18. Qc3 $14 {Henriksen,G-Fyllingen,R/Norway 1997}) 13... bxc5 14. Nd2 Qe7 15. Rad1 (15. Nb3 Rad8 16. f3 $14 {Kempinski,R-Ostrowski,L/Suwalki 1999}) 15... Ng5 16. f4 Nf7 17. e4 $14 {Grivas,E-Kindermann,S/Katerini 1992.}) 12. O-O Rf6 ({Other options for Black are: a)} 12... Qe7 13. Nd2 (13. Rad1 Ndf6 (13... Rf6 $6 14. d5 e5 15. Nh4 $1 g6 16. f3 Ng5 17. f4 Nf7 (17... Ne4 18. g4 $1 Rf7 19. gxf5 Qxh4 20. fxg6) 18. e4 $1 fxe4 19. Qxe4 Re8 20. Bd3 Qd8 21. f5 $16 {Browne,W-Zlochevskij,A/Philadelphia 1991}) 14. Nd2 Rae8 15. f3 Ng5 16. Rde1 h5 17. Bd1 $14 {Browne,W-Rohde,M/USA 1987}) 13... e5 (13... Nxd2 14. Qxd2 Rf6 (14... e5 15. c5 $1 $14) 15. f3 Rh6 16. Rf2 Qh4 (16... Rf8 17. a4 e5 18. a5 f4 19. exf4 exf4 20. axb6 axb6 21. Ra7 $16 {Yakovich,Y-Izeta,F/Sevilla 1994}) 17. g3 $14 {Petrosian,A-Reshevsky,S/Palma de Mallorca 1989}) 14. f3 (14. d5 Nxd2 15. Qxd2 $14) 14... Nxd2 15. Qxd2 Rae8 16. Rfe1 $14 {Gelfand,B-Pelletier,Y/Cap d'Agde 2002.}) ({b)} 12... Qf6 13. Nd2 Qg6 (13... Rae8 14. f3 Ng5 15. a4 Qg6 16. Qc2 $14 {Gelfand,B-Ionov,S/Klaipeda 1988}) 14. f3 Nef6 15. Qc3 (15. Rae1 a5 16. Bd1 axb4 17. axb4 e5 $13 {Georgiev,K-Rogers,I/Germany 1998}) 15... Rae8 16. Rae1 e5 17. Bd1 exd4 18. Qxd4 $14 {Gozzoli,Y-Postny,E/Cappelle la Grande 2007.}) ({c)} 12... a5 13. d5 e5 14. Nd2 Nxd2 15. Qxd2 Qe7 16. Bc3 axb4 17. axb4 Nf6 18. f3 b5 19. Ra5 bxc4 20. Bxc4 $14 {Kishnev,S-Lukov,V/Cappelle le Grande 1994.}) ({d)} 12... Ng5 13. Nxg5 Qxg5 14. d5 (14. f3 Rf6 15. Rf2 $14) 14... Rae8 (14... Nf6 15. g3 $14) 15. f4 Qe7 16. Bh5 Rd8 17. Bf3 $14 {Haritakis,T-Tzoumbas,A/Athens 1995.}) 13. d5 e5 ({A mistake, leaving Black's position in disarray. Instead he should choose between: a)} 13... Rg6 14. Rad1 (14. dxe6 Nf8 $1 15. c5 (15. Ne1 Nxe6 16. f3 Qg5 $1 17. f4 Qh4 18. Qc2 Rh6 19. Nf3 Qh5 $17 {Twardon,M-Nikolenko,O/Katowice 1993}) 15... Nxe6 16. cxd6 cxd6 $1 17. Rad1 (17. Rfd1 $6 N6g5 18. Qb3+ Kh8 19. Ne5 dxe5 $1 20. Rxd8+ Rxd8 21. Rd1 Nd2 $15) (17. g3 f4 18. Rac1 Qe7 $13) 17... Kh8 18. Qb5 $5 (18. Ne1 $2 N6g5 19. Kh1 Nh3 $1 {0-1 Gelfand,B-Illescas Cordoba,M/Madrid 1996}) 18... N4g5 $1 (18... f4 19. Qh5 Qf8 20. Bd3 $14) 19. Nxg5 Qxg5 (19... Nxg5 20. Qxf5 Be4 21. Qg4 Nf3+ 22. Bxf3 Rxg4 23. Bxg4 $14) 20. g3 f4 $1 (20... Rh6 21. f4 $16) (20... Qh6 21. Qxf5 Rf8 22. Qh5 Ng5 23. Qxh6 Rxh6 24. h4 Nh3+ 25. Kh2 Nxf2 26. Rc1 $16) 21. Qxg5 Nxg5 22. Bg4 Nf7 (22... Nf3+ 23. Bxf3 Bxf3 24. Rc1 $16) 23. Bh5 Ng5 $11) 14... e5 (14... Qe7 15. Ne1 a5 16. f3 Ng5 17. Nc2 exd5 18. cxd5 Ba6 19. b5 Nc5 20. Qd2 Bb7 21. Nd4 $14 {Kempinski,R-Aronian,L/Batumi 1999}) 15. Qc2 (15. Nd2 Qh4 16. Nxe4 fxe4 17. Qc2 Nf6 18. f4 Qh3 $11) 15... Rh6 16. g3 a5 (16... g5 $6 17. Nd2 Ndf6 18. f4 Nxd2 19. Qxd2 gxf4 20. exf4 e4 21. Qd4 $16 {Kempinski,R-Bartel,M/Warsaw 2002}) 17. Nd2 Nxd2 18. Rxd2 $14 {.}) ({and b)} 13... Rh6 $1 14. dxe6 $5 (14. Rad1 c5 (14... e5 15. g3 c6 16. Nh4 Rxh4 17. gxh4 Qxh4 18. f3 $1 (18. dxc6 $6 Bxc6 $13 {Saric,A-Sulava,N/Sibenik 2007}) 18... Ng3 19. dxc6 Bxc6 20. Rf2 $14) 15. dxe6 (15. g3 Rg6 16. Ne1 cxb4 17. f3 Nxg3 $1 18. hxg3 Rxg3+ $44 {Doettling,F-Sulava,N/Montpellier 2008}) 15... Nf8 16. bxc5 bxc5 $13) 14... Nf8 $6 (14... Rxe6 $1 {is the right continuation:} 15. Qb3 (15. Nd4 $6 Rg6 $1) (15. Rfd1 Rh6 $13) (15. Rad1 Rg6 16. Qb3 Kh8 17. g3 Qe7 18. Rfe1 Rf8 $13) 15... c5 16. Rfd1 Rg6 17. g3 Qe7 18. Rd3 $14) 15. Nd4 $1 Qh4 16. h3 Qg5 (16... g6 17. Bf3 Re8 18. c5 $1 dxc5 (18... Nxe6 19. Nxe6 Rxe6 20. Qd4 $16) 19. bxc5 Nxc5 20. Qc3 $16) (16... Rg6 17. Nxf5 Rxg2+ (17... Qxh3 18. Ne7+ Kh8 19. Nxg6+ $18) (17... Nc5 18. Nxh4 Nxd3 19. Nxg6 $18) 18. Kxg2 Nxf2+ 19. Kg1 $1 $18) 17. f4 $1 Qg6 18. Nxf5 $1 Qxf5 19. Bg4 Qg6 20. e7 $16 {Gershon,A-Aronian,L/Yerevan 2000.}) 14. Ne1 ({A bad move. Stronger is} 14. Nh4 $1 g6 15. f3 Ng5 16. f4 Ne4 17. Nf3 Qe7 18. Nd2 Nxd2 19. Qxd2 Rf7 20. e4 $16 {Miles,A-Mascarinas,R/Lugano 1986.}) ({(} 14. Nd2 Nxd2 15. Qxd2 $14 {Zhukova,N-Macieja,B/Internet 2004)}) 14... Rh6 15. g3 ({After} 15. f3 $2 Qh4 $1 16. fxe4 fxe4 17. Qd2 Qxh2+ 18. Kf2 Rf8+ {Black is winning.}) 15... Qg5 16. Ng2 Qg6 17. f3 ({Too early. White should prepare it with} 17. Qc2 {.}) 17... Ng5 ({The sacrificial continuation} 17... Nxg3 $1 {was good:} 18. hxg3 Qxg3 19. Qxf5 Rh2 20. Rf2 Nf6 $17 {.}) 18. h4 e4 ({Black realizes the difficulties after the "natural"} 18... Nf7 19. g4 $3 fxg4 20. fxg4 {and decides to complicate the position, seeking counterplay that will allow him to stay in the fight for a positive result.}) 19. Qd2 (19. Qc2 $1 Nxf3+ 20. Bxf3 Qxg3 $1 ({After} 20... exf3 21. Rxf3 {White has a strategically won position, Black being devoid of any counterplay.}) {Now a critical moment in the game has been reached. White, apart from his extra material, also has better placed pieces than the corresponding black ones (a8-rook, b7-bishop and d7-knight), which will struggle ever to occupy satisfactory posts.} 21. Bd1 $6 ({The return of the extra material with} 21. Bxe4 fxe4 22. Qxe4 Rg6 23. Rf5 Ba6 24. Rg5 Rxg5 25. hxg5 {would leave White with a positional advantage and in no danger. Naturally, the game continuation must also be good for White, but Black will have enough practical chances to cause serious headaches.}) 21... Rxh4 22. Rxf5 Rf8 $1 {The exchange of an important defender (the f5-rook) for a useless piece (the a8-rook) certainly suits Black.} 23. Rxf8+ {0-1 (33) Grivas,E (2495)-Gazis,E (2265) Chalkidiki 2002 CBM 128 [Grivas,Efstratios]}) 19... Nxf3+ 20. Bxf3 Qxg3 21. Bd1 Rxh4 22. Rxf5 Rf8 23. Rxf8+ Nxf8 24. Qc3 Rh6 25. Qc2 Rh4 26. Qc3 ({White reacts instinctively after realizing that the planned} 26. Qf2 $4 {loses to} Rh1+ $1 {, while the threat ...c8-h3 is strong.}) 26... Rh6 27. Qd4 ({White's chain of thought is broken and for that reason it would be better (from a practical viewpoint) to agree to a draw by repetition. From a theoretical viewpoint he could continue his effort with} 27. Qe1 $5 {, although then Black would enjoy rich tactical possibilities.}) 27... Qh2+ 28. Kf1 Rf6+ 29. Nf4 Ng6 30. Ke1 Ne5 (30... Nxf4 $1 31. exf4 e3 $1 {was simple.}) 31. Be2 g5 ({Black could have returned to the right path with} 31... Nf3+ 32. Bxf3 exf3 {.}) 32. Nh5 ({White could have played} 32. Qxe4 $1 gxf4 33. Bxe5 Qg1+ 34. Kd2 Qxe3+ 35. Qxe3 fxe3+ 36. Kxe3 dxe5 37. Ke4 {with a slight edge.}) 32... Rf2 33. Nf6+ Rxf6 0-1


