1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. g3 b6 4. Bg2 Bb7 5. O-O Be7 6. c4 O-O 7. Nc3 Ne4 8. Qc2 Nxc3 ({Black's main alternatives are: a)} 8... f5 9. Ne5 {and now: a3)} Nd6 ({a1)} 9... d5 10. cxd5 exd5 11. Qb3 Kh8 (11... a5 12. Be3 Kh8 13. Rac1 Bd6 14. Nb5 $16 Bxe5 $6 15. dxe5 Na6 16. Bxe4 $1 f4 (16... dxe4 17. Nxc7 $1 Nxc7 18. Bxb6 Rc8 19. Rfd1 $18) 17. Nxc7 Nxc7 18. Bxb6 $18 {Gabriel,C-Skembris,S/Portoroz 1993}) 12. Bf4 Bf6 13. Rfd1 c6 14. Rac1 (14. f3 Nxc3 15. bxc3 Nd7 16. Nxd7 Qxd7 $11 {Djingarova,E-Kovanova,B/Plovdiv 2008}) 14... Qe7 (14... Nd7 $2 15. Nxc6 Bxc6 16. Nxe4 $18) (14... g5 15. Be3 f4 16. gxf4 gxf4 17. Bxf4 Nxf2 18. Rf1 $1 Bg5 19. e3 $18) 15. Rc2 $14 {.}) ({a2)} 9... d6 $2 10. Nxe4 (10. Nd3 d5 11. Nf4 Qd7 12. Qb3 Nxc3 13. Qxc3 Bf6 14. cxd5 exd5 15. Qb3 c6 16. Be3 $14 {Gislason,G-Berg,E/Reykjavik 1996}) 10... Qc8 (10... Kh8 $2 11. Nxd6 Bxg2 12. Ndf7+ Kg8 13. Nxd8 Be4 14. Qxe4 fxe4 15. Nxe6 {1-0 Stanojevic,B-Pikula,R/Sozina 2004}) (10... fxe4 11. Bxe4 Bxe4 12. Qxe4 dxe5 13. Qxa8 Qxd4 14. Be3 Qxb2 15. Qxa7 Bd6 16. c5 $18 {Dogarescu,S-Baciu,O/Bucharest 2002}) 11. Nxd6 cxd6 12. Bxb7 (12. Nf3 Nc6 13. Bd2 Bf6 14. e3 Ne7 15. Rfc1 $16 {Bojda,L-Gasik,R/Hlohovec 1998}) 12... Qxb7 13. Nf3 $16 {Andreev,A-Dimitrov,I/Sofia 1960.}) 10. Bxb7 Nxb7 11. e4 Nd6 (11... Nc6 12. Nxc6 dxc6 13. Be3 $14) (11... fxe4 12. Qxe4 c6 13. Qg4 $1 (13. d5 Bf6 (13... Nd6 14. Qe2 exd5 15. cxd5 $14 {Atalik,S-Bindrich,F/Dresden 2007}) 14. Bf4 (14. dxc6 Nc5) 14... Nc5 15. Qe2 cxd5 16. cxd5 d6 17. Nd3 e5 18. Nxc5 bxc5 19. Bd2 $14) (13. b3 Nd6 14. Qd3 $14 {Przezdziecka,E-Lundberg,R/Barlinek 2007}) 13... Nd6 (13... Bf6 14. Ne4 $16) 14. d5 $1 $16) (11... d6 12. Nd3 (12. Nf3 Nc6 13. Qe2 (13. d5 Nb4 14. Qb1 fxe4 15. Nd4 $14 {Horvath,M-Rakay,K/Slovakia 1999}) 13... e5 14. dxe5 dxe5 15. exf5 Rxf5 16. Be3 $14) 12... Nc6 (12... Na5 $6 13. Nf4 Qc8 14. d5 $16 {Grebeniuk,S-Mashevsky,A/Kiev 2002}) 13. Be3 $14 {Brychta,D-Cely,J/Moravia 2002}) 12. exf5 Nxf5 13. Qe4 Na6 14. Rd1 c6 15. d5 Nc5 16. Qe2 exd5 17. cxd5 $14 {Ftacnik,L-Petrik,S/Detva 1977.}) 9. Qxc3 c5 10. b3 Bf6 (10... cxd4 11. Nxd4 Bxg2 12. Kxg2 Bf6 (12... Nc6 13. Bb2 (13. Nxc6 dxc6 14. Bb2 Bf6 15. Qc2 Bxb2 16. Qxb2 {½-½ Gligoric,S-Keres,P/Amsterdam 1971}) 13... Nxd4 14. Qxd4 Bf6 15. Qd2 Bxb2 16. Qxb2 {transposes})) 11. Bb2 cxd4 ({Alternatives are: a)} 11... Bxf3 12. Qxf3 Nc6 13. e3 $1 $14 {.}) ({b)} 11... d6 12. Rad1 Qe7 (12... Qc7 13. Qd2 Rd8 14. dxc5 (14. Rfe1 $5 Nd7 15. e4 $14) 14... dxc5 15. Qf4 Na6 16. Qxc7 Nxc7 17. Ne5 (17. Bxf6 gxf6 $10 {Andersson,U-Karpov,A/Biel 1990}) 17... Bxg2 18. Kxg2 $14) 13. Rd2 $5 (13. Qd2 Nd7 14. dxc5 Bxb2 15. c6 $1 Bxc6 16. Qxb2 Rfd8 (16... Nf6 17. Rd2 Rfc8 18. Rfd1 Ne8 19. Ne1 Bxg2 20. Nxg2 Rab8 21. e4 $1 b5 22. cxb5 Rxb5 23. Ne3 $1 $14 {Andersson,U-Beliavsky,A/Tilburg 1984}) 17. Rd4 Nf6 18. Rfd1 $14 {Ribli,Z-Short,N/Skelleftea 1989}) 13... Nd7 (13... Bxf3 $2 14. Bxf3 $1 Bxd4 15. Qd3 Bxb2 16. Bxa8 $16) (13... Nc6 $5 14. Qe3 Nxd4 15. Nxd4 cxd4 16. Bxd4 Bxd4 17. Rxd4 Bxg2 18. Kxg2 $14) 14. Qc2 Rac8 15. Qb1 Rfd8 16. Rfd1 $14 {Andersson,U-Stefansson,H/Havana 2001.}) ({c)} 11... Nc6 12. Qd2 d6 (12... d5 13. dxc5 Bxb2 (13... dxc4 $6 14. Bxf6 $1 (14. Qxd8 Rfxd8 15. Bxf6 gxf6 16. cxb6 cxb3 17. bxa7 bxa2 18. Rxa2 Rxa7 19. Rxa7 Nxa7 {½-½ Rashkovsky,N-Kuzmin,G/Baku 1977}) 14... Qxf6 15. bxc4 bxc5 16. Rab1 Ba6 17. Qc2 (17. Qd6 Rac8 18. Qxc5 Ne7 19. Qxa7 Bxc4 20. Nd2 $1 $16 {Ivkov,B-Andruet,G/Cannes 1986}) 17... Nb4 18. Qb3 Rab8 19. a3 Nc6 20. Qa4 $16 {Andersson,U-Nikolic,P/Thessaloniki 1984}) 14. Qxb2 bxc5 15. cxd5 exd5 16. Rfd1 Qd6 17. Rac1 $14 {Heyken,E-Dudek,R/Germany 1989}) 13. Rad1 Qe7 (13... Re8 14. Rfe1 Qe7 15. d5 exd5 16. Bxf6 Qxf6 17. Qxd5 Rad8 18. Qg5 Qxg5 19. Nxg5 Na5 20. Rd2 Bxg2 21. Kxg2 $14 {Ivkov,B-Evans,LM/Sao Paulo 1978}) 14. d5 (14. e4 e5 (14... cxd4 15. Nxd4 Rfd8 16. Rfe1 Nxd4 17. Bxd4 Bxd4 18. Qxd4 $14 {Ftacnik,L-Tiviakov,S/Polanica Zdroj 1995}) 15. d5 Nd4 16. Bxd4 (16. Nxd4 cxd4 17. f4 $14) 16... cxd4 17. Ne1 g6 18. Nd3 Bc8 19. f4 $14 {Ribli,Z-Andersson,U/Germany 2003}) 14... exd5 15. Bxf6 Qxf6 16. Qxd5 (16. cxd5 Nb4 17. a3 Na6 18. e4 $14 {Del Prado,J-Ramirez,J/Los Barrios 1995}) 16... Rfe8 17. Rd2 $14 {.}) 12. Nxd4 Bxg2 13. Kxg2 Nc6 ({The immediate} 13... d5 $6 {is tricky, and White should continue with} 14. Rad1 $1 (14. Rfd1 Nc6 15. Qc2 Nxd4 16. Bxd4 Rc8 (16... dxc4 17. Qxc4 $14) 17. Rac1 Bxd4 18. Rxd4 Qc7 19. e4 Qe5 20. Qd3 dxe4 21. Rxe4 Rcd8 22. Rxe5 Rxd3 23. Rc2 Rc8 $10 {Andersson,U-Brynell,S/Malmo 1994}) 14... Nc6 15. Qe3 Nxd4 16. Bxd4 Re8 (16... dxc4 17. Bc5) 17. Bxf6 Qxf6 18. cxd5 exd5 19. Qf3 $16 {.}) 14. Qd3 (14. Qd2 {was not good:} Bxd4 $1 15. Bxd4 d5 $1 $11) ({but also possible is} 14. Qe3 Qe7 (14... Qc8 15. Rfd1 (15. Rad1 Rd8 16. Kg1 Bxd4 17. Bxd4 d5 18. cxd5 Rxd5 19. Ba1 $14 {½-½ Seirawan,Y-De Firmian,N/Reykjavik 1990}) 15... Rd8 16. Qf3 (16. Rac1 Nxd4 17. Bxd4 Qb7+ 18. f3 Be7 19. Qe5 Bf8 20. Bb2 $14 {Nikolic,P-Stefansson,H/Reykjavik 1996}) 16... Ne5 17. Qe4 Ng6 18. Rac1 $14 {Beliavsky,A-Adams,M/Belgrade 1995}) 15. Rad1 (15. Rfd1 Rfd8 16. Rab1 Qc5 17. Nc2 Bxb2 18. Rxb2 a5 19. Nd4 a4 20. Rbd2 axb3 21. axb3 Nb4 22. Qf3 $14 {Andersson,U-Almasi,Z/Malmo 1994}) 15... Rfd8 16. Rd2 Bxd4 17. Bxd4 d5 {(½-½ Azmaiparashvili,Z-Almasi,Z/Pamplona 1996)} 18. cxd5 Rxd5 19. Bb2 Rxd2 20. Qxd2 Rd8 21. Qc3 $14 {.}) 14... Bxd4 (14... Qc8 15. Rfd1 Rd8 16. Rac1 Nb4 (16... a6 17. Qe4 Ne7 18. Ba3 Qb8 19. Rc2 b5 20. Bxe7 Bxe7 21. c5 $14 {Ribli,Z-Horvath,J/Austria 1999}) 17. Qd2 Qc5 18. a3 Nc6 19. b4 Qh5 20. Nf3 $14 {Fridman,D-Jussupow,A/Linares 1997}) (14... Rc8 15. Rad1 Ne7 16. Ba3 $14 {Grabarczyk,M-Kunin,V/Griesheim 2003.}) 15. Bxd4 d5 ({This is an attempt to improve Black's play.} 15... Nxd4 16. Qxd4 Qc7 17. Rfd1 {Ivkov,B-Dzindzichashvili,R/Tbilisi 1973, gives White a slight but enduring edge, and should be compared with Grivas,E-Ionescu,C/Elista 1998.}) 16. Bb2 $1 Rc8 ({Black's other options,} 16... dxc4 17. Qxc4) ({and} 16... d4 17. e3 $1 dxe3 18. Qxe3 {, also lead to a pleasant position for White, as his bishop will eventually prove its superiority over the black knight due to the fact that there are pawns on both sides.}) 17. cxd5 $1 Nb4 18. Qf3 $1 Qxd5 19. Rfd1 $1 Qxf3+ 20. Kxf3 {White has gladly accepted the exchanges offered by Black, ending up in a pleasant endgame where he has four basic factors on which to build: 1) Better minor piece (bishop vs knight), taking the pawn-structure into account. 2) Better-placed king (centralized), in contrast to the enemy monarch who will have difficulties in occupying a satisfactory position, either active or passive. 3) Possibility of a white rook invading Black's camp. 4) Good prospects of further improving his position, while Black can only sit and wait.} Nd5 $5 ({An interesting idea. Two other moves were unsatisfactory:} 20... Rc2 $2 21. Ba3 $1 a5 22. Bxb4 axb4 23. Rd4 {with material gain}) ({, and} 20... Rfd8 21. Rac1 $1 Nxa2 22. Rxd8+ Rxd8 23. Ra1 Nb4 24. Rxa7 $16 {.}) 21. e4 Ne7 22. Ba3 (22. Rd7 Nc6 23. Ke3 (23. Rc1 $4 Ne5+ $1) 23... Rfd8 {is interesting and similar to the game.}) 22... Rfe8 23. Rac1 $1 ({The exchange of one pair of rooks will enable the white king to breathe more freely and will further highlight the weak points of Black's position, as the remaining black pieces will have to take on greater defensive duties. Naturally,} 23. Rd7 $6 Nc6 $1 24. Ke3 Ne5 $1 {would only help Black.}) 23... Rxc1 24. Rxc1 Rc8 25. Rd1 $1 {The exchange of rooks would now be in Black's favour, as then White would surrender one of his aforementioned advantages, the possibility of invading Black's lines with his rook.} Nc6 26. Ke3 Rc7 27. e5 $1 {An apparently illogical move, placing the pawn on a square of the same colour as the bishop. However, this move essentially prevents the activation of the black king, who now cannot approach the centre unless Black decides to accept further pawn weaknesses. If Black waits passively then White will continue with f4, g4, d6, e4 and f5, gaining even more space and developing substantial pressure on Black's position.} f5 28. exf6 gxf6 29. Rc1 Kf7 30. Rc4 $1 {Now the white rook can swing to either side of the board. Working together with the strong bishop, it will create multiple problems for Black. The black king has improved its placement but Black's pawn-structure has deteriorated with the emergence of weak pawns.} e5 $6 {Black should have stayed passive, without exposing himself with pointless pawn moves that, although seemingly strong, actually create new targets.} 31. f4 $1 {With the idea to isolate one more black pawn (apart from h7) on e5 or f6. Black wisely opts for the latter since if he were left with a pawn on e5 then all pawn endings would be lost, due to the possibility of White creating an outside passed pawn.} exf4+ 32. Kxf4 Ke6 33. Bb2 Rc8 34. Ba3 Rc7 35. Ke4 Rc8 36. Ke3 {White has played some waiting moves to gain time and now prepares to increase the pressure with h4-h6 and b2. After the black pieces are tied to the protection of the kingside pawns, the white king will invade the queenside. A simple plan, but one that is very difficult for Black to oppose.} Kd5 37. Bb2 Re8+ 38. Kd3 Re6 $2 ({Black's position was difficult, but with this move he loses material. He should objectively have preferred the passive} 38... Rf8 39. Rh4 Rf7 40. a3 Ne5+ 41. Ke3 {with advantage for White.}) ({It should be noted that Black cannot play} 38... Ne5+ $2 39. Bxe5 Rxe5 (39... fxe5 40. Rc7 e4+ 41. Ke3) 40. Rc7 Rh5 41. h4 a5 42. Rb7 Kc6 43. Rf7 Rh6 44. Ke4 {, when White's superiority is more than obvious and Black's chances of survival minimal.}) 39. Rh4 a5 40. a3 $1 Ne5+ 41. Bxe5 fxe5 42. Rxh7 Rf6 43. Ke3 Rc6 44. Rd7+ $1 {The game is practically over as White has won material and is able to protect his position.} Ke6 45. Rd3 Kf5 46. h3 Rh6 47. g4+ Ke6 48. Ke4 Rf6 49. Rf3 1-0


