1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Bb4 3. g3 (3. Nd5 Bc5 4. Nf3 c6 5. Nc3 d6 6. e3) 3... Bxc3 4. bxc3 (4. dxc3 d6 5. Bg2 Nf6 6. e4 O-O 7. Be3 Be6) 4... Nf6 5. Bg2 O-O 6. e4 d6 7. Ne2 Be6 8. d3 c6 9. Rb1 (9. f4) 9... Qc8 (9... d5 10. exd5 cxd5 $6 11. d4 e4 (11... Nc6 {1-0 Abramovic,B-Krstic,P/Belgrade 2008.} 12. Rxb7 Na5 13. dxe5 Nxb7 14. exf6 Qxf6 $16 15. cxd5) (11... dxc4 12. dxe5 Qxd1+ $14 13. Kxd1 Ng4 14. Bxb7 Bf5 15. Rb2 Nxf2+ 16. Kd2 Nxh1 17. Bxa8) 12. Rxb7 dxc4 13. O-O Nbd7 14. Nf4 Bg4 15. f3 exf3 $2 16. Bxf3 Bxf3 17. Qxf3 Qa5) 10. Bg5 (10. h3 d5 11. exd5 cxd5 12. g4) 10... Bh3 (10... Nbd7 11. O-O h6 12. Bc1 d5) 11. Bxh3 Qxh3 12. Bxf6 gxf6 13. Ng1 (13. g4 b5 14. cxb5 cxb5 15. Ng1 Qg2 16. Qf3 Qxf3 17. Nxf3) 13... Qg2 14. Qf3 Qxf3 15. Nxf3 Na6 16. Nh4 {After a long theoretical variation (which is more extensively analysed in Grivas,E-Khetsuriani,B/Athens 2003) Black is stuck with a weak backward pawn on d7. Naturally, as often happens in this type of position, White's advantage is not really great, but it is static and consequently long-term, while the danger of defeat is significantly reduced. White's plans are simple and include the doubling of the major pieces on the d-file and the development of an initiative on both flanks. A nice, related example, can be found in the game Gheorghiu,F-Ree,H/Lone Pine 1979:} Nc5 17. Ke2 (17. Kd2) 17... Rad8 18. Nf5 Rfe8 19. Ne3 (19. f3 Rd7 (19... d5 20. d4) 20. d4 Ne6 21. d5 Nc5 22. Kd2) 19... a6 20. Rb6 (20. Rhd1 b5 21. f3 Rb8 22. d4 Na4 23. Kd2) 20... Rb8 21. Nf5 Na4 22. Rb3 Red8 (22... b5 23. cxb5 $2 {White had made good use of his position so far and should have now played 37.h5!. Next would be the advance of his g-pawn, supported by the white rooks. It is not necessary to offer specific variations as means of proof, as these plans would take up a lot of time and preparation. The only certain thing is that Black cannot effectively stop White's plan and, as a result, is condemned to defeat.} (23. Ra3 Kf8 24. Rb1 Red8 25. cxb5 axb5 26. c4) 23... axb5 $1 {The only move and a very good one, securing the draw. The question is, of course, why? The answer is simple! The lack of any satisfactory breakthrough favours the defending side. Both flanks have been blocked; as a result, White does not have at his disposal the most useful tool in such positions, i.e. the creation of a second front. This is an instructive and very significant strategic motif.} 24. Nxd6 Red8 25. Nf5 Nc5 26. Ne7+ Kg7 27. Nxc6 Ra8 28. Rxb5 (28. Nxd8 Rxa2+ 29. Ke3 Nxb3 30. Rb1 Nd2 31. Rd1 $14 {is quite similar:} Nb3 32. Nc6 Rc2 33. Na7 b4 34. cxb4 Nd4 35. Rd2 Rc7 36. Ra2 Nc2+ 37. Ke2 Nxb4) 28... Rxa2+ 29. Kf1 Nxd3 30. Nxd8 Nxf2 31. Ra5 (31. Rg1 Ng4) 31... Rb2 32. Ra7 Nxh1 33. Nxf7 Kf8 (33... Kg6 34. Nd6 Nf2 {Rather premature. The move} 35. h4 $1 {intending h5 and g4-g5 would cause Black a serious headache.} Kh5 36. Rg7) 34. Nd6 Nf2 35. c4 Ng4 36. Ke1 Nxh2 37. Rf7+ Kg8 38. Rxf6) 23. Ra3 Nc5 $1 24. Ke3 Kf8 25. d4 Ne6 $6 {Black finds it impossible to remain passive for such a long time. With this move he also weakens the e6-pawn, but hopes for counterplay based on the exposed white king.} 26. Rb1 Nc7 27. d5 cxd5 28. cxd5 b5 29. c4 Rb6 (29... bxc4 30. Rc1 Nb5 31. Rxa6 c3 32. a4 $1) 30. cxb5 Nxb5 31. Rab3 Rdb8 32. Kd3 $1 Ke8 {Forced, as White was threatening 33.b4!. But now Black has given up the possibility of counterplay with ...b5, the only decent plan he had at his disposal.} 33. a4 1/2-1/2


