1. e4 c5 2. c3 e6 3. d4 d5 4. exd5 exd5 5. Be3 c4 (5... Qb6 6. dxc5 Qxb2 7. Qb3 Qxb3 (7... Qxa1 8. Bb5+) 8. axb3 Ne7 9. Na3 Bd7 10. Nb5) 6. b3 cxb3 7. axb3 Bd6 8. Bd3 Nc6 (8... Nf6 9. Nd2 O-O 10. h3 Re8 11. Qf3 Qe7 12. Ne2 Ne4 13. O-O $11 {Hakulinen,E-Houtsonen,P/Kuopio 1991} Nd7 14. Nf4 Bxf4 15. Qxf4 Nxc3 16. Rfc1 Ne4 17. Bxe4 dxe4 18. Nc4) 9. Nd2 (9. Nf3 $11 {Anastasian,A-Akopian,V/Yerevan 1989} Nge7 10. O-O Bf5 11. c4 Bb4) 9... Be6 10. Qf3 Nge7 11. Bf4 (11. Ne2 Ng6) 11... Bxf4 12. Qxf4 Ng6 13. Qg3 O-O 14. h4 (14. Ne2 Nce7) 14... Qf6 $2 (14... Nce7 $13 {Benjamin,J-Watson,W/Hastings 1984} 15. h5 Nh8 16. h6 g6 17. Qe5) 15. Ne2 Bf5 16. Bxf5 Qxf5 17. h5 $1 ({The main alternative is} 17. Qf3 Qxf3 (17... Qc2 18. Rc1 (18. h5 Nge7 19. Rc1) 18... Qb2 19. h5 Nge7 {½-½ Hulak,K-Vukic,M/Reggio Emilia 1983.} (19... Rae8 20. Rb1) 20. Qd3) 18. Nxf3 Rfe8 19. Kd2) 17... Nge7 18. Qf3 Rfe8 (18... Qxf3 19. Nxf3 Nf5 20. Nf4 Rfe8+ 21. Kd2 Rad8 22. Rhe1 $13 {Jacobsen,B-Taulbut,S/Silkeborg 1980.}) 19. O-O Qg5 $2 20. Nf4 a5 (20... Rad8 21. b4) (20... Nf5 21. Nxd5 Nh4 22. Qg3) 21. Rfd1 Rad8 22. Nf1 Nf5 23. Rd3 (23. Nh3 Qf6 24. g4 Nfxd4 {is fine for Black.} 25. Qxf6 Ne2+) 23... Nh4 24. Qg3 Qxg3 25. fxg3 Nf5 26. g4 {White has a stable advantage as transformations of the pawn-structure are highly unlikely. This advantage is owed to his superior bishop that controls vital squares, particularly the sensitive a2-g8 diagonal (from d5). Black's main problem is to find an active plan and improve the f8-bishop which lacks targets. It must be noted that the presence of major pieces is particularly important; were we to remove them from the board, the position would be drawn. Thus, this exchange of the major pieces must be Black's plan, even if he has to offer material (a pawn) to achieve it.} Re4 (26... Nfe7 27. Re1 Kf8 28. Rde3) (26... Nh6 {with unclear play, Bareev,E-Beliavsky,A Ubeda 1997.} 27. Ne3) 27. gxf5 (27. Nxd5 Nfxd4) (27. Rf3 Nfxd4 28. cxd4 {The d5-knight is menacingly placed but Black should delay its exchange as much as possible.} Nxd4 {was compulsory.} {Almost forced, as} 29. Kf2 (29. Rf2 Rxf4) 29... Nxf3 30. Kxf3 Rb4 $1 {promises White the advantage.} {Clearly better than} 31. Nd2) 27... Rxf4 28. Ne3 f6 (28... g6 29. g3 Re4 30. Kg2 Rd6 31. hxg6 hxg6 32. fxg6 fxg6) (28... b5 29. g3 Re4 30. Kf2 b4 31. cxb4 Nxb4 32. Rd2 Rde8 33. Ng2 Nc6 34. Ra4 Rb8 35. Rd3) 29. g3 Re4 30. Kf2 Kf7 31. Kf3 Ree8 32. Ng2 b6 (32... g5 33. hxg6+ hxg6 34. fxg6+ Kxg6 35. Nf4+) (32... b5) 33. Nf4 Rd7 34. g4 h6 35. Re3 Rxe3+ 36. Kxe3 b5 {Black has been forced to weaken his king with his last move. The lack of counterplay suits White who, with slow, "mostly pointless" manoeuvres gradually but steadily improves his position.} (36... Ke7 37. Kd3 Kd6 38. Re1 Nd8 39. c4 dxc4+ 40. bxc4) 37. Ne6 Ra7 38. Kd3 a4 39. bxa4 bxa4 40. Ra3 Nb8 41. c4 {White has won a pawn while keeping the rooks on the board. His position is won, unless Black succeeds in exchanging these rooks under favourable circumstances.} dxc4+ 42. Kxc4 Nd7 43. Kb5 Ke7 44. Rxa4 Rb7+ $2 {This eases White's task as it allows the exchange of the important black c5-pawn for the weak white one on e2. As a consequence, White also obtains a passed pawn; this proves decisive. The end of the game is instructive for the slow but sure way in which White secured the point:} (44... Rxa4 45. Kxa4) 45. Kc6 Rb6+ 46. Kc7 (46. Kd5 Rxe6) 46... Rb1 47. Ra6 Rc1+ 48. Rc6 Rg1 49. Kc8 Rb1 50. Kc7 Rb4 51. d5 Rxg4 (51... Nb8 52. d6+ Ke8 53. Nxg7+ (53. Rb6 Rxb6 54. Kxb6 Kd7) 53... Kf7 54. Rb6) 52. d6+ Ke8 53. Kc8 1-0


