1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. g3 Ba6 5. Qa4 Bb7 6. Bg2 $1 c5 7. dxc5 $1 bxc5 8. Nc3 $1 Be7 9. O-O O-O 10. Rd1 Qb6 11. Bf4 d6 12. Rd2 $1 Nc6 13. Qb5 $1 {Threatening 14.e5!.} (13. Bxd6 Bxd6 14. Rxd6 Qxb2 15. Rb1 Qxc3 16. Rxb7 Nd4 17. Qd1 (17. Nxd4 Qe1+ 18. Bf1 Ne4) 17... Nxf3+ 18. Bxf3 Qxc4 19. Qb1 h6 20. Kg2 a5 21. Rxf7 Kxf7 22. Bxa8 Qb4 23. Qxb4 axb4 24. Bb7 c4 25. Rc6 c3 26. Ba6 Ke7 27. Bc4 Kd7 28. Bb5 Ke7 29. Bc4 Kd7 30. Bb5 Ke7) 13... Qc7 (13... Qxb5 14. cxb5 Na5 (14... Nd4 15. Nxd4 Bxg2 16. Nf5 exf5 17. Kxg2) 15. Bxd6 Bxd6 16. Rxd6 Nc4 17. Rdd1 Nxb2 18. Rdc1) 14. Rad1 Rfd8 (14... a6 15. Qa4 Nd4 16. Bg5 (16. Ne1) 16... Bc6 (16... Nxf3+ 17. Bxf3 Bxf3 18. exf3) 17. Qa3 Nb5 18. cxb5 axb5 19. Qb3 b4 20. Bxf6 Bxf6 21. Rxd6 bxc3 22. Rxc6 Qxc6 23. Ne1 Qa6 24. Bxa8 Rxa8 25. bxc3 Qxe2) 15. Qa4 a6 16. Ne1 (16. Ng5 Nd4 17. Nge4 Nxe4 18. Bxe4 f5 (18... h6) 19. Bxb7 Qxb7 20. Rb1 Rab8 21. Qd1 (21. b4) 21... Qc6) 16... h6 17. h3 $1 {What we practically have here is a case of an outpost (the c3-knight) very close to the white camp. White will double rooks on the c-file and at the same time develop an initiative on the flank where the exposed black king resides. At the appropriate moment the outpost will be removed in such a way that Black will be unable to defend against all of White's threats. Simple plan, but the execution is difficult!} (17. Ne4 Nxe4 18. Bxe4 Rab8 19. g4 (19. Bxc6 Bxc6 20. Qc2 e5 21. Be3 a5) (19. b3 e5 20. Be3 Nb4 21. Bxb7 Rxb7 (21... Qxb7 22. Bxc5 dxc5 23. Rxd8+ Rxd8 24. Rxd8+ Bxd8 25. Qe8+ Kh7 26. Qxd8 Nxa2 27. Qd3+) 22. Ng2 Rbb8) 19... Nd4 20. Bxb7 Qxb7 21. Qa3 Qe4 22. Qe3 Qg6 23. Qg3 e5 24. Be3 Rb4 (24... Re8 25. Nd3 f5 26. gxf5 (26. Bxd4 cxd4 27. gxf5 Qxf5) 26... Qxg3+ 27. hxg3 Nxf5) 25. b3 d5 26. Bxd4 exd4 27. Nd3 Rb7 (27... dxc4 28. Nxb4 c3 29. Nd3 cxd2 30. Rxd2 Bd6) 28. cxd5 Rxd5 29. Qf3 Qc6 30. Rc2 Qd7 31. Kh1 (31. Rdc1) 31... Rg5 32. Rdc1 Rc7 33. b4 Rxg4 (33... Qxg4 34. Qxg4 Rxg4 35. bxc5) 34. Ne5) 17... e5 18. Be3 Nd4 19. Bxb7 $1 {A strong move, aiming at the transfer of the knight(s) to the f4-square; from there, in combination with the approach of the white queen (h5) they will be able to create direct threats against the black king.} Qxb7 20. f3 Nh7 $6 (20... Nd7 {would fully justify Black's last move. Since the h1-a8 diagonal will be blocked after ...d5, the white bishop will have no targets on g2.} 21. Nd5 Nb6 22. Nxb6 Qxb6 23. Bf2 Qb7 24. h4 Rab8 25. Kg2 g5 26. hxg5 hxg5 27. g4 Kg7 (27... f5 28. gxf5 Nxf5 29. Qc2) 28. e3) 21. Nd5 Bg5 (21... Nf6 $14 {Marques,V-Comp Shredder 7/Vicente Lopez 2003} 22. Bxd4 cxd4 (22... Nxd5 23. Bxc5) (22... exd4 23. Qc6 Rab8 24. Qxb7 Rxb7 $16 {Tunik,G-Sorokin,M/Sochi 2004.} 25. e4 Nxd5 26. exd5 Rdb8 $16 27. Nd3 $6 Bd8 $18 {Postl,A-Hentunen,A/Izmir 2004} 28. Re2 Kf8 $16 {The automatic} 29. h4) 23. Qc6) 22. Bxg5 $1 Nxg5 $2 23. h4 $1 Nge6 24. e3 Nf5 25. Kf2 $1 (25. Qc2 Ne7 (25... Nxg3 26. Rg2)) 25... Rab8 26. Nd3 $3 {White's great positional superiority creates the basic requirements for tactical combinations!} h5 27. Nc1 g6 (27... Nc7 28. Nc3) 28. Nb3 {Black cannot avoid checkmate.} {This move loses in spectacular fashion, but anyway there was no salvation. Black could not free his position by} Rdc8 (28... Kg7 29. Na5 Qd7 30. Qxd7 Rxd7 $11 {Halkias,S-Postny,E/Mureck 1998.} 31. Nc3 $6) (28... a5 29. Nxa5 Qa7 30. b3 Ra8 $16 {Kulaots,K-Alekseev,E/Moscow 2004} 31. Nc6 Qxa4 $1 32. bxa4 Rf8 33. Nb6 Ra6 {followed by 0-0, fe1 and e4 promises a nice advantage to White.} 34. Rb2) 29. Na5 Qa8 {in view of} 30. g4 (30. e4 Nfd4 31. Qd7 Rd8 $1 32. Qe7) 30... hxg4 (30... Nxh4 31. Rh1 g5 32. Nc6 hxg4 33. Nxb8 $14) 31. fxg4 Nxh4 32. Kg3 g5 (32... Ng5 33. Kxh4 $16 {.} {b)} Ne4 $6 34. Qc2 Nxd2 35. Qxd2 Kg7 36. Qf2 Rh8+ 37. Kg3 f5 38. gxf5 Rh5 ({c)} 38... gxf5 39. Qxf5 $6 Rh6 40. Nc7) 39. f6+ $16 {Grivas,E-Tsouktakos,N/Athens 2004.}) (32... Rb4 33. Qd7 Rd8 $11 {Grivas,E-Ivanchuk,V/Iraklion blz 2004.} 34. Qc6 $1) 33. Nc6 {, winning for White.} (33. Ne7+ Kf8 34. Nxc8 Qf3+ 35. Kh2 Rxc8) 33... Rb7 34. Nce7+ Rxe7 35. Nxe7+ Kf8 36. Nd5 Qb7 37. Rf1 f5 (37... Kg7 38. Rdf2 $1 {), who now faces a multitude of problems: not only must he cater for the c-file, but also for his kingside weaknesses.} {Seems best. Black has also tried: a)} Rf8 $6 39. Qc2) 38. gxf5 $1 Ng7 {is no improvement:} 39. Rdf2 $1 Nh5+ 40. Kg4 Ng7 41. Kxg5 Ngxf5 ({The exchange of queens would significantly relieve Black (} 41... Qf7 $2 42. Qd1) 42. Rxf5+ Nxf5 43. Rxf5+ $1 Kg7 44. Rf6 $1 {.} Rf8 45. Qc2 {intending g1 and h3+} {With the false impression of imminent material gain, thanks to the double threat 23...xa2 and 23...xe3+. The defensive} Rxf6 {was essential.} {This appears strong, but in reality only serves to complicate Black's defensive task, as this knight works as a second outpost for White. Better is} 46. Nxf6 {and ...e7, assigning the knight to the defence of the king.} 1-0


