1. c4 Nf6 2. Nc3 e5 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. g3 Nd4 5. Nxe5 Qe7 6. f4 d6 7. Nd3 Bf5 8. Kf2 (8. e3 Bg4 9. Be2 (9. Qa4+ Bd7 10. Qd1 Bc6 11. Kf2 Bxh1 12. exd4 Be4) 9... Bxe2 (9... Nxe2 10. Nxe2 Qe4 11. Nf2 Qxc4 (11... Qg2) 12. Nxg4 Nxg4 13. Nd4 Nf6 {Not falling into the obvious trap} 14. Qe2 $2 Qxe2+ {when White is simply winning.} 15. Nxe2 {is more accurate, but the text-move does not do any serious harm to Black.} {Although Black wants to stay centralised with his king,} O-O-O {is also enough for the draw.} 16. b3 d5 17. Bb2 Ne4 18. d3 Nd6 19. Kf2 $11) 10. Nxe2 $11 {White cannot make any progress with either} Qe4 11. O-O {or} Nf3+ 12. Rxf3 Qxf3) 8... O-O-O (8... Bxd3 9. exd3 O-O-O 10. Bh3+ Kb8 11. Re1 Ne6 12. f5) (8... Ng4+ 9. Kg1 Bxd3 10. exd3 h5 11. Nd5 {A last try! It must be mentioned that White tortured Black for many moves, which is not such a common practice between Grandmasters. During the game I felt a bit offended but in the end I must confess that it was my mistake that I ended up in a slightly worse endgame!} Qd7 12. h3 (12. b4) 12... Nf6 13. Qe1+ Kd8 14. Qf2 c5 (14... Nxd5 15. Qxd4 $18 Nb4) 15. Ne3 Be7 16. b3 Ne8 17. Nd5 Bf6 18. Nxf6 Nxf6 19. Bb2 $11 Nc6 $2 20. Bg2) 9. Ne1 h5 {(D) } (9... Kb8 10. Bg2 h5 11. e3 Bg4 12. Qa4 Bd7 13. Qd1 (13. Qa3 Nf5 14. Qb3 Ng4+ 15. Kf1 c6 16. Bf3 g5 17. Ng2 Bg7 18. a4 Rde8 19. Qd1 Rhg8 20. Kg1 Nd4 21. exd4 Bxd4+ 22. Ne3 gxf4 23. Ne2 Qf6 24. Nxd4 Qxd4 25. Kg2 Rg6 26. Bxg4 Bxg4 27. Nxg4 hxg4 28. Re1 Rh8 29. Rh1 Qe4+) 13... Bg4 (13... Nf5 14. e4 Nd4 15. Nf3) (13... Nc6)) 10. e3 Ne6 (10... h4 11. Bg2 (11. exd4 hxg3+)) 11. d4 g5 $6 (11... h4 12. Bg2 Bg4 13. Qd3) 12. Nd5 Ne4+ (12... Nxd5 13. cxd5 h4 (13... Ng7 14. fxg5 h4 15. g4 Be4 16. Bg2) 14. dxe6 hxg3+ 15. Kg1 gxh2+ 16. Rxh2 Rxh2 17. Kxh2 fxe6) 13. Kg1 Qd7 (13... Qe8 14. Bd3) 14. Bd3 gxf4 (14... Ng7 15. Qc2 Qe6 16. Nf3) 15. Bxe4 $5 (15. Qc2 N6g5 16. h4 Nh3+ 17. Rxh3 Bxh3 18. Bxe4 fxg3 19. Nf4) 15... Bxe4 $6 16. Nf6 Qc6 17. d5 $1 Qxc4 18. Nxe4 Qxe4 19. dxe6 fxg3 $1 20. hxg3 fxe6 (20... Rg8 21. Qf3 Qxe6 22. Rxh5) 21. Qd4 $1 Qh7 $2 (21... Qxd4 22. exd4 Bg7 23. Nf3) 22. Qxa7 Rg8 23. Qa8+ $1 $16 Kd7 24. Qxb7 $1 (24. Qa4+ Kc8 25. Kf2 Kb8) 24... Rxg3+ 25. Kf2 $2 h4 26. Qb5+ Kc8 27. Qa6+ Kb8 28. Qb5+ Kc8 29. Bd2 (29. Qc4 Be7 30. Qxe6+ {White is a pawn up, but in reality he has no winning chances. The black king will stop the white h-pawn and the black rook will attack the white a-pawn and defend its own pawn.} Kb7 31. Ke2) 29... d5 (29... Qe4 30. Rf1 (30. Qa6+ Kd7 31. Qb5+ Ke7) 30... Bh6) 30. Qa6+ Kb8 (30... Kd7 31. Qa4+) 31. Qb5+ (31. Qa4 Be7 32. Nc2 Rdg8) 31... Kc8 32. Qa6+ Kb8 33. Qb5+ 1/2-1/2


