1. Nf3 Nf6 2. d4 g6 3. c4 Bg7 4. g3 O-O 5. Bg2 d6 6. O-O Nc6 7. Nc3 Bf5 8. b3 Ne4 9. Bb2 Nxc3 10. Bxc3 Be4 {(D) } 11. Rc1 d5 12. e3 a5 13. Bh3 $6 ({"Forced" is} 13. Qe2) 13... e6 $2 ({Black did not understand White's wrong idea. With} 13... Nb4 $1 14. Ra1 Bd3 {he should feel happy.}) 14. Ne1 g5 $5 (14... Qg5 15. Nd3 Ne7 16. Nc5 Qh6 17. Bg4 b6 18. Nxe4 dxe4 {looks nice for White.}) 15. Nd3 b6 16. cxd5 (16. f3 Bg6 17. f4 Be4 $13) 16... Qxd5 17. f3 Bg6 18. Bg2 Qb5 $6 (18... Ne7 19. Ne5 Bxe5 20. dxe5 Rad8 21. Qe1 $14) 19. Nb2 $2 ({It was time for White to benefit from Black's wrong 13th and 18th moves and get a clear advantage with} 19. f4 Qxd3 (19... Bxd3 20. Bxc6 Qxc6 21. Qxd3 Qd5 22. e4 Qd8 23. d5 c5 24. Bxg7 Kxg7 25. d6 $16) 20. Qxd3 Bxd3 21. Rfd1 Be2 22. Rd2 Bb5 23. a4 gxf4 24. gxf4 Rad8 25. axb5 Ne7 26. b4 $16) 19... Nb4 $6 (19... Ne7 {again was correct.}) 20. a4 $1 Qd7 21. Bxb4 axb4 22. Nc4 $2 ({Natural and nice for White was} 22. f4 Rad8 23. Rc6 gxf4 24. gxf4 $16) 22... Rac8 23. Rf2 b5 24. axb5 Qxb5 25. Ra2 Ra8 26. Rca1 Rxa2 27. Rxa2 Qf5 28. Ra5 Qc2 29. Qxc2 Bxc2 30. Nd2 Rd8 $1 {Preparing a future ...e5. Black can be satisfied with his position, although with precise play White can can still maintain the equilibrium.} 31. Rc5 Bg6 32. Kf1 (32. Rxc7 $6 e5 33. e4 exd4 $15) 32... e5 33. d5 Bf8 34. Ra5 c6 35. e4 cxd5 36. Rxd5 (36. exd5 Bd3+ 37. Kf2 Bd6 $15) 36... Rxd5 37. exd5 Bc2 38. Bh3 f5 39. g4 $1 f4 40. Ke1 Bc5 41. Bf1 Bg1 42. h3 Be3 43. Bc4 Kf8 44. Ne4 Bxe4 45. fxe4 Ke7 46. Ke2 Kd6 47. Kf3 Bb6 48. Ke2 Kc5 49. Kd3 h6 50. Ba6 {T: 1.53 - 2.28} 1/2-1/2


