1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 dxc4 5. e3 b5 6. a4 Qa5 $6 7. Bd2 b4 (7... Qb6 8. axb5 cxb5 9. b3 $1 {would also leave White better.}) 8. Na2 e6 9. Bxc4 ({White is now targeting the black b4-pawn. Black will have to spend precious time eliminating one of the white pieces attacking this pawn.} 9. Qc2 $5 Ba6 10. Bxc4 Bxc4 11. Qxc4 Qxa4 12. O-O (12. Bxb4 a5 13. b3 Bxb4+ 14. Ke2 Qb5 15. Nxb4 O-O 16. Ne5 $16 {Heras Cuencas,M-Starostits,I Collado Villalba 2010}) 12... Qb5 13. Rfc1 $16 {Kecskes,G-Shurygin,S Budapest 1994.}) 9... Ne4 (9... Bd6 $5 10. O-O Nbd7 11. Re1 (11. Qe1 $5 Rb8 12. e4 e5 13. Nc1 $16) 11... Rb8 12. Nc1 Ne4 13. Qc2 $14 {Steinskog,A-Kagambi,L Tromsoe 2009.}) 10. O-O Nd7 11. Nc1 $1 {White improves the placement of his knight, setting his sights on the important squares e5, c5 and a5.} Bd6 12. Bd3 $1 (12. Nb3 $6 {is less accurate:} Qh5 $1 13. Bd3 Ng5 $1 {, when Black has a satisfactory game.}) 12... Nxd2 13. Nxd2 Qc7 {This move shows the futility of 6...a5. It is true that Black now 'wins a tempo', but the queen is exposed on the semi-open c-file and will have to move again soon, thus returning the tempo...} 14. f4 $1 c5 $6 ({Black should have resigned himself to an inferior position by} 14... O-O 15. Ncb3 Bb7 16. Rc1 {. In his efforts to achieve equality by drastic means, Black neglects the safety of his king. Naturally, opening up the position can in no way be to his benefit!}) 15. Ncb3 cxd4 ({Practically forced. After} 15... O-O $2 16. Rc1 {White's advantage is decisive.}) 16. Nxd4 Bb7 ({Again after} 16... O-O $2 17. Rc1 Qb8 (17... Qd8 {loses immediately to} 18. Be4) 18. Be4 Bb7 19. Qf3 $1 Bxe4 20. Nxe4 Be7 21. Nc6 Qe8 22. Rc2 $1 {White has a large advantage.}) 17. Rc1 $1 Qd8 ({Other moves would meet the same fate:} 17... Nc5 $2 18. Be4 a6 19. N4b3) (17... Qb8 18. Bb5 $1 {.}) {It is clear that Black needs just one move (...0-0) to solve his problems almost in their entirety. Indeed, his position is free of static weaknesses, thus White is obliged to act immediately if he wishes to benefit from his promising position.} 18. Be4 $1 Bxe4 (18... Rb8 {is no better:} 19. Qf3 $1 Ba8 20. Bxa8 Rxa8 21. Nc6 {.}) 19. Nxe4 Be7 20. Nc6 Qb6 21. Nd6+ Kf8 22. Nxf7 $1 {A conclusive small combination, the direct result of White's positional and tactical superiority.} Kxf7 23. Qxd7 Rhe8 (23... Qxe3+ 24. Kh1 Rhe8 25. Ne5+ Kf8 26. Qxe6 {is also losing.}) 24. f5 $1 {Opening more lines towards the black king.} Qxe3+ ({Of course if} 24... exf5 $2 {White mates with} 25. Rxf5+ Kg6 26. Ne5+ Kh6 27. Rh5+ $1 {.}) 25. Kh1 exf5 26. Rce1 1-0


