1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. g3 c5 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. O-O O-O 6. d5 d6 7. Nc3 Na6 8. e4 Nc7 9. a4 Bg4 10. h3 Bxf3 11. Qxf3 a6 12. Qe2 ({White's other options are not bad either: a)} 12. a5 Nb5 13. Ne2 Nd7 14. Qb3 Qc7 15. Be3 Nd4 16. Nxd4 cxd4 17. Bd2 $14 {Panchenko,A-Barlov,D/Bern 1992}) ({b)} 12. Qd3 Rc8 13. Bd2 c4 14. Qe3 Nd7 15. Nd1 b5 16. axb5 (16. a5 Nc5 17. Bb4 e6 18. Nc3 exd5 19. exd5 Re8 20. Qd2 $14 {Nikolac,J-Mohr,G/Pula 1997}) 16... axb5 17. Ra7 $14) 12... Nd7 13. a5 (13. Bg5 b6 14. Ra2 $5 Rb8 15. Rfa1 Re8 16. Bf1 h6 17. Bf4 Ne5 18. Kg2 $14 {Garcia Gonzales,G-Zapata,A/Havana 1986}) 13... b5 (13... Rb8 14. Nd1 b5 15. axb6 Nxb6 16. Ne3 Qd7 17. h4 $14 {Valerga,D-Needleman,A/Villa Ballester 1997}) 14. axb6 Nxb6 15. Nd1 {White stands better due to his healthier pawn-structure and the bishop-pair.} a5 16. h4 Qd7 17. c4 $2 ({This is not in line with White's idea for handling this particular position. Correct was} 17. h5 a4 18. c3 e6 19. dxe6 $14) 17... e6 $1 18. Bh3 (18. dxe6 Nxe6 19. Bd2 Nd4 20. Qd3 a4 $13) 18... Qe7 19. Qc2 exd5 20. exd5 (20. cxd5 Nb5 21. Bg5 Qb7 22. Ne3 Nd4 23. Qd3 a4 $15) 20... Rfe8 21. Ne3 $6 (21. Bd2 Qe4 $5 22. Qxe4 Rxe4 23. Bxa5 Nxc4 24. Nc3 Bxc3 25. Bxc3 Rxa1 26. Rxa1 Nb6 27. Bg2 Re8 28. Ba5 Rb8 $11) 21... Na6 22. h5 Nb4 23. Qe2 Qe4 $1 24. Ra3 $6 (24. Rd1 Bd4 25. Bg2 Qe5 26. Bf3 a4 $15) 24... a4 25. Bg2 Qb1 $1 $17 26. Qf3 Nc2 $6 (26... Na2 $1) 27. Nxc2 Qxc2 28. b3 axb3 29. Rxb3 Nxc4 30. Bf4 Ne5 31. Bxe5 Rxe5 32. hxg6 hxg6 $17 {White is lost as he has not even counterplay for his minus pawn. One must also take in account the difference in power of the bishops: White's is doing nothing; Black's is destined to proceed against the valuable f2-pawn.} 33. Rb6 Rd8 34. Rc6 Re7 35. Qa3 Bd4 36. Qa5 Rde8 $1 37. Rxd6 Re1 38. Qa6 Kg7 39. Kh2 Rh8+ 40. Bh3 Re5 41. g4 Qc3 42. f3 Qb2+ 43. Kg3 Re2 0-1


