1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. g3 Bg7 4. Bg2 O-O 5. O-O d6 6. c4 Nc6 7. d5 Na5 8. Nfd2 {(D) } c6 $5 {A lot of games have been played with 8...c5 but I am quite fond of the alternative c-pawn move.} 9. Nc3 ({The main alternative is} 9. Na3 cxd5 (9... c5 10. Nc2 e5 11. a3 Qc7 12. e4 Bh6 13. Ne3 Bxe3 14. fxe3 Ne8 15. b3 b6 16. Bb2 Bd7 $13 {Maiorov,N-Zhigalko,A/Minsk 2005}) 10. cxd5 e6 11. dxe6 (11. e4 exd5 12. exd5 Bg4 13. Bf3 Bxf3 14. Qxf3 Nd7 15. Rb1 b6 16. b4 Nb7 {½-½ Forintos,G-Balashov,Y/Skopje 1970}) 11... Bxe6 12. Nb3 Nxb3 (12... Nc6 13. Nb5 d5 14. Be3 Ng4 15. Bc5 Re8 16. N5d4 Nge5 17. Nxe6 fxe6 18. e4 $14 {Burmakin,V-Kurenkov,N/Pardubice 2003}) 13. axb3 Qd7 14. Nc4 Rfd8 15. Be3 Bh3 $11 {Kovaljov,D-Blehm,P/Hallsberg 1999}) 9... Ng4 $5 ({An interesting idea, although Black should feel also fine after the more usual} 9... cxd5 10. cxd5 Bd7 11. e4 Rc8 12. Qe2 Qb6 13. Re1 Ng4 {Fuchs,A-Lanka,Z/Saarlouis 2003}) 10. Qc2 Ne5 (10... cxd5 11. cxd5 Bf5 12. Nde4 Rc8 {Van Parreren,H-Zude,E/Munich 1992 and}) (10... Bf5 11. e4 Bd7 12. b3 cxd5 13. exd5 b5 14. Bb2 bxc4 15. bxc4 Rb8 {Horvath,A-Werner,D/Budapest 2003, are fine options for Black.}) 11. b3 cxd5 12. cxd5 {(D) } b5 $5 (12... Bd7 13. Bb2 b5 14. Rac1 Qb6 $13 {Gross,G-Zude,E/Germany 1991}) 13. Bb2 $6 ({I think White is forced to enter the following long variation:} 13. Nxb5 Nd3 14. Rb1 Nb4 15. Qc7 a6 16. Qxd8 Rxd8 17. Na3 Nxa2 18. b4 Nb7 19. Bb2 Nc3 20. Bxc3 Bxc3 21. Nac4 a5 22. bxa5 Nxa5 23. Nb6 Rb8 24. Nxc8 Rdxc8 25. Rxb8 Rxb8 26. Ne4 Bg7 $11) 13... b4 14. Nb5 Bf5 $1 15. Ne4 (15. e4 Bd7 16. Nd4 Rc8 17. Qb1 Qb6 $15) 15... Rc8 16. Qd2 $6 (16. Qb1 Qb6 17. Nd4 Nf3+ (17... Bd7 $5 18. Rd1 Nb7) 18. Nxf3 Bxe4 19. Qxe4 Bxb2 20. Rab1 Bf6 21. Rfc1 Rc3 $15 {was forced.}) 16... Qb6 $1 17. Nd4 Bxe4 18. Bxe4 Nec4 $1 19. bxc4 Nxc4 20. Qc2 Bxd4 21. Bxd4 Qxd4 22. Qd3 Qxd3 23. Bxd3 Nb6 24. Rfb1 a5 25. a3 Nxd5 26. axb4 Nxb4 27. Rxa5 Nxd3 28. exd3 Rb8 29. Rc1 Rfc8 30. Rxc8+ Rxc8 31. Kf1 {If White had her e-pawn on e2 instead of d3, Black would have, at some point, to transpose to a 4:3 ending with a passed d-pawn (see the relevant chapter). Now Black is unable to obtain a passed pawn, but he can instead attack the weak white d-pawn.} Rc2 32. Ke1 Kg7 33. h4 Kf6 34. Rb5 h5 35. Ra5 Rc5 36. Ra4 g5 {Black wishes to cross over to d4 with his king and attack the d-pawn. However, the absence of his king from the kingside will leave his pawns there exposed, thus he decides to exchange them.} 37. hxg5+ Kxg5 38. Ke2 Re5+ 39. Kd2 Rf5 40. Ke3 Re5+ 41. Kd2 Re6 42. Rb4 f5 43. Ra4 Rf6 44. Ke3 Rf8 45. Ra7 Kf6 46. Rb7 Rg8 47. Rb4 Rg4 48. Rb8 h4 49. gxh4 Rxh4 {The g- and h-pawns have been exchanged and thus White's potential counterplay is zero.} 50. Rf8+ Ke5 51. Rf7 e6 52. Re7 Ra4 53. Rh7 f4+ 54. Kf3 Kd5 55. Rh6 e5 56. Ke2 Ra2+ $1 57. Ke1 {The restriction of the white king on the 1st rank was forced (57.f3? d2).} Ra6 58. Rf6 Kd4 59. Kd2 Ra2+ 60. Ke1 d5 61. Rd6 Ra3 62. Ke2 Rxd3 ({Black could also win with} 62... f3+ 63. Kxf3 Rxd3+ 64. Ke2 e4 {, but the pawn ending he opts for is also sufficient.}) 63. Rxd5+ Kxd5 64. Kxd3 e4+ 65. Kc3 Kc5 66. Kc2 Kc4 67. Kd2 Kd4 68. Kc2 e3 69. Kd1 $1 Kd3 70. Ke1 f3 ({The alternative path is} 70... e2 71. f3 Kc2 72. Kxe2 Kc3 {. Black will win the white f-pawn and, as his own pawn has crossed its 4th rank, the opposition will prove useless for White.}) 71. Kf1 e2+ $1 72. Ke1 Ke4 $1 {(And Black wins by transferring his king to g1 (...f4-g4-h3-g2-g1). If we were to move the entire setup one square to the right, then the position would be drawn, as the black king would be unable to penetrate via the kingside. An alternative win after} 73. Kd2 {is} Kd5 74. Ke1 Kd4 75. Kd2 e1=Q+ 76. Kxe1 Kc3 77. Kd1 Kd3 78. Ke1 Kc2 79. Kf1 Kd2 80. Kg1 Ke2 81. Kh2 Kxf2 {0-1 (81) Shumiakina,T (2350)-Grivas,E (2460) Cappelle la Grande 1995 CBM 122 [Grivas,Efstratios] ).} 0-1


