1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nbd2 Bf5 5. Nh4 Be4 6. f3 Bg6 7. Qb3 Qc7 8. e3 (8. e4 {leads to nowhere:} dxe4 9. Nxg6 hxg6 10. Nxe4 Nxe4 11. fxe4 e5 (11... Rxh2 $2 12. Rxh2 Qxh2 13. Qxb7 $18) 12. d5 Nd7 $13 {as White has obtained a passed pawn but Black controls the dark squares.}) ({Also satisfactory for Black is} 8. cxd5 cxd5 9. Nxg6 hxg6 10. e3 Nc6 11. f4 e6 {.}) 8... e6 9. Nxg6 ({An untested line is} 9. Be2 Nbd7 10. g4 {but probably this is too 'much' for White.}) 9... hxg6 10. Bd3 Nbd7 ({A bit passive, but still OK for Black. The 'correct' follow-up is} 10... c5 $1 {- see game Grivas,E-Rusev,K Bursa 2009.}) 11. f4 $1 g5 $1 ({And now this is an active continuation!} 11... O-O-O $6 12. Nf3 Ne4 13. cxd5 cxd5 (13... exd5 $6 14. Bxe4 dxe4 15. Ng5 $16) 14. O-O Ndf6 15. Bd2 {allows White to feel slightly better.}) 12. fxg5 Ng4 13. Nf3 O-O-O ({Black could safely play} 13... Nxh2 14. Nxh2 Rxh2 15. Rxh2 Qxh2 16. Qxb7 Rb8 17. Qxc6 Bb4+ 18. Kf2 Qh4+ 19. Kg1 Be1 $1 {which leads to a draw by perpetual check!}) 14. Bd2 Nxh2 15. O-O-O {White should again 'feel' happy, as his bishop pair can be proven strong in the long run, as his king is now safe. But of course there is a long way to go before this can be a reality...} Be7 16. g6 (16. Nxh2 Rxh2 17. Rxh2 Qxh2 18. Rf1 Qxg2 19. Rxf7 Qxg5 20. cxd5 exd5 21. Bf5 g6 22. Be6 Qh4 $1 23. Qd3 Kb8 {is just drawish.}) 16... f5 $1 ({Rightly asking to create a 'correct' environment for his knight, by blocking the centre. The main alternative is} 16... Nxf3 $6 17. Rxh8 $1 (17. gxf3 Rxh1 18. Rxh1 fxg6 19. Bxg6 Qg3 20. Bh5 Rh8 $13) 17... Rxh8 18. gxf3 fxg6 19. Bxg6 Qg3 20. Bf7 $14 {.}) 17. cxd5 $1 cxd5+ 18. Kb1 Kb8 ({The bishop pair can come into force after} 18... Nxf3 $6 19. gxf3 Rxh1 20. Rxh1 Kb8 21. e4 $14 {.}) 19. Nxh2 ({Probably the best try. Black should feel fine after} 19. Qc2 Qxc2+ (19... Nxf3 $6 20. Qxc7+ Kxc7 21. gxf3 Bd6 22. e4 $14) 20. Kxc2 Ng4 {or}) (19. Bb4 Bxb4 20. Qxb4 Nxf3 21. gxf3 Nf6 22. Rxh8 Rxh8 23. Rc1 Qd8 {.}) 19... Rxh2 20. Ba5 $1 b6 $2 ({Weakening too much the light squares around the black king. Black should have opted for} 20... Nb6 $1 21. Bxb6 axb6 22. Rxh2 Qxh2 23. Qxb6 Rd6 $1 24. Qc5 Qh4 $1 {with about equal chances.} (24... Qxg2 $2 25. Rc1 $16)) 21. Ba6 $2 ({White still retains a certain advantage after the text move, but} 21. Rxh2 $1 Qxh2 22. Ba6 Qd6 (22... Qxg2 23. Rc1 Qe4+ 24. Ka1 Bd6 25. Qb5 $18) 23. Qb5 {planning c1-c6 x b6, was curtains.}) 21... Rxh1 ({Not of course} 21... Ka8 $2 22. Rxh2 Qxh2 23. Qa4 $18 {.}) 22. Rxh1 Qd6 $2 ({Black had to go straight for} 22... Ka8 23. Rc1 {which transposes.}) 23. Rc1 $2 (23. Qb5 $1 {was again curtains - see the note to White's 21st move.}) 23... Ka8 $1 {Finally!} 24. Be1 Nb8 25. Bb5 {White's bishop pair can operate strongly if some central pawns are exchanged, so he should focus on that plan. On the other hand Black cannot do much more than stay put and watch the procedures.} Kb7 26. Qc2 ({Also possible was} 26. g4 fxg4 (26... f4 $6 27. a3 $1 $16) 27. Qd1 a6 28. Ba4 b5 29. Bb3 Nd7 (29... g3 30. Qg4) 30. Qxg4 Nf6 31. Qg2 Qd7 32. Bg3 Bd6 33. Bh4 Be7 34. Rf1 $14 {but White is in no hurry!}) 26... a6 27. Be2 Qd7 28. g4 $1 fxg4 (28... Rc8 $6 29. Qxc8+ Qxc8 30. Rxc8 Kxc8 31. gxf5 exf5 32. Bd3 $18 {.}) 29. Bxg4 Bg5 30. Bg3 $1 (30. Qc3 {was also fine, but White found a tactical shot.}) 30... Nc6 ({Or} 30... Bxe3 $6 31. Rf1 $1 Rc8 32. Qd3 Bh6 33. a3 $1 (33. Rf7 $2 Rc1#) 33... Qe8 34. Rf7+ Nd7 35. Bh4 $1 $18 {.}) 31. Qf2 Bf6 32. Qf4 $1 {The bishop pair cooperates beautifully with the major pieces, giving to its owner a decisive advantage in the long run.} Rc8 (32... Re8 33. a3 a5 34. Be2 $1 Rc8 35. Bb5 $16 {.}) 33. a3 a5 34. Bh3 $1 {Preparing g4 and e4.} Ne7 $6 ({Maybe a bit 'better' was} 34... Nd8 35. Rxc8 Qxc8 36. e4 $1 dxe4 37. Bg2 $1 $16 {.}) 35. Rxc8 Qxc8 36. Qd6 $1 {White wins!} Qc4 37. Qb8+ Ka6 $6 ({Losing on the spot, but even after the 'correct'} 37... Kc6 38. Qc7+ Kb5 39. Qxc4+ $1 dxc4 (39... Kxc4 40. Kc2 $1 Kb5 (40... a4 $2 41. Bf1#) 41. Bxe6 $18) 40. Bxe6 Nxg6 41. Kc2 $1 Bh4 42. Bh2 (42. Bxh4 Nxh4 43. Kc3 $18) 42... Nf8 43. Bf7 Nh7 44. Be8+ Ka6 45. a4 {White wins.}) 38. Bc7 (38. Bc7 {And Black resigned due to} Qd3+ (38... Qc6 39. Bf1+ b5 40. Bxb5+ Qxb5 41. Qa8#) 39. Ka1 Qd1+ 40. Ka2 {. An instructive example of the power of the bishop pair.}) 1-0


