1. c4 Nf6 2. Nc3 d5 3. cxd5 Nxd5 4. Nf3 g6 5. Qa4+ $5 c6 $5 6. Qd4 (6. Nxd5 {seems to be a simpler and more economical choice, my preference being for White because of his central pawn majority.}) 6... f6 7. e4 e5 $1 (7... Nxc3 $2 8. Qxc3 $1 e5 {is difficult for Black after} 9. Bc4 {because he'll have trouble getting his king to safety and meanwhile White can open it up with d2-d4.}) 8. Nxe5 $5 Nxc3 $1 {The only good reply.} ({Both} 8... Qe7 9. Nxd5 cxd5 (9... fxe5 10. Nxe7 exd4 11. Nxc8 Nd7 12. Nxa7 Rxa7 13. a3) 10. Bb5+ Nd7 11. Nxd7 Bxd7 12. Qxd5) ({and} 8... Nb4 9. Qxd8+ Kxd8 10. Nf7+ Ke8 11. Nxh8 Nc2+ 12. Kd1 Nxa1 13. b3 Bg7 (13... Be6 14. Bc4) 14. Nxg6 hxg6 15. Bb2 Nxb3 16. axb3 {are good for White.}) 9. Qxc3 Qe7 10. Nf3 $1 Qxe4+ 11. Be2 ({Rybka's novelty is} 11. Kd1 $5 {but is it really that great? I think Black can defend himself with} Nd7 12. Bc4 Kd8 $1 {when} 13. Re1 Qg4 14. Be6 $6 (14. g3 Kc7 {is fine for Black}) 14... Qxg2 15. d4 Bd6 {is unconvincing.}) 11... Bg7 $2 ({Black should play} 11... Nd7 $1 {when} 12. O-O Bb4 13. Qe3 (13. Qb3 {can be answered by} Nc5 14. Qd1 Nd3) 13... Qxe3 14. dxe3 Nb6 15. Rd1 Be6 16. a3 Be7 17. Nd4 Bc4 18. Bxc4 Nxc4 19. b3 Nb6 20. e4 Kf7 21. Be3 {was just a tiny bit better for White in Franco Ocampos, Z-Krupkova, P/Montecatini Terme 1998.}) ({On the other hand} 11... Be7 $2 {is strongly met by} 12. O-O $1 {when} Qxe2 13. Re1 Qb5 14. Qxf6 {would win on the spot.}) 12. O-O $1 O-O 13. Re1 ({After} 13. Bc4+ Kh8 14. Re1 {Black can hang on with} Qf4 $1 15. d4 Qd6 {.}) 13... Kh8 14. d4 Nd7 15. Bc4 Qf5 $6 (15... Qg4 {was another try, though White can then play} 16. b3 {followed by 17.Ba3 which seems to win the exchange.}) 16. Be6 Qb5 17. a4 $1 Qb6 18. Bf4 $6 (18. Nh4 $1 {threatening 19.Nxg6+ would have been very strong, for example} Ne5 19. Rxe5 fxe5 20. Nxg6+ hxg6 21. Qh3+ {leads to mate.}) 18... Qd8 19. a5 ({Once again missing the deadly} 19. Nh4 $1 {threatening 20. Nxg6+.}) 19... Ne5 (19... Re8 {might have been a bit tougher but even so White's lead in development gives him a winning advantage. A sample line is} 20. Ba2 Rxe1+ 21. Rxe1 Nf8 22. Qb4 b6 23. Qc4 $18 {threatening mate on g8.}) 20. Nxe5 Bxe6 ({Or} 20... fxe5 21. Bxe5 Bxe5 (21... Bxe6 22. Bxg7+ Kxg7 23. Rxe6) 22. Rxe5 Qf6 23. Qe3 $18 {with a good pawn up.}) 21. Nxg6+ hxg6 22. Rxe6 Re8 (22... Qd7 23. Rd6 {would not have helped Black much.}) 23. a6 $1 Rxe6 24. Qh3+ 1-0



